<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-SecondOldest     08-03 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Second Oldest,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman in Guinness Book to Celebrate 112th Birthday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The year Birdie May Vogt was born, Alexander Graham
Bell patented the telephone, Rutherford B. Hayes became president,
and Gen. George Custer had his last stand at the Little Big Horn.
   The year was 1876.
   Today, Ms. Vogt was celebrating her 112th birthday.
   Born in Akron, Ohio, on Aug. 3, 1876, her longevity has earned
Ms. Vogt a listing in the 1989 edition of the Guinness Book of
World Records due out in October as the world's oldest person,
according to Guinness Assistant Editor Cyd Smith.
   But the subsequent discovery by Guinness officials of Madame
Calment, born in Arles, France, Feb. 21, 1875, makes Ms. Vogt the
world's second-oldest known inhabitant, Smith said.
   Guinness editors plan to correct the error in an updated section
at the back of the edition, Smith added.
   Ms. Vogt planned to celebrate her birthday with balloons and a
cake at the East Ridge Retirement Village in Cutler Ridge, her home
for the past quarter century.
   ``We're very proud of her,'' said Bonnie Barton, director of
activities at the village's medical center.
   Despite eyesight and hearing problems, Ms. Vogt remains alert
and healthy, Ms. Barton said.
   Ms. Barton said Ms. Vogt is incredibly receptive toward babies.
   ``Her whole face just brightens right up when she sees
children,'' Ms. Barton said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
