<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BritishIntellectuals     08-03 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-British Intellectuals,0730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcherism Runs Into Opposition From Intelligentsia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated`Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As novelist John Mortimer would reflect, the way
some people reacted, ``we might have been plotting to pinch the
Crown Jewels'' by gathering to grouse about Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's policies.
   All the author of ``Paradise Postponed'' and the ``Rumpole'' TV
series did was attend a soiree in June at the home of Lady Antonia
Fraser, the historian. The liberal literary set assembled there for
a discussion of how to counter Mrs. Thatcher's plans to bury
British socialism.
   The reactions of some right-wing commentators illustrate the
bilious tenor of political debate in this 10th year of the Thatcher
revolution.
   Intellectuals have never enjoyed the esteem in Britain that
their peers are accorded in France and Germany.
   ``British intellectuals tend to disguise themselves,'' said
Patrick Bateson, provost of King's College, Cambridge.
   In this case, having poked their heads above ground at the
Fraser dinner, they have come in for attacks ranging from the snide
through the derisive to the downright belligerent.
   Common themes are these: writers know nothing of politics, they
have become richer in the Thatcher years, they are ``champagne
socialists'' out of touch with the masses they claim to defend, and
other regimes would put them in jail.
   The Sunday Telegraph headlined ``The Betrayal of the
Intellectuals'' and its editor, Peregrine Worsthorne, got even more
personal.
   Writing in the conservative weekly Spectator, Worsthorne
questioned the propriety of Lady Antonia holding her do in the room
once used for conservative gatherings by her first husband, the
late Sir Hugh Fraser, whom she left for playwright Harold Pinter.
   Writer Paul Bailey argued in the centrist Independent newspaper
that Lady Antonia and Co. had been enriched by Mrs. Thatcher's tax
cuts. He found ``comic appeal'' in their concern for the poor.
   D.J. Taylor wrote in the conservative Evening Standard that it
was ``an anti-Thatcherite cabal'' and ``a rather dangerous joke,''
then shot himself in the foot by deriding the group for lacking
such high-caliber writers such as Ian McEwan and Salman Rushdie _
both of whom were indeed present.
   Lady Antonia's dinner was not the only stirring of organized
intellectual dissent. Center-left academics formed a think tank
last month devoted to challenging Thatcherite doctrine.
   ``The right have managed to persuade the public of a range of
myths that need to be exploded,'' said Baroness Tessa Blackstone,
head of the socialist-oriented Birkbeck College in London and of
the new Institute for Policy Research.
   Among the ``myths'' she named at a news conference: the free
market is sacrosanct, inequality is essential to a prosperous
society, all nationalized industry is bad, and ``to manifest social
concern is to be wet,'' _ Mrs. Thatcher's term for bleeding-heart
liberalism.
   The catalyst of the intellectual ferment was Mrs. Thatcher's
third successive election victory in June 1987, unprecedented in
Britain's modern times.
   She considers it a mandate to implement her most radical reforms
and has launched a program ranging from revamping the state health,
education and welfare systems to curbing promotion of homosexuality.
   In rolling back the liberal legacy of the 1960s, Mrs. Thatcher
seems to be borrowing an old slogan of her friend Ronald Reagan:
``You ain't seen nothin' yet.''
   Lady Antonia said all this motivated her to invite Mortimer,
novelist Margaret Drabble, feminist guru Germaine Greer and other
eminent figures to dinner.
   ``We were talking about the way society was going,'' she told
the conservative Sunday Times, ``Clause 28 (on homosexuality), the
cuts in welfare ... people sleeping rough in the streets. ... We
said, so many people must be talking like this and can we do
anything? If we try, at least we can tell our grandchildren that we
tried.''
   Rushdie, author of ``Midnight's Children,'' called it ``our
first, hesitant efforts to join forces against the present
regime.'' In an article for the liberal weekly Observer, he added:
``I'm damned if I'll be apologetic.''
   Such intellectual stirrings are but a pinprick for Mrs. Thatcher
at this stage because the economy is strong and unemployment is
falling. A Sunday Times poll indicated 74 percent of Britons are at
least fairly satisfied with their lot and 62 percent support her
economic policies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
