<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NavajoSlayings     08-03 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navajo Slayings,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Convicts 2, Deadlocks On 3rd Defendant In Police Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury Tuesday convicted two men
and deadlocked in the case of a third man accused in the December
shooting and burning deaths of two Navajo tribal police officers.
   The jury found Thomas Cly, 22, and Vinton Bedoni, 31, guilty of
two counts of first-degree murder each. The two also were convicted
of aiding and abetting and use of a firearm in a crime.
   The jury was ordered back to the jury room after reading
verdicts on Cly and Bedoni, but was unable to reach a verdict on
the third defendant, Ben Atene Jr., 24. U.S. District Judge J.
Thomas Greene declared a mistrial and ordered Atene returned to the
Salt Lake County Jail, where he is being held without bail.
   Prosecutors said they would not dismiss charges against Atene in
the slayings of officers Roy Lee Stanley and Andy Begay, whose
charred bodies were found inside a burned-out police truck in a
remote southern Utah canyon on Dec. 5.
   During the trial, prosecution witnesses testified that the
officers were shot as they tried to break up a bonfire drinking
party on the night of Dec. 4. Alcohol is prohibited on the Navajo
Indian Reservation.
   When the verdicts were read to a silent courtroom by the court
clerk, Cly and Bedoni remained expressionless, but Cly looked
toward the ceiling for a long moment.
   Greene scheduled sentencing for Cly and Bedoni on Oct. 3. They
face maximum possible sentences of life in prison.
   Attorney Ed Brass said he was certain Cly would appeal. Defense
attorney Robert VanSciver said he planned to discuss the
possibility with his client, Bedoni.
   ``I'm disappointed, it was a hard case, we struggled,''
VanSciver said. ``I think we got a fair trial, but the chips will
fall where they may.''
   Brass insisted that Cly is innocent.
   ``That's not a criticism of the jury. They obviously saw it
differently,'' he said.
   During the trial, government and defense witnesses offered
conflicting accounts of where the defendants were the night the
officers were killed. Five prosecution witnesses placed the trio at
the bonfire scene, but defense witnesses and the defendants said
they were elsewhere.
   In closing arguments, prosecutors told jurors their witnesses
had no reason to lie. Defense attorneys said the prosecution's case
was based on lies that were made up in response to authorities
threats of perjury charges or to collect a $10,000 reward.
   The 12-member jury got the case Thursday and reached its
verdicts on the fifth day of deliberations.
</TEXT>
