<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CarrierFire 1stLd-Writethru a0848 08-03 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carrier Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0848,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>18 Sailors Injured In Fire About USS Constellation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with all injuries described as minor,
spokesman unsure when fire might be controlled, FAA imposing 5-mile
air space restriction around ship, background on training mission.
ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SHARON L. JONES</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen sailors were injured Tuesday battling
a fire that raged in an engine room of the USS Constellation as the
aircraft carrier steamed out to sea for a training mission, Navy
officials said.
   Fourteen sailors were evacuated to Balboa Navy Hospital for
treatment, said Navy spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Bob Pritchard. He said
most of the injuries were smoke-related or burns and all were minor.
   Information from the burning aircraft carrier remained sketchy
Tuesday night, said Pritchard. He said he didn't know how serious
the blaze was or when it might be controlled.
   The entire crew of about 3,000 was probably engaged in the
firefighting efforts, the spokesman said.
   ``This is an all-hands evolution,'' he said.
   The fire in one of the Constellation's four engine rooms started
about 12:10 p.m., when the ship was about four miles off the coast
of San Diego.
   ``They contained the fire within minutes. However, the fire did
reflash'' in mid-afternoon, Pritchard said.
   Initial reports indicated the fire had been contained within the
engine room, he said.
   ``The ship is currently under way with her own power, heading
away from the coast,'' Pritchard said. ``We don't have an exact
position for her.''
   Asked if the ship would return to port, Pritchard said, ``It's
too early to tell. That's going to have to wait until we get an
exact assessment of damage. The No. 1 concern right now is to get
the fire out.''
   In addition to water, firefighters were using foam and powder
fire smothering systems.
   The Federal Aviation Administration imposed a 5-mile air space
restriction around the burning ship about 4:10 p.m, Pritchard said.
   The Constellation, which is conventionally powered, was heading
out for a session in which replacement pilots qualify to fly
various types of aircraft aboard a ship, he said.
   The qualification tests are regularly conducted off the Southern
California coast, he said.
</TEXT>
