<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     08-03 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC's Oldies Win Another Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mark Harmon was the most-watched man on
television last week, in a four-year-old miniseries that led NBC to
another weekly victory in the A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings.
   Harmon starred in ``Deliberate Stranger,'' a two-part miniseries
about alleged serial killer Ted Bundy. The 18.8 rating on the July
25 episode was the week's highest.
   The first part of ``Deliberate Stranger'' had been the No. 5
show the previous week, with a rating of 14.3.
   NBC said the two parts averaged a 29 percent share of the
viewing audience, the best performance for an NBC miniseries repeat
since ``V'' had the same share figure in 1984.
   Each rating point represents the nation's 886,000 homes with
television. The share is the portion of sets in use in a given time
period.
   In its first run during the May sweeps in 1986, ``Deliberate
Stranger'' had a rating of 18.6 for part one and 21.7 for part two.
   The rest of last week's top 10 were: ``The Cosby Show'' and its
spinoff ``Different World'' tied for second with a 17.6 rating,
``Night Court'' at 17.2, ``Golden Girls'' 17.1, ``Cheers'' 17.0,
``Hunter'' 15.6, ``L.A. Law'' 15.3, ``Miss Teen USA'' 15.1 and
``Amen'' 14.5.
   Except for ``Miss Teen USA,'' which was live on CBS, all of the
top shows were NBC reruns. ABC's highest-rated show was ``Who's the
Boss?,'' which placed 15th.
   NBC won the week with an average rating of 12.2, followed CBS's
9.5 and ABC's 8.5. For the 45 weeks of the season, NBC's average is
14.9 followed by CBS's 12.5 and ABC's 12.4.
   CBS had the top-ranked evening news broadcast for last week with
an 8.9 rating. NBC and ABC tied at 8.7.
</TEXT>
