<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-PlantClosing-Glance     08-03 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Plant Closing-Glance,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prospective New Plant-Closing Law At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Plant Closing Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are major provisions of the
bill providing for 60 days' advance notice of plant closings and
mass layoffs. Congress passed the measure last month and President
Reagan announced Tuesday he will allow it to become law without his
signature.
   The prospective law:
   _Will take effect Thursday although companies will not have to
start providing the notices until Feb. 4, 1989, six months after
enactment. Written notices have to be provided to affected workers
individually and local government officials. Meantime, the Labor
Department is instructed to issue regulations for enforcing the
statute.
   _Affects only companies with 100 or more full-time workers at
any single site of employment.
   _In instances of plant closings, which include shutdowns of any
single product line or operation within a plant, requires 60 days'
advance notice if 50 or more workers lose their jobs.
   _In cases of layoffs, requires notice only if one-third of a
plant's work force or at least 500 people, whichever is less, are
being laid off. For example, a company with 750 employees at a
particular location laying off 200 of them would not have to
provide the notices. But if it laid off more than 250, it would. So
would a plant with 2,500 employees that lays off 550 of them, even
though the reduction does not total one-third of its work force.
   _Exempts companies from providing the full 60 days' notice if
the plant closing or layoff was caused by ``not reasonably
foreseeable circumstances'' such as sudden cancellation of a
government contract, floods or droughts.
   _Exempts companies from providing advance notice if the notices
would have precluded them from obtaining capital or new business
that would have enabled them to avoid or postpone the plant closing
or layoffs.
   _There is a ``presumptive requirement'' to provide notices if
companies are involved in bankruptcy court reorganizations or
situations where creditors are trying to seize their assets. Only
by showing the unforeseen circumstances would they be exempted.
   _Authorizes the Labor Department to require violators to award
up to 60 days' back pay and benefits to any worker not given proper
notice.
   _Authorizes federal judges to levy fines of up to $500 per day
for each of the 60 days that advance notice was not provided, or up
to $30,000, which is to be paid affected communities.
   The bill's sponsors said it would have covered about 800,000
workers in each of the past two years who were laid off without
warning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
