<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0151EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EmergencySpending     08-03 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Emergency Spending,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel OKs $421 Million Supplemental Spending Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Senate may consider bill today; top prospects uncertain</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $421 million emergency spending bill is
awaiting approval by the Senate, but the measure seems to be
turning into a pawn in the election-year struggle over aid to the
Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   The Senate Appropriations Committee sent the supplemental
spending bill for fiscal 1988 to the full Senate on Tuesday by a
voice vote without objections.
   The Senate was expected to vote on the measure as early as
today. However, maneuvering between Democrats and Republicans over
Contra aid made the timetable unclear.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., has proposed a $47
million Contra aid package and has said he wants to attach it to
the supplemental spending measure.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., said he would not
bring up the supplemental package if Dole will introduce a Contra
aid amendment. Democrats are trying to write a milder formula for
Contra aid, which they want to insert into a Pentagon
appropriations bill.
   The supplemental, which would cover spending in the fiscal year
that ends Sept. 30, would provide $421 million in new spending and
allow more than $100 million to be transferred among the budgets of
various agencies.
   Supplemental spending for this year is supposed to be approved
only for ``dire emergencies,'' according to the budget summit
agreement of last fall between President Reagan and congressional
leaders.
   Several senators said that to honor that pact, they would
withhold requests for additional spending. This rare behavior
inspired Sen. J. Bennett Johnston, D-La., a senior member of the
committee, to call the measure ``lean, mean and urgent.''
   The largest slice of the legislation is $297 million for the
Veterans Administration, which needs more money because some of the
benefits it pays are being adjusted for inflation and because the
agency's caseload has been larger than expected.
   The bill includes $60 million for the Coast Guard, which says it
needs the money to keep its ships and planes on patrol; $55.4
million for the Justice Department to cover expenses incurred
during last year's riots by Mariel Cuban detainees at federal
prisons; and $55 million for the Agriculture Department, which has
seen its spending go up as a result of the drought.
   The measure would provide $22.6 million for FBI agents to
observe Soviet inspectors monitoring American compliance with the
nuclear weapons treaty the two nations have signed.
   The legislation also would transfer an estimated $49 million to
trade programs for workers who lose their jobs because of imports,
and about $43 million to the program that dispenses benefits to
victims of black lung disease.
   On an 8-7 vote, committee members voted to strip a provision
that would have freed $44 million the government has withheld from
the United Nations. The United States has been holding back
portions of its annual contributions to the international agency,
arguing that the United Nations needs to make management reforms.
   The House approved a $189.1 million version of the bill July 27.
It contains none of the veterans' assistance. House leaders have
said they will try to pass a second bill containing less urgent
spending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
