<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Gilbert'sDefense 1stLd-Writethru a0687 08-03 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gilbert's Defense, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0687,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Mercy Killer' Asks For New Trial, Claims Movie Deal Harmed
Defense</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS in 3rd graf that reporters sted judge asked
question. Inserts 3 grafs after 16th graf `For me' to UPDATE with
later testimony.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 79-year-old man convicted of
murdering his ailing wife in what he called a mercy killing asked
for a new trial Tuesday, saying his lawyer was compromised by
emotions surrounding the case and negotiations for a movie deal.
   Roswell Gilbert, represented by a new attorney, made a rare
appearance in court during a hearing before Broward Circuit Judge
Thomas Coker.
   Reporters asked what Gilbert wanted to accomplish during the
two-day hearing.
   ``Something that will help me terminate this nightmare, I
guess,'' he replied.
   Gilbert was convicted of first-degree murder in the March 1985
shooting death of Emily Gilbert, his wife of 51 years, at their
seaside condominium. The retired electronics engineer said he shot
her twice in the head to end the misery she suffered from
osteoporosis and Alzheimer's disease.
   He was sentenced to life in prison.
   The case was recounted in last year's television movie, ``Mercy
or Murder,'' which featured Robert Young as Gilbert.
   Gilbert's new attorney, Bradley Stark, said the original trial
lawyer, Joseph Varon, had trouble separating the legal case from
the movie, a portion of which was filmed in Varon's office.
   ``Instead of being completely devoted to Mr. Gilbert, Mr. Varon
got swept away by the emotions of the event,'' Stark said.
   Stark said Varon wanted to use Gilbert's trial to make the
country aware of the lack of laws concerning euthanasia.
   Stark told the court Gilbert's contention that he shot his wife
to put her out of her misery was not effectively made in the first
trial.
   One of the witnesses called was Harry Gulkin, a partner in
Varon's law firm, who said Gilbert was ``in a state of shock,
disbelief, bewilderment and also very depressed about the whole
thing,'' contradicting the prosecution's argument that it was
premeditated.
   ``(Varon) didn't think any juror in this county, or this country
for that matter, would return a verdict of first-degree murder,''
Gulkin said.
   Also testifying was Steven Gethers, who produced the movie.
   The movie would not have been made if Gilbert had not been
convicted of first-degree murder, the producer said.
   ``For me, the drama was in the sentence that was given,'' he
said.
   Stark presented evidence unheard at the first trial, which he
claims was rushed to make Varon's rights to Gilbert's story more
profitable.
   Two neighbors, Mrs. Gilbert's hairdresser, Aghdas Sedghi, and a
waitress who served the couple regularly, all testified that Mrs.
Gilbert's health deteriorated rapidly shortly before the shooting.
   ``She was suffering constantly from pains in her back,'' said
neighbor Pauline McGinness. ``She said if she became old or
decrepit or put in a wheelchair, she hoped someone would put her
out.''
   Assistant State Attorney Kelly Hancock, who prosecuted Gilbert
and expects to testify at the hearing, rejects the argument Varon
mishandled the case.
   Hancock will argue that regardless of the defense, Gilbert
killed his wife and understood the consequences.
   Gilbert is serving his sentence at Lawtey Correctional
Institution and has no chance of parole for 25 years.
   Gilbert signed a pretrial agreement with Varon giving the lawyer
the rights to his story. MGM-UA Productions paid Varon $50,000 for
the rights.
   Gilbert donated his share, $5,000, in his wife's name to a
non-profit institution for Alzheimer's research.
</TEXT>
