<HEAD>Restroom Auctioned For $504,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tiny public restroom facility
overtaken by drug addicts and street people sold for $504,000 to a
restaurateur who plans to build a three-story Italian eatery on the
site.
   Real estate auctioneer Keith Jones said the art-deco style
restroom attracted 43 bids before Gino Bigazzi made the winning bid
Tuesday. Bigazzi, who has another restaurant in Sydney, plans to
tear down the restroom.
   The price stunned the City Council, which had been willing to
accept a bid about one-third of the selling price.
   The property, measuring 1,300 square feet, is in Sydney's
red-light suburb of King's Cross.
   The auctioneer promised bidders the property would be sold
without the squatters who lived in the building.
   The astronomical price reflects a real estate boom in Sydney,
where many property prices have doubled during the past year.
</TEXT>
