<DOCNO> AP880803-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MedicareBenefits     08-03 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Medicare Benefits,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Overturns Regulation Limiting Reimbursement for Home Health
Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court decision ordering the Reagan
administration to relax eligibility standards for elderly people to
get health care at home could help thousands of Medicare
recipients, according to a lawyer in the case.
   U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin's decision overturning a
Medicare regulation may encourage thousands of recipients to apply
for benefits they thought they never had, said William Dombi, legal
director of the National Association for Home Care, which brought
the lawsuit.
   Sporkin overturned a 1986 regulation defining ``part-time or
intermittent'' care as limiting eligibility to patients who
received four or fewer home visits a week.
   Sporkin said the four-day limit ``produces absurd results.''
   ``A beneficiary needing a total of five hours of care per week
is denied coverage if the care is needed over the course of five or
more days, while the person needing as many as 27 hours of care
spread over only four days may qualify for coverage,'' the judge
said in a 69-page opinion released Tuesday.
   ``Home health care beneficiaries must survive seven days a week
_ their medical needs do not take weekends off,'' he said.
   Dombi said the decision probably affects several thousand
Medicare beneficiaries who were denied reimbursement for visits by
nurses or health aides.
   ``People who sought nursing-home care as the alternative may now
have a chance to come into the home setting,'' he said.
   It also will encourage people who are receiving less care than
they need to get Medicare reimbursement for more frequent visits.
``We presented evidence that indicated people were receiving less
care than they needed solely to qualify for some benefit payment,''
Dombi said.
   ``People who have deprived themselves of care may come back into
the system,'' Dombi said.
   Sporkin ordered the Department of Health and Human Services to
reopen claims that had been denied since the lawsuit was filed Feb.
17, 1987, by the home care organization on behalf of 17 Medicare
recipients. The lawsuit was joined by 14 members of Congress.
   Sporkin found that HHS had improperly interpreted the term
``part-time or intermittent'' to mean that care must be both
part-time and intermittent. The plaintiffs argued that when
Congress enacted the Medicare program in 1965, it intended that
such home visits could be one or the other.
   The definition amounted to a four-day limit on visits that a
Medicare patient could receive each week from care providers, the
judge found.
   Robert Hardy, a spokesman for the Health Care Financing
Administration, an HHS unit that operates Medicare, said: ``We
haven't read the opinion but we believe that HCFA is properly
administering the home health benefit.''
   Dombi predicted the government would appeal Sporkin's decision,
but Hardy declined to comment on what legal steps the agency would
take.
   Legislation recently signed by President Reagan providing
catastrophic care coverage for Medicare recipients contains
language that lifts the four-day restriction.
   Sporkin also determined that the agency's policy forced elderly
people to go to administrative law judges to get the benefits to
which they are legally entitled. Most of the administrative law
judges side with the patients when they rule on the claims, Sporkin
said.
   But ``those that have insufficient energy or resources to appeal
simply fall by the wayside,'' Sporkin said.
   The judge said there were no statistics to indicate how many of
the 100,000 people denied home-care benefits last year were refused
payment because of the four-day limit.
   But the judge estimated ``the number of such people certainly is
in the hundreds and may be in the thousands.''
   Home care was offered by Congress, Sporkin said, as a more
economical and humane alternative to hospitals or nursing homes.
   Harold Galbraith, a paraplegic who suffers severe skin ulcers
and needs a catheter, was refused reimbursement for five hourly
visits each week by a health aide, the judge noted.
   ``With the help of the aide, Mr. Galbraith has managed to use a
wheelchair and has achieved some independence at his home and has
avoided going to an institution, Sporkin said.
   Sporkin has yet to rule on the plaintiffs' challenge to the
agency's definition of ``reasonable and necessary care.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
