<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Blind-Maps     08-03 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Blind-Maps,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Publishes Braille and Tactile Maps of Nation's Capital</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The newest tourist maps of the nation's
capital are written in braille with federal monuments and landmarks
visible to the hand as well as the eye.
   These braille and tactile maps will be available free to blind
and visually impaired visitors to Washington through congressional
offices.
   They were produced by the University of Maryland under a
$150,000 contract from the U.S. Education Department's Office of
Special Education and Rehabilitative Services.
   Madeleine Will, an assistant secretary of education, called the
maps ``the first of their kind.''
   ``They set a standard for other cities and help to make
Washington, D.C., the most accessible capital in the world,'' she
said.
   The colorful maps feature captions in both English and braille,
with such landmarks as the Lincoln Memorial, the White House, the
U.S. Capitol and the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier depicted by bumps
shaped like their contours.
   The set of six maps includes a guide to Metro, the rapid transit
system; the floor plan of the Capitol, Capitol Hill and the Mall
area, and the stretch from the White House to Arlington Cemetery.
</TEXT>
