<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SteelTrade     08-03 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steel Trade,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Firms Seek Commitments On Import Quotas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The steel industry turned a profit last year,
but its problems will surface again if the next president does not
renew import quotas that expire in 1989, steel company executives
said.
   A handful of executives told the Congressional Steel Caucus on
Tuesday that they were encouraged by public and private statements
by the two presidential contenders that the next administration
will extend the quotas, which cover 30 nations.
   The steel industry was profitable last year for the first time
since 1981.
   But allowing the so-called ``voluntary restraint agreements''
with Japan, South Korea and other nations to lapse in 1989 could
have dire consequences, said Thomas C. Graham, president of the
steel division of USX Corp., the nation's largest steel producer.
   ``Our balance sheets are still very fragile, and most analysts
see a market downturn in the relatively near future,'' Graham said.
He said the worldwide excess capacity and foreign governments'
steelmaking subsidies and unfair trading practices that prompted
the establishment of the quotas ``have not disappeared.''
   Graham and David Hoag, president and chief executive officer of
LTV Steel Co., the No. 2 steelmaker, said the presidential campaign
had yielded encouraging signals about steel trade from Democratic
contender Michael Dukakis and Republican rival George Bush.
   ``The domestic steel industry is very grateful that
(Massachusetts) Gov. Dukakis has stated his support for continuing
the voluntary restraint agreements, and we're hopeful that Vice
President Bush will also come out for extension before too long,''
Graham said.
   In an interview, Hoag said that Bush ``has said he is favorably
inclined (to extending the agreements), but he hasn't said it
publicly.'' Calls to the Bush campaign were referred to vice
presidential press assistant Kristin Taylor, who said she would
have to consult other aides before providing an answer.
   Hoag said the push to continue the trade agreements was ``an
industry position.'' Also briefing caucus members Tuesday were
Walter F. Williams, chairman of Bethlehem Steel Corp., the
third-leading steelmaker; and Joseph Toot Jr., president of the
Timken Co.
   Hoag said last year's industry-wide net income of $1 billion was
``good news.'' But he added that there has been ``little change in
the global structural conditions that contributed to the worst
period ever in the industry's history _ $12 billion in losses
during 1982-1986.''
   Congressional pressure and a finding by the U.S. International
Trade Commission that the steel industry was being harmed by
imports led the Reagan administration to negotiate five-year
agreements with leading steel-exporting nations in 1984. The
agreements placed product-by-product caps on the amount of steel
that can be imported into the United States each year.
   The American Institute for Imported Steel, an association of 70
steel importers, has lobbied against the quotas, saying ``free
enterprise must prevail.''
   U.S. firms that rely on imported steel claim that the Reagan
program has stifled competition, raised prices and caused harmful
shortages of certain types of steel.
   Since the quotas took effect in 1984, the foreign share of the
American steel market has dropped from nearly 30 percent to roughly
21 percent. Steel firms say the reduction has given them enough
breathing space and market stability to enable them to modernize.
</TEXT>
