<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     08-03 0864</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House, Senate Negotiators Seek Drought Relief Compromise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Agriculture Committee Chairman E.
``Kika'' de la Garza says he thinks President Reagan probably would
accept a temporary 50-cent increase in the price-support level for
milk if it arrived on his desk as part of drought relief
legislation.
   ``I feel confident that this won't violate the guidelines that
we received from the White House,'' de la Garza, D-Texas, said
Tuesday as House and Senate negotiators prepared to meet to resolve
differences over the drought bill.
   The House last week approved as part of its drought bill a
compromise that would raise the price-support level for milk by 50
cents, but only from April through June next year, after which the
benefit would expire.
   The compromise offered by Reps. Steve Gunderson, R-Wis., and Tim
Penny, D-Minn., replaced a proposed permanent increase of 50 cents
in the price-support level starting in October. Agriculture
Secretary Richard Lyng lobbied against such a measure, saying it
would cost $300 million.
   Lawmakers said the price tag would be less than half that. They
placed the cost of the Gunderson-Penny version at $100 million.
   Both the House and Senate versions of the bill would cancel a
50-cent cut in the support level. But the senate has no provision
for an increase and that represents one of the major differences
the conference committee must resolve.
   At the heart of both bills are disaster payments to farmers
equal to 65 percent of earnings lost as a result of crop losses in
excess of 35 percent of the expected harvest.
   De la Garza was noncommittal about a key Senate provision not
contained in the House version of the drought bill. It would allow
ethanol makers to buy corn and other government-owned commodities
for 110 percent of the acquisition prices _ well below current cash
crop prices that have skyrocketed as a result of the drought.
   Ethanol makers could buy up to 2 million bushels a month but a
total of no more than 16 million bushels a month would be available
and the program would end in September 1989.
   The measure is being presented as a frank effort to help small,
hard-pressed ethanol makers with a price break. But it also could
mean a substantial break for the Archer Daniels Midland Co. of
Decatur, Ill., a major company that manufactures the lion's share
of domestic ethanol.
   ``I could live with it as long as they spread around some of the
joy and didn't just save everything for the big boys, if they let
some of the little guys have some too,'' de la Garza said.
   Ethanol is ethyl alcohol, made from farm goods such as corn, and
mixed with gasoline to form the fuel gasohol.
   Ethanol also has been causing a snag in efforts to win fast
Senate approval of legislation to curb record U.S. trade deficits.
Farm-state senators have been trying to knock out a House-passed
provision that would increase duty-free imports of Caribbean
ethanol.
   U.S. corn growers are anxious to hold down imports and say the
Caribbean products often are nothing more than European
agricultural products, such as Spanish wine, that have been run
through island ethanol refineries.
   Meanwhile, de la Garza and a contingent of farm Democrats are
scheduled to fly to Boston on Wednesday night for a talk with
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis at his Brookline, Mass., home.
   ``I don't think he wants to talk about the drought so much as
the future of farming,'' de la Garza said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite trade tensions between the two
countries, Japan remains the top consumer of U.S. agricultural
exports and the Agriculture Department is offering tips on how to
do business in that market.
   ``Carefully choose a partner or partners to work with in
Japan,'' Suzanne Hale, U.S. agricultural trade officer in Tokyo,
advised in an interview in the department-produced magazine Foreign
Agriculture.
   ``Visit and study the market,'' she said. ``Keep in touch with
customers, try to understand their needs and be flexible in meeting
those needs. Above all, be flexible. Japan is a big market.''
   The Japanese imported $20 billion worth of agricultural
commodities in 1987, $6.7 billion of that amount, or about 20
percent, from the United States. Chief competitors are Australia,
Canada and Argentina for grains, France and Germany for wines, the
entire European Community for processed foods, Thailand for chicken
and Denmark and Taiwan for pork.
   Hale said young Japanese are ``becoming much more
adventuresome'' in eating habits with Italian and Mexican
restaurants burgeoning in Tokyo.
   ``There are a lot of opportunities in the market for traditional
Western-style foods as well,'' she said.
   She said health-consciousness is sharpening among Japanese food
buyers and, because more women are working than ever before, there
is greater interest in convenience foods that can be readily
prepared.
   She cited Japanese import quotas and food additive regulations
as among some of the toughest problems that U.S. exporters face.
   ``Another difficulty for U.S. companies is that Japanese
consumers are used to high-quality packaging,'' she said. ``A few
U.S. companies have developed special packaging for Japan, but much
more could be done.''
</TEXT>
