<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NewPlanet Bjt   08-03 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Planet, Bjt,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Astronomers Find Planet Near Distant Star</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of astronomers making routine
measurements on a star have found the first confirmed evidence of a
planet orbiting a star other than our own sun.
   David W. Latham, who led the team that made the discovery, said
the planet is 30,000 times larger than the Earth and probably
lifeless because it would have a surface temperature of hundreds of
degrees.
   ``It's much hotter than an oven,'' said Latham. ``This is not a
place you would look for life.''
   The planet is so close to its star that it orbits once every 84
days, Latham said. Mercury, the planet closest to the sun, has an
orbit of 87 days.
   Latham reports on the discovery today at the 20th general
assembly of the International Astronomical Union in Baltimore.
   Latham and his team found the planet while running instrument
tests on a star called HD 114762. He said the star was one of a
group called ``candidate standard stars'' that astronomers have
been measuring for years to establish the characteristics of basic
star types. The study is being conducted to give astronomers
worldwide a standard for calibrating instruments.
   Using light gathered by a 61-inch reflector telescope at the Oak
Ridge Observatory in Massachusetts, the astronomers processed the
star sightings through an instrument called the photon counting
system.
   The instrument detected a slight wobble in the motion of the
star that could only be caused by a nearby orbiting body.
   Latham said the planet would have to be massive, some 20 times
larger than Jupiter, the largest planet in the solar system, in
order to give star HD 114762 such a wobble.
   ``It's at the upper edge (of being the size) of a planet,''
Latham said. Minimum starlike bodies are usually 100 times the size
of Jupiter.
   Despite its size, the planet is too small and too distant to be
seen directly. Star HD 114762 is 90 light years from Earth, about
522 trillion miles away. Seeing the planet would be like trying to
sight a single candle placed beside a powerful searchlight on the
moon, Latham said.
   Instead, the scientists used calculations of the gravitational
effects on the star to determine that another body was there.
   Latham said the discovery raises the intriguing possibility that
``companion bodies,'' or planet-like bodies orbiting stars, may be
more common than previously believed.
   ``It wouldn't surprise me if more people started finding them,''
he said.
   Latham added: ``It would be pretty boring if there weren't lots
of planets because that would mean there aren't many chances for
life.''
   The technique that discovered the planet around star HD 114762
is not sensitive enough, he said, to find a planet the size of
Earth.
   ``We're far short of being able to find anything as small as
Earth,'' he said, because the gravitational effect on a star would
be too slight to be detected.
   Star HD 114762 is a magnitude 7, too faint to be seen by the
naked eye. It is also a spring star, seen only from March through
July. The tilt of the Earth causes it to be blotted from view by
the sun from August through February.
   Detection of the planet around the star has been confirmed by a
Swiss astronomer, Michel Mayor, at the Geneva Observatory.
   Members of Latham's team include Robert Stefanik, Richard
McCrosky and Robert Davis of the Smithsonian, and Tsevi Mazeh of
the University of Tel Aviv.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880803-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Trade     08-03 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethanol Clash Looming as Senate Leaders Push Trade Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate leaders are pushing for fast action on
their bill to curb trade deficits but they face obstacles posed by
Farm Belt lawmakers who want to reduce Caribbean ethanol imports.
   ``We are going to send the president another trade bill,''
Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said Tuesday as
lawmakers turned to the 1,000-page measure that has lingered on
their calendar in one form or another for the last three years.
   They planned to discourage any amendments, whisk the
House-passed measure through the Senate and speed it toward
President Reagan's desk this week.
   Amendments would send the measure to a House-Senate conference
committee that easily could become bogged down. Senate leaders said
that might prove fatal with only 26 legislative days remaining
before they recess and head for the campaign trail full time.
   However, an array of amendments quickly materialized, including
changes proposed by Sen. J. James Exon, D-Neb., and other farm
state lawmakers opposed to a provision of the bill that would
increase the amount of duty-free ethanol imported from the
Caribbean.
   Ethanol is ethyl alcohol made from agricultural products and
blended with gasoline to form the fuel gasahol. U.S. corn growers
are sharply opposed to any increase in imports and complain that
the Caribbean product often consists of European goods, such as
Spanish wine, recycled in island refineries.
   The lawmakers are seeking to delete the ethanol provision, or at
least alter it to bar any upsurge in shipments.
   The trade bill, dormant for weeks, came to the Senate floor only
hours after President Reagan announced that he would allow to
become law a separate measure requiring companies to provide their
employees with advance notice of plant closings and large-scale
layoffs.
   Reagan had vetoed an earlier version of the trade bill which
contained the plant-closings provision, saying that provision would
needlessly tie the hands of business.
   There had been an implied threat than unless the president
signed the plant-closings measure, the trade bill could die in the
Senate.
   The administration has not been very enthusiastic about trade
bills, either, but it is getting anxious to receive congressional
authorization to conclude agreements under the current Uruguay
Round of international trade talks. The bill would provide that
authorization along with accelerated consideration by the House and
Senate of deals made in the negotiations.
   ``The president indicated that he wanted a trade bill _ that's
why he swallowed the plant closings,'' said Senate Minority Leader
Bob Dole, R-Kan.
   Besides giving the administration authority to reach trade
agreements, the measure would streamline the machinery under which
the government imposes import restraints. They are used to protect
U.S. industries and retaliate against violations of international
rules and other unfair practices.
   Other provisions range from a potential $2 billion in
agricultural subsidies to repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil
company earnings.
   The measure is largely shorn of the protectionism that once
brought fierce opposition from both the administration and a raft
of congressional critics.
   Even though the measure is likely to pass by a wide margin, one
of the Senate's most outspoken free traders, Sen. Daniel J. Evans,
R-Wash., was critical of it in floor debate Tuesday night.
   ``The real problem isn't corrected by this bill,'' he said.
``The real problem is that we as a nation are spending too much,
living beyond our means and saving too little,'' Evans said.
   Evans, whose home-state economy includes an export-dependent
aircraft industry and a major port, said that because the economy
is now performing well the measure ``is probably too late if it was
ever necessary and in this senator's view it was probably never
necessary at all.''
   ``This trade bill represents those who fear the future, not
those who have confidence in the future,'' he said.
</TEXT>
