<1ST_LINE>r w PM-King-Holiday     08-03 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-King-Holiday,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coretta Scott King Seeks Federal Funds for Holiday Commission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coretta Scott King says Congress must provide
``the means and encouragement'' for the federal commission that
coordinates observances of the holiday honoring her late husband,
the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
   ``The Congress placed an enormous responsibility upon the
commission, but it gave no funds,'' Mrs. King, who chairs the
Martin Luther King Jr. Federal Holiday Commission, told a House
panel Tuesday.
   ``I ask the Congress which gave birth to the national holiday to
help us continue our work _ to give us the means and encouragement
to complete the job we have just started.''
   The King commission was created on a temporary basis in 1984 as
part of a bill to make the civil rights leader's birthday a
national holiday. Because of opposition to the bill from some
conservative members of Congress, led by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,
funding plans for the commission were dropped in order to get the
bill passed.
   The commission's congressional mandate expires in April 1989,
and a bill sponsored by Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., now before the
census and population subcommittee of the House Post Office and
Civil Service Committee, would provide $300,000 in annual funding.
   Sen. Lowell Weicker, R-Conn., a supporter of the Conyers bill,
said requests to the commission now outstrip what the group is able
to accomplish.
   ``The commission has more work than the meager resources it has
been able to raise from the private sector can begin to support,''
Weicker said.
   Rep. Mervyn Dymally, D-Calif., who chairs the House panel,
agreed and pledged to add an amendment to the legislation that
would increase funding to at least $500,000 per year.
   The commission processed more than 5,000 information requests
and helped 135 state and local governments plan holiday events in
1987, according to commission records.
   The Atlanta-based commission collected $183,552 in private
contributions in 1987, and has no paid employees, the records
showed.
   Nearly all money received went to producing newsletters and
pamphlets on King's life, said Lloyd Davis, the commission's
executive director. Staff assistance comes from federal employees
``loaned out'' from their agencies on a temporary basis, he said.
   By contrast, the Commission on the Bicentennial of the United
States Constitution will receive $21 million in federal money this
year, while the United States Holocaust Memorial Council will
receive just over $2 million.
   ``We're talking about a desperate situation,'' Davis said. ``We
simply can't do it without some federal help.''
   Dymally said the bill should reach the full Post Office and
Civil Service Committee next week, and be considered on the House
floor in September.
   The holiday is officially celebrated on the third Monday in
January, which falls close to King's Jan. 15 birthday. The only
states that do not observe the date are Arizona, New Hampshire,
Montana, Wyoming, South Dakota and Idaho.
   Besides King, only George Washington and Abraham Lincoln have
their birthdays marked by national holidays.
   Meanwhile, Mrs. King revealed some of the plans for a second
March on Washington, to be held in commemoration of the historic
``I Have a Dream'' speech her husband delivered 25 years ago before
more than 200,000 civil rights activists in front of the Lincoln
Memorial.
   The celebration, scheduled for Aug. 27, will focus on
employment, housing and civil rights issues, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
