<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WritersStrike 1stLd-Writethru a0781 08-03 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0781,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Informal Talks Hoped Useful Toward Ending Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADs with 5 grafs to UPDATE with talks continuing; picks up
5th graf pvs, `The contacts ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives for producers and striking
scriptwriters met Tuesday, exploring ways to break a deadlock in
the 22-week-old labor dispute that has shut down most Hollywood
production.
   The informal talks were continuing as of 11 p.m. Tuesday.
   Although the top West Coast official of the Writers Guild of
America expressed hope that agreement could be reached, the union
and producers declined to elaborate Tuesday on the exact nature of
the discussions.
   ``There is nothing I can comment on now,'' spokeswoman Cheryl
Rhoden said. ``We are using every avenue we can to have the talks
resume.''
   After the formal, federally mediated talks collapsed early
Saturday morning, intermediaries for the opposing sides made
contact to determine if negotiations should resume, Ms. Rhoden said.
   The contacts spurred hope among some at WGA headquarters that a
settlement with the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television
Producers might be near, two guild sources said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Herb Steinberg, a spokesman for the producers alliance,
confirmed that intermediaries were attempting to resume talks.
``The alliance is not a part of it,'' Steinberg said. ``It's
shuttle diplomacy.''
   The main sticking point in the contract dispute is how much
writers should be paid for syndicated reruns of television shows.
The 9,000-member guild blamed the collapse of formal negotiations
on the alliance, while producers said the guild made unreasonable
demands and refused to compromise.
   Brian Walton, executive director of the guild on the West Coast,
said late Monday that he had spoken with two representatives of the
dissident Writers Coalition, which has threatened to break away
from the guild to return to work.
   The coalition of 21 writers has pushed for a strike settlement
under contract terms that the guild has strongly opposed.
   Walton said he did not guarantee them that an end to the strike
was imminent, but asked them to remain patient. ``All I said was
that I was hopeful,'' Walton said.
   The group has threatened to drop out of the strike and was
expected to resign from the guild this week. After a four-hour
strategy conference Monday, the coalition announced it would
continue to honor the walkout that began March 7.
   But the dissidents will again reconsider resigning if the strike
continues past week's end, said Lionel Chetwynd, a spokesman for
the coalition.
   An official at 20th Century Fox film studio said Monday that his
company will pay any union fines incurred by striking scriptwriters
who cross picket lines.
   Barry Diller, the head of 20th Century Fox, made the offer,
according to Fox spokesman Michael Binkow.
   Guild fines against strike-breaking writers are set at 110
percent of all compensation received for unauthorized strike work,
and violators are subject to lifetime expulsion from the guild, Ms.
Rhoden said.
</TEXT>
