<1ST_LINE>r p PM-StuartKarl     08-03 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stuart Karl,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pleads Guilty in Connection With Illegal Contributions To Hart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Video entrepreneur G. Stuart Karl has
pleaded guilty to two counts involving unlawful political
contributions made to the campaign of former Democratic
presidential candidate Gary Hart.
   Karl, 36, of Newport Beach, entered his plea Tuesday in U.S.
District Court to two counts of a 12-count indictment handed up by
a federal grand jury in June.
   He pleaded guilty to one count of conspiracy involving efforts
to impede an investigation by the Federal Election Commission and
to one count of making a political contribution in the name of
another person.
   Under terms of the plea bargain approved by Judge Alicemarie
Stotler, Karl may be fined $350,100 and given six months probation,
but will get no jail time in return for his cooperation with
authorities in a federal investigation.
   He faced a maximum of 36 years in prison and $930,000 in fines.
   Karl was released on $25,000 bail pending sentencing Sept. 19.
   The indictment charged Karl, producer of the Jane Fonda
``Workout'' videos, with six counts of campaign financing law
violations, one count of conspiracy and five counts of filing false
statements.
   It alleges Karl asked former employees to contribute up to
$1,000 each to various candidates, then reimbursed them in cash.
   The bulk of the donations, $159,500, went to Hart's 1984
presidential campaign, the indictment said.
</TEXT>
