<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Iran-Iraq     08-03 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Iran-Iraq,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN Chief Says He Won't Impose Unilateral Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Confounding Diplomacy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
backed down and said he would not try to impose a cease-fire in the
Iran-Iraq war after Iraq declared it would reject such a truce.
   Iraq continued Tuesday to insist on direct talks with Iran
before a cease-fire. But in Iran, President Ali Khamenei said his
government would not agree to face-to-face negotiations before a
truce and that an end to the 8-year-old war appears ``extremely
doubtful.''
   Riyadh al-Qaysi, Iraq's former U.N. ambassador and now a member
of the Iraqi delegation to U.N.-mediated peace talks, accused Iran
of seeking ``simply a cease-fire which they so urgently need after
their successive defeats.''
   He said Iraq would reject any cease-fire it had not agreed to
and would not allow Iran to regroup during a truce: ``We will not
accept a fait accompli, no matter in what form or from which
quarter it comes.''
   Iraq has continued attacks on Iran despite Tehran's announcement
July 18 that it was finally accepting a year-old U.N. Security
Council cease-fire resolution.
   Iraq said last year that it would accept Resolution 598, which
calls for a cease-fire, withdrawal to recognized borders, prisoner
exchange, peace negotiations and an investigation of which side
started the war.
   On Monday, Perez de Cuellar said, ``Listen, D-Day (the day a
cease-fire begins) does not depend on the parties.''
   Asked if he might announce D-Day if Iraq remains opposed, the
U.N. chief said: ``That is a decision which I have to take in any
case in consultation with the members of the Security Council.''
   But on Tuesday, he said: ``When I say I will declare a
cease-fire with members of the Security Council, I do not exclude
that I would be in touch with the two foreign ministers.''
   U.N. officials said the secretary-general would be consulting
now with the head of a U.N. fact-finding team, Gen. Martin Vadset
of Norway, who arrives Thursday from the Persian Gulf, then with
the Security Council and foreign ministers Ali Akbar Velayati of
Iran and Tariq Aziz of Iraq.
   On Tuesday, Perez de Cuellar did not meet official with either
foreign minister. The talks began last week.
   Khameini said: ``We shall not accept any preconditions from Iraq
over the implementation of the resolution and a cease-fire on the
fronts ... such as direct negotiations or any other condition.''
   ``If Iraq sets down preconditions, we too shall set down a
condition and ours will be what we have stated before, the
punishment of the aggressor,'' he said in a speech on Tehran radio,
monitored in Cyprus.
   During the year of Iran's holdout on the resolution, it insisted
there could be no truce until Iraq was branded as the aggressor.
Iraq invaded Iran in September 1980 after several border skirmishes.
   In a speech at a rally in Ahvaz, near the Iraqi border, Khamenei
criticized ``the Iraqi regime's attitude during the past two weeks,
its obstructionist behavior regarding the implementation of
Resolution 598.''
   ``I look at the prospect of achieving peace and an end to the
war in the context of Resolution 598 as extremely doubtful and
suspect,'' he said. ``This enemy has proved that it understands
nothing except the language of force and of strength.''
   Qaysi said Resolution 598 ``is not simply a cease-fire. It is a
peace plan and that has to be negotiated face-to-face to test the
real intentions of Iran.''
   Iranian Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati said the
secretary-general should declare a D-Day to begin a cease-fire even
if Iraq is opposed and that the Security Council should consider
imposing an arms embargo against Iraq if it does not accept a truce.
</TEXT>
