<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LibyanIndictments     08-03 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Libyan Indictments,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says More Indictments Expected in Libya Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men who have refused to testify
before a grand jury investigating an alleged plot to use Libyan
government money to recruit support in the United States can remain
free until Thursday afternoon to appeal a contempt order, a federal
judge ruled.
   U.S. District Judge T.S. Ellis III on Tuesday gave Vernon
Bellecourt, William Means and Bob Brown until 5 p.m. Thursday to
appeal to the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals the order that they
be jailed for civil contempt of court.
   The three have been told they are not targets of the
investigation. They were promised immunity from prosecution but
refused to testify in protest over the government's wire tapping of
their phones and what they said were other violations of their
rights.
   Six Libyans and two other Arab nationals were accused last week
in a 40-count indictment that charges them with laundering money
and violating the 1986 Libyan sanctions regulations that prohibit
travel to and transactions with Libya.
   The indictment makes no mention of previous accusations that one
of the eight participated in a plot to assassinate a senior U.S.
official _ purportedly former White House aide Oliver North _ who
helped plan the 1986 U.S. bombing of Libya.
   Attorney John Keats, representing Bellecourt and Means, argued
that their testimony was not needed since the grand jury already
had returned indictments.
   But Assistant U.S. Attorney Lawrence J. Leiser said that ``there
are continuing ongoing investigations being conducted by the grand
jury.''
   ``Are you referring to indictments other than those already
handed down?'' asked Ellis.
   ``Absolutely,'' Leiser replied. He did not elaborate.
   Bellecourt, of the White Earth Chippewa Nation from northern
Minnesota, said he visited Libya several times and was an organizer
of a 1987 rally in Tripoli marking the first anniversary of the
U.S. bombing.
   Means, of the International Indian Treaty Council, also has
acknowledged visiting Libya.
   Brown is from the All-African People's Revolutionary Party,
which supports a unified Africa. Before the hearing, he told a news
conference: ``We proudly traveled to Libya to condemn this
government's barbaric attack and reaffirm our First Amendment
right.''
</TEXT>
