<DOCNO> AP880803-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0404EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseProbe     08-03 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Rep. Chappell Being Investigated in Defense Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators probing alleged Pentagon
procurement fraud are investigating whether Rep. Bill Chappell and
others receive money illegally funneled from the Unisys Corp., The
Washington Post reported today.
   The money allegedly came to Chappell, a Florida Democrat, and
others influential in defense contracting through operating
expenses and purchasing orders of Armtec Inc., a small
subcontractor based in Palatka, Fla., the newspaper said, citing
unidentified sources. Federal agents seized records from the
Florida plant in a June 14 raid.
   Chappell could not be reached for comment Tuesday night, but he
told the newspaper he is not a target of the investigation and that
he has conducted himself in an ethical manner.
   ``I think it is inappropriate for me to comment on any aspect of
this ongoing investigation and I hope the investigation will go
forward in the most fair, expeditious manner,'' Chappell told the
Post.
   Under investigation are allegations that defense contractors and
consultants, many of them former military men, bribed Pentagon
officials for contracting details that could be vital in winning
contracts worth billions of dollars.
   Documents unsealed in a New York court last month showed that
investigators were examining whether private consultants and others
extorted campaign contributions from companies.
   The papers also indicated investigators were looking into
whether defense industry officials, consultants and others bribed
federal officials involved in authorizing or appropriating defense
contracts.
   Chappell and other congressmen have been mentioned earlier as
subjects of investigative interest in the probe.
   However, Henry Hudson, the U.S. attorney for northern Virgnia
who is in charge of the investigation, has told congressional
leaders that no members of Congress were targets of the probe,
according to congressional sources who attended meetings with
Hudson.
   The newspaper said the investigation involving Chappell concerns
William W. Roberts, a retired Unisys executive; William M. Galvin,
a defense procurement consultant, and Charles F. Gardner, a former
vice president of Unisys' plant in Great Neck, N.Y.
   Roberts and Galvin formed Armtec in 1986 to produce wire
harnesses for a shipboard electronic warfare system manufactured at
the Great Neck plant, and Gardner arranged for the noncompetitive
contract with Armtec, the newspaper said.
   Investigators have subpoenaed the financial records of an Ocala,
Fla., health club in which Chappell once had an interest.
</TEXT>
