<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Attack 3rdLd-Writethru a0472 08-03 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Attack, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0472,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Contras Attack Boat, Kill 2, Injure 27</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with number of passengers;
picks up 3rd graf pvs: The boat...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels attacked a passenger boat on a
remote southeastern river Tuesday and killed two people and wounded
27, including an American clergyman, according to government and
witness reports.
   A witness to the attack on the Rama River said about a dozen
Americans and several Sandinista soldiers were aboard the vessel, a
regular passenger boat on the river called the Peace Mission.
   Witnesses said about 200 people were aboard the vessel.
   The boat was traveling upstream to the town of Rama after
leaving Bluefields, the country's main Caribbean port, when a group
of Contras began firing weapons at about 4 p.m., the Defense
Ministry said.
   It said two people were killed and 27 wounded, and that all the
victims were civilians.
   One of the American passengers, Gail Walker, 29, said her
father, the Rev. Lucius Walker, ``was grazed in the buttocks by a
bullet,'' but he ``was fine now'' and receiving some stitches.
   Speaking in a telephone interview in Managua, where the group
was flown after the attack, Ms. Walker said the attack lasted about
10 minutes.
   Walker, 59, of Demarest, N.J., is executive director of the
Inter-Religious Foundation for Communication Organizations, an
inter-denominational group based in New York. Ms. Walker, 29, of
Paterson, N.J., is its communications programming director.
   The communique said the raid occurred near the village of El
Mango, about 150 miles southeast of Managua.
   The Rama River connects the recently built Managua-Rama road and
links the capital with Bluefields, where Nicaragua receives the
bulk of its military supplies from the Soviet Union, Cuba and other
Soviet bloc nations.
   The only other port capable of handling military supplies is
Puerto Sandino, on the west coast, which would require a long trip
through the Panama Canal.
   Ms. Walker said the Contras opened fire on the boat two hours
before it was to reach Rama.
   ``I dove down the stairs. I figured brusies were better than
bullet holes. The bullets came through the walls,'' she said,
adding that she was ``a little bruised, a little hoarse, a little
scared but OK.''
   About 20 Sandinista soldiers were on the top deck when the
attack came, but most of the Contra fire was aimed at the
mid-section of the vessel where the civilians were standing, Ms.
Walker said.
   She said she and her father came with the religious group, which
does not support President Reagan's Central American policy, to
Nicaragua on July 26 ``to find out first hand the actual situation
of the country.''
   ``Now we're all in agreement on condemning Contra aid. This was
a civilian boat,'' she added.
   No confirmation or claim of responsibility had surfaced by late
Tuesday from the U.S.-supported rebels, known as Contras.
   The Contras have tried to cut the Managua-Bluefields supply link
several times. In January, they seized several towns and villages
along the Managua-Rama road to stop the supply flow, but later
retreated.
   The attack violates a fragile cease-fire to which the Contras
and the leftist Sandinista government agreed on March 23.
   Later efforts by the two sides have failed to negotiate a
permanent truce in the 7-year-old war and Reagan is seeking to
renew military aid to the Contras, which Congress cut off in
February.
   The cease-fire was due to end June 30, but was tacitly extended
by both sides, despite complaints of violations. The truce was due
to expire again on July 31, but President Daniel Ortega
unilaterally extended it to Aug. 31.
   The last Sandinista-Contra meeting was on June 9. The Saninistas
offered to meet again in Managua on Aug. 26-29, but the Contras
said they want the meeting held outside the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
