<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Gulf-Explosion     08-03 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Gulf-Explosion,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Filipino Freighter Explodes in Gulf of Oman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small Filipino cargo vessel exploded
and sank in the Gulf of Oman early today, Persian Gulf-based
shipping executives reported.
   The cause of the explosion could not be immediately determined
and it was not known if there were any casualties.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
explosion could have resulted from engine problems, but they did
not exclude the possibility that the vessel hit a mine.
   The executives identified the vessel as the 1,870-ton Fatima.
   They said a French warship in the vicinity rushed to help and
rescued seven crew members about 30 miles off Oman outside the
Strait of Hormuz, gateway to the Persian Gulf.
   Mines were detected south of where the vessel sank during the
rash of explosions last summer that prompted the United States and
other nations to send mine sweepers.
   Iran was accused of planting the mines as part of its strategy
in its 8-year-old war with Iraq.
   No mine incidents have been reported since the U.S. warship
Samuel B. Roberts hit one in the gulf in April.
   The area where the Fatima blew up is roughly where the Kuwaiti
tankers flying the American flag assemble for escort by U.S. Navy
warships through the Strait of Hormuz and up to Kuwait.
   Kuwait reflagged the 11 tankers in the United States last summer
to obtain U.S. protection from Iranian attacks.
   An Iranian envoy to the gulf Arab capitals recently said he
expected that Kuwait would call soon for an end to the escort
operations because of Iran's acceptance last month of a year-old
U.N. cease-fire resolution.
   The U.N. secretary-general is negotiating with Iraq and Iran to
implement the resolution.
</TEXT>
