<1ST_LINE>d a PM-NationalMedical     08-03 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-National Medical,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oakland Physician New President of Black Doctors' Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Oakland physician has been installed as
the new president of the National Medical Association, one of the
nation's oldest black professional organizations.
   Dr. Frank E. Staggers Sr. was installed as the 87th president of
the group of 1,500 black physicians meeting here this week.
   In assuming leadership of the group, which was founded in
Atlanta in 1895, Staggers told his colleagues that black physicians
need to form a coordinated policy to deliver the best health care
to their patients.
   ``As NMA president, I will be adressing those issues and my
other goals will be to address the challenges that impact the black
family, especially the young black male,'' Staggers said in a
statement.
   ``If we are to address the issues of the drug culture, the AIDS
epidemic and the associated violence perpetuated upon our
communities by these problems, we must address the pathology of
young black males in our country,'' he said during his acceptance
speech.
   He said the greatest health crisis confronting the black
community is that the health of young black men is threatened by
drug abuse, violence and the AIDS epidemic.
   A native of Charleston, S.C., Staggers is married to California
Assemblywoman Teresa P. Hughes.
</TEXT>
