<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     08-03 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business at the General Hospital cafeteria here
has been victimized in an attack of Big Macs, Health and Hospitals
Manager John Fairman says. So he wants to reopen negotiations with
the fast-food chain.
   After just a month of operation, the McDonald's at the hospital
has been eating into cafeteria, snack bar and vending machine
revenues, he said.
   The restaurant apparently has cost the cafeteria $500 a day _
even on burrito day _ and an additional $150 at the snack bar
operated by hospital volunteers.
   ``By projecting the daily drop we're having right now, we could
lose $20,000 a month,'' Fairman said Tuesday.
   The city is guaranteed a yearly rent of $80,000 plus 6 percent
of McDonald's sales exceeding $1.3 million. When the contract was
signed last year, city officials believed the arrangement would
bring in a total of $150,000 yearly.
   ``We're clapping our hands over $150,000?'' Fairman asked.
``That's an embarrassment. The $150,000 didn't take into
consideration the loss factor in the cafeteria and vending
machines.''
   Fairman has written a letter to McDonald's, suggesting that ``we
renegotiate the financial terms'' of the deal with the hospital.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LA CANADA FLINTRIDGE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peacocks and peahens have
``peaturbed'' a lot of residents here, so the City Council voted to
buy traps to help catch some of the colorful birds.
   The peafowl population has increased since 1984, when a forest
fire in the area reduced the number of coyotes roaming the area.
Before that, coyotes kept the peafowl population down by preying on
them.
   The birds, known for their fan-like tails, have been causing
problems for residents in the north part of the city, nestled at
the foot of the San Gabriel Mountains just north of Los Angeles.
   Robert Barrow, who led the drive against the peacocks, said he
has spent $200 so far this year to replace vegetation eaten by the
birds in his yard.
   ``My wife buys (plants), I dig the hole, she plants them and the
peacocks tear them up,'' he said. ``If some people want to keep
peacocks, they should keep them on a leash.''
   The boxlike traps will be loaned to residents who can catch the
animals and turn them over to the Wildlife Way Station.
   ``People have a right to take action just as if they were
bothered by gophers or skunks,'' Mayor Joan Feehan said when the
council acted on the trap purchases Monday night.
</TEXT>
