<HEAD>Legislators Seek End To Racially Offensive Marketing Practices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators concerned about racially offensive
marketing practices by some Japanese companies are calling for an
end to derogatory representations of blacks and warning of a
possible boycott if changes aren't made.
   The head of the Congressional Black Caucus on Tuesday made
public a letter to Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita urging
him to call a meeting with Japanese businessmen ``to formally bring
an end to the negative stereotypic representations of black
Americans once and for all.''
   Rep. Mervyn M. Dymally, D-Calif., the caucus chairman, suggested
blacks might boycott Japanese products if changes are not made. He
said the portrayal of blacks in marketing and advertising in Japan
is insensitive and racially inflammatory.
   Members of the Black Caucus and other legislators accused the
Sanrio Co., Sogo Department Store and Yamato Mannequin Co. of
producing products and mannequins which show blacks in a
stereotypical and degrading light.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Drunken Driving Bill Gets Support From Beer Distributors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation that would encourage states to
crack down on drunken drivers has gained a vote of support from the
nation's beer distributors, who say they don't need the business of
intoxicated drivers.
   ``We don't want their business,'' Ronald R. Rumbaugh, president
of the National Beer Wholesalers' Association, told the Senate
Commerce consumer subcommittee Tuesday. ``In fact, we want to put
them out of business.''
   The subcommittee heard from Rumbaugh and other private and
government officials about proposed legislation offering increased
federal aid to states that adopt several strict plans intended to
prevent traffic accidents caused by drunken drivers.
   Among them are the immediate confiscation of a driver's license
when the operator fails a chemical test for intoxication or refuses
to take such a test. The state would have 15 days to suspend the
license or return it to the operator.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Comment Sought On Plan To Ensure Accuracy of Lab Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government is accepting public
comments on a proposal to toughen standards for clinical
laboratories in an effort to ensure the accuracy of Pap Smears and
other tests.
   The proposed rules apply to the 12,000 labs that are federally
regulated either because they do work under Medicare or Medicaid or
engage in interstate commerce.
   The practical effect is to cover virtually all commercial labs,
except those in physicians' offices. However, Congress has ordered
the Health Care Financing Administration to regulate physicians'
office labs that test 5,000 specimens or more starting in 1990.
   The 90-day comment period outlined in Tuesday's Federal Register
also solicits comments on whether the uniform standards should
apply to physicians' office labs once they are covered by federal
standards.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Craft Dolls Recalled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission says
two soft plastic dolls sold in craft stores around the nation are
being recalled because small children might choke on their parts.
   The dolls, 4{ inches and 5{ inches in height, are unclothed and
sold in clear plastic bags. The larger one has red hair, freckles
and painted-on red shoes.
   Wang's International of Memphis, Tenn., packaged the dolls,
which were labeled Cupid Doll PDT3538 or PDT631D on the packages
but not the dolls.
   The safety commission warned that the arms can be pulled off the
dolls, creating a potential choking hazard for small children. No
injuries have been reported, but the agency urged Tuesday that the
dolls be taken away from children and returned to retailers for
refunds.
   Consumers needing more information can call Wang's at
1-800-824-0467 or the safety commission at 1-800-638-2772.
</TEXT>
