<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Carcione     08-03 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Carcione,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Green Grocer' Dead at 73</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURLINGAME, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Carcione, who has offered millions
of people consumer tips as TV's ``Green Grocer,'' has died after a
long battle against intestinal cancer. He was 73.
   Carcione, who began his career in his father's produce market
after finishing high school, died Tuesday at Peninsula Hospital of
cardiac arrest, said his son-in-law, Charlie Erle.
   The gravelly voiced produce expert whose trademark was his
pronunciation of ``VEG-ee-tibles'' was famous for his weekly radio
and television spots in which he told consumers about produce
bargains and pitfalls. He also wrote two books.
   At his peak, Carcione wrote three newspaper columns a week,
producing TV and radio spots that reached 10 million listeners and
helped him earn $500,000 a year. He was syndicated on about 80 TV
stations nationwide.
   He attributed his success to his sincerity.
   ``I'm going to tell the truth,'' he said. ``If I can't do what's
right, I'm going to get off the air. There's no other way.''
   Two years ago, he told the San Francisco Chronicle that people
would see him on the street and say, ``Hi Joe, I feel like I know
you.''
   ``That's a real compliment,'' Carcione said.
   He began working in his father's produce market in San Francisco
in 1933 after finishing high school.
   In 1957, he got started in broadcast when he began making his
own commercials. He later was asked to do unpaid grocer spots on
San Francisco's KCBS and other radio stations.
   In 1974, KRON-TV offered to pay him and his career took off.
   His produce warehouse in the Golden Gate Produce terminal in
South San Francisco now is mostly operated by his oldest son, Peter.
   The elder Carcione would go to work at 5 a.m., strolling through
the terminal, sampling fresh fruits and vegetables and making notes
for his shows and columns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
