<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     08-03 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Assails Bush, Kemp Urges Blacks To Join GOP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush was hailed before the National Urban
League by Rep. Jack Kemp as a friend of blacks, while Jesse Jackson
assailed the vice president for failing to address many social
challenges facing the nation.
   Kemp, a New York congressman who bowed out of the Republican
presidential chase earlier this year, told about 300 Urban League
members Tuesday that the GOP will be wooing black voters as
aggressively as the Democrats.
   ``George Bush is going to seek the votes of blacks,'' Kemp said,
telling the crowd to ``come home'' to a party that will rebuild the
inner city with incentives for entrepreneurs.
   ``We want you. We want you home,'' Kemp said.
   Jackson, speaking at a reception attended by about 150 league
members, accused Bush, the likely GOP presidential nominee, of
failing to rise to many social challenges as vice president.
   ``George Bush, at the hour of challenge, has never been there.
We needed someone to fight the war on drugs. George Bush was not
there. We needed someone to fight to extend the Voting Rights Act.
... In a real sense, George Bush has never been here,'' Jackson
said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Plank Pushed For GOP National Platform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New Jersey congressman is pushing to have
the platform adopted at the Republican National Convention include
a plank that reflects a commitment to equality and the civil rights
movement.
   Republican Rep. James Courter said Tuesday he has drafted a
proposed plank that addresses housing issues, discrimination,
inner-city businesses and welfare.
   ``The Republican Party of Lincoln was founded to be the party of
natural rights and civil rights, the party to fulfill the meaning
of the Declaration of Independence when it says that all human
beings have an equal right to life, liberty and pursuit of
happiness,'' Courter said.
   ``I believe Republicans must show that we are serious when we
talk about the politics of inclusion,'' Courter said. ``Above all,
I believe Republicans should do it because it is morally right.''
</TEXT>
