<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Gandhi     08-03 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Gandhi,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Throws Out One Conviction In Gandhi Slaying; Upholds Two</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today threw out the
conviction and death sentence of a former security official in the
assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi and ordered him
released immediately.
   But the three-judge panel upheld the convictions and death
sentences of two other Sikhs in the Oct. 31, 1984 killing.
   The court said prosecutors failed to prove conspiracy charges
against Balbir Singh, who was arrested more than a month after the
slaying, accepting the appeal of the former subinspector in Mrs.
Gandhi's security guard.
   But it rejected appeals by Satwant Singh, a police constable who
was one of Mrs. Gandhi's bodyguards, and Kehar Singh, a government
official.
   A trial court had sentenced all three men to death by hanging,
and the sentences were upheld by the New Delhi High Court.
   The Supreme Court is the final court of appeal in India, but the
condemned men can appeal to President Ramaswamy Venkataraman for
mercy.
   Satwant Singh and another bodyguard, Beant Singh, shot Mrs.
Gandhi to death in the garden of her New Delhi residence. Beant
Singh, also a Sikh, was shot and killed by other security guards
just after the assassination.
   ``The manner in which she (Mrs. Gandhi) was mercilessly attacked
... repels any consideration of reduction in the sentence of
Satwant Singh,'' said Justice G.L. Oza, the senior judge on the
panel.
   ``In this view of the matter, even the conspirator who inspired
the persons who actually acted, does not deserve any leniency in
the matter of sentence,'' he said.
   Prosecutors had proved charges of conspiracy against Kehar
Singh, the maternal uncle of Beant Singh, he said.
   The three defendants are not related. ``Singh,'' which means
lion in the Punjabi language, is part of every Sikh male's name by
doctrine of the minority faith.
   The Supreme Court was ringed by policemen wielding automatic
rifles to prevent any attacks by Sikh terrorists. Visitors to the
courtroom were frisked and forced to pass through a metal detector.
   ``I am very pleased with the judgement,'' Swaran Singh, the
brother of Balbir Singh, said outside the court. ``They caught an
innocent man, but now justice has been done.''
   The chief defense lawyer, Ram Jethmalani, was not present. But
his daughter, Rani, who is also his junior partner, said: ``The
court has vindicated us.
   ``Balbir Singh was just roped in by the overzealousness of the
police with the collusion of the government,'' she said. ``The Sikh
community should feel that finally the Supreme Court has given them
some justice.''
   Mrs. Gandhi was slain in revenge for an Indian army raid on the
Sikhs' Golden Temple in Amritsar the previous June. At least 1,200
people died in the attack, most of them Sikhs.
   The slaying triggered anti-Sikh riots in New Delhi and other
northern cities in which more than 2,000 people were killed. Most
of the victims were Sikhs. Mrs. Gandhi's son, Rajiv Gandhi,
succeeded her as prime minister.
   Sikh radicals have been fighting since 1982 for a separate state
in the northern Indian state of Punjab, where Amrisar is located.
   They say Sikhs are discriminated against by Hindus, who are more
than 80 percent of India's 800 million people. Sikhs form about 2
percent of the population but are a majority in Punjab.
   The army raid on the Golden Temple, Sikhism's holiest shrine,
was meant to drive out Sikh radicals who took refuge there.
   The militant movement has grown, and more than 1,600 people have
been killed this year in attacks blamed on Sikh militants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
