<1ST_LINE>r p PM-MissouriPrimary     08-03 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missouri Primary,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearnes, Amendment to Make Missouri More Lucrative Gain Voters'
Approval</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Primaries Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN BALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Betty Hearnes, who once occupied the
governor's mansion as first lady, now has an opportunity to return
as the state's chief executive, while voters also approved making
the state's lottery more lucrative.
   Former Democratic presidential hopeful Richard Gephardt easily
won the party nomination for a seventh term in Congress, while farm
activist Wayne Cryts earned a chance for a rematch against
Republican Rep. Bill Emerson.
   Mrs. Hearnes won overwhelmingly in Tuesday's Democratic primary
and now faces Republican Gov. John Ashcroft in November's election.
   With 97 percent of precincts reporting, Mrs. Hearnes had 368,390
votes, or 81 percent, and Lavoy ``Zaki'' Reed, a St. Louis-area
teacher, had 84,123 votes, or 19 percent.
   ``I think you can say it's a new era for the Democratic Party,''
said Mrs. Hearnes, whose husband, Warren, served as governor from
1965 to 1973. ``We're excited because we intend to win it all. They
(Republicans) can sit home and talk about a sweep, but we'll be out
working and winning.''
   Ashcroft had no primary opposition as he bids for a second term.
   On the lottery amendment with 96 percent of precincts reporting,
455,068 voters, or 57 percent, had voted in favor and 337,182, or
43 percent, voted against the amendment.
   The amendment removed restrictions that now limit the lottery to
spending 45 percent on prizes, 45 percent on the state and 10
percent on administrative costs.
</TEXT>
