<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0559EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico     08-03 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governing Party Brings In New Blood After Election Losses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing party chose a young political
scientist as its general secretary in what appeared to be the
beginning of a major leadership shakeup after a poor showing in
recent elections.
   At a carefully planned meeting Tuesday night, the Institutional
Revolutionary Party party's national executive committee accepted
the resignation of veteran Humberto Lugo Gil and unanimously named
Manuel Camacho Solis to replace him.
   Camacho Solis, 42, is a close friend and associate of victorious
presidential candidate Carlos Salinas de Gortari. His selection
followed a promise by Salinas to modernize and streamline the
party, which has been in power in Mexico since it was founded in
1929.
   Camacho Solis promised in his acceptance speech to bring new
blood to the party leadership, which has been little more than a
closed club of politicians.
   Salinas, 40, won the presidential election July 6 with about 50
percent of the vote. But for the first time in decades, he was
strongly challenged by two opposition candidates _ Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas of the leftist National Democratic Front coalition and
Manuel J. Clouthier of the conservative National Action Party.
   Cardenas, who came in second, and Clouthier, in third place,
claim widespread fraud and have challenged the returns of the
presidential and House and Senate elections, which were held
simultaneously.
   The Federal Election Commission and the Election Tribunal, which
oversaw the balloting, rejected most of the opposition complaints,
and Congress is expected to proclaim Salinas president-elect in
September. He is to succeed President Miguel de la Madrid for a
six-year term Dec. 1.
   But the accusations of fraud sparked widespread irritation among
voters. It was also the first time the governing party won a major
election with less than 70 percent of the vote.
   Also for the first time, the party lost its absolute control of
the Senate. Cardenas' coalition won four of the upper chamber's 64
seats.
   A few days after the election, Salinas said that ``the time of a
one-party system in Mexico is over'' and said his party will have
to learn to live with a growing opposition and compete harder in
honest elections.
   Lugo Gil ostensibly resigned because his native state of Hidalgo
elected him to a Senate seat. But his replacement was viewed as
following Salinas' wish to fill key posts within the party and his
administration with people who share his views.
   Camacho Solis said, ``It is vital that we appear before society
practising an open-door policy for all, not for members of the ...
party, but for the whole of society.''
</TEXT>
