<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-Train 1stLd-Writethru a0508 08-03 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Train, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0508,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Illinois Central's Foresight Helps It Profit During Drought</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 1 graf with water level of Mississippi rising</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought-Heat, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought has kept the mighty Mississippi from
rolling along, but it's helped profits roll in for Illinois Central
Railroad thanks to the troubles of its rival barge haulers, the
railroad's chairman said.
   While barges have been stranded in shallow water, the Illinois
Central, whose tracks have paralleled the river for 137 years, has
been chugging along, bringing grain and coal from Illinois to the
South.
   ``This is probably the first time since the railroad started in
1851 that we've made a profit in July, and we're off to a rather
rousing start in August,'' Harry J. Bruce, chairman and chief
executive of the railroad, said Tuesday.
   He attributed his company's success to an ``educated gamble.''
   Last spring, before the full impact of the drought was felt in
the Midwest, the railroad hired weather forecasters and other
consultants to study Mississippi River water levels, Bruce said.
   After the consultants concluded the drought would make the year
difficult for barge operators who depend on deep water to move
their towboats, the railroad began stockpiling rail cars and other
equipment.
   The Illinois Central spent $700,000 to lease about 600 cars _
primarily covered hopper cars to handle grain _ from as far away as
Canada, Bruce said. Its fleet increased by almost 20 percent in
July, a traditionally slow month for the railroad.
   ``It was a reasoned, educated gamble, and it has paid off
handsomely,'' said Bruce. ``We keep a close eye on what's going on
on the river because it's a main competitive force for us.''
   The railroad's operating income for the second quarter of 1988
was $20 million, compared with $12 million for the period last
year, or a 67 percent increase.
   Joseph Farrell, president of the American Waterways Operators,
said Monday that drought conditions on the Mississippi will cause
the inland barging companies to lose $150 million to $200 million
in revenue between June 15 and Sept. 30.
   In July, the Illinois Central moved 71,075 carloads of freight,
a 12 percent increase over last year, Bruce said. The biggest
increase was in corn and soybean shipments, which totaled 10,221
cars in July compared with only 5,995 cars in July 1987.
   Coal shipments were up by 48.2 percent and chemical shipments by
8 percent for the same period.
   Bruce said the railroad plans to keep its leased cars, at least
into the early part of next year. The railroad's consultants
predict the low river levels will last into the winter, causing ice
jams to form earlier than usual and spread even farther down the
river than normal, Bruce said.
   The current low water levels reflect a 10-year trend in which
the Mississippi has dropped steadily due to reduced snowfalls and
rain, he added.
   ``We've seen for some time now that Ol' Man River hasn't been
rolling along so well.''
   Even so, the U.S. Geological Survey reported that the
Mississippi's water level jumped a surprising 10 percent in the
Twin Cities area in only five hours Tuesday, the result of rainfall
in northern Minnesota during the past few days.
</TEXT>
