<1ST_LINE>r p PM--MichiganPrimary     08-03 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM--Michigan Primary,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-congressman Gains Comeback Bid from Michigan Primary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Primaries Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters resurrected the political career of a
millionaire ex-congressman, while a congressman who boasted about
his certainty of victory wound up winning by a smaller margin than
expected in the Michigan primary.
   Jim Dunn, who served one term in Congress then lost 1982, 1984
and 1986 bids for a return to Washington, won the Republican
Party's nomination for U.S. Senate by defeating another millionaire
one-term congressman, Robert Huber.
   The prize: the right to take on Democratic Sen. Donald Riegle,
who hasn't lost an election in 22 years.
   Voters on Tuesday also put on the books a statute prohibiting
casinos within Detroit city limits if they ever are legalized by
the state Legislature.
   In the only lively congressional race, Democrat George Crockett
had a close call in his bid for renomination.
   With 50 percent of the vote counted, Crockett edged Detroit City
Councilwoman Barbara-Rose Collins, 46 percent to 40 percent, in a
four-person race.
   Collins ran an aggressive campaign, criticizing the eight-year
incumbent as a do-little, out-of-touch legislator who failed to
improve conditions for residents of the district.
   Crockett bragged that he was so sure of victory he didn't open a
campaign office and didn't make a single campaign speech.
   Dunn, whose margin of victory was 61 percent to 39 percent, was
equally confident.
   ``We started the fall campaign in February,'' he said. ``We said
all along that our target was Don Riegle.''
   Dunn's road to victory was paved with his own money and a change
in tactics.
   When he unsuccessfully ran for the Senate nomination in 1984, he
alienated voters with sharp attacks on his opponent and alienated
party regulars by condemning their support of ex-astronaut Jack
Lousma. In 1986, he ran a hard-nosed campaign against Democratic
Rep. Robert Carr, earning him the epithet ``junkyard dog.''
   He began his 1988 Senate bid by announcing there was a ``new Jim
Dunn'' who would take the high road in campaigning. And he made an
effort to make peace with the party activists and contributors he
had castigated four years earlier.
   His efforts, and the belief that Huber was too conservative to
unseat Riegle, earned Dunn the endorsements of virtually every
prominent Republican in the state.
   Huber attracted the only real attention of the primary race with
his declaration on acquired immune deficiency syndrome: ``If it
isn't the wrath of God, it should be.''
</TEXT>
