<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Ellis,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Big Leaguer Claims Ignorance Of State Lobster Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLD SAYBROOK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former major-league baseball player
John Ellis, arrested last week on charges of illegally fishing for
lobsters, said he was ignorant of state lobstering laws and called
it ``stupidity on my part.''
   ``It's extremely embarrassing,'' Ellis, now a 39-year-old New
London real estate businessman, said Tuesday. ``I hope I can
restore my reputation in the community. I'm going to work hard at
it.''
   Without commenting directly on the charges filed against him by
the state Department of Environmental Protection, Ellis said he
``made some serious mistakes not knowing the full fish and game
laws. I didn't know about having pots marked. That's stupidity on
my part.''
   Neither Ellis nor his lawyer, Thomas Cloutier, would say how he
would plead when the case is heard Monday. But both pointed out
that Ellis can mail in a $2,650 fine without having to appear in
court.
   Ellis, who played for the New York Yankees, Cleveland Indians
and Texas Rangers during a 13-year career that ended in 1982, said
he also is distressed by the publicity his arrest has attracted.
