<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0609EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CraterLakeStudy     08-03 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crater Lake Study,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sub Prepped for First Look at Bottom of Crater Lake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRATER LAKE NATIONAL PARK, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A helicopter lifted a
one-man submarine to Wizard Island in the prelude to man's first
in-person look at the bottom of Crater Lake, the deepest lake in
the United States.
   ``This is a fantastic opportunity ... a once-in-a-lifetime
chance,'' Mark Buktenica, a National Park Service fish biologist
scheduled to dive in the Deep Rover submarine, said Tuesday.
   Three weeks of dives from Wizard Island were to begin today in
the 1,932-foot-deep lake, the centerpiece of Crater Lake National
Park in the Cascade Mountains.
   Scientists plan to look for evidence of hot-water vents on the
floor of the 20-square-mile lake. The dives are part of a study of
the lake and a decrease in the clarity of its water in recent years.
   Crater Lake, which was born by the explosion of Mount Mazama
nearly 7,000 years ago, is famous for its clear, cobalt-blue water.
   Scientists theorize vents below the bottom may be altering
clarity by stirring up sediment and plant life in the lake, which
has no inlet or outlet.
   The park service is also concerned that geothermal exploration
planned just outside the park boundary could affect lake water.
   The Deep Rover resembles a big glass ball with a recliner chair
inside. An operator sitting in the chair can maneuver the sub and
manipulate two robot arms while monitoring banks of switches and
instruments.
   Jack Dymond of Oregon State University said he and fellow
oceanographer Robert Collier will first look for small vents they
discovered last summer with a remote-control submarine.
   Collier, Dymond and Buktenica received one week of classroom
training and diving with the submarine at its home base in
Vancouver, British Columbia.
   Buktenica said that despite the sub's sophisticated appearance,
it's fairly easy to operate.
   ``It's only hard in the sense that there is a lot to remember.
You are monitoring your own life-support systems. But mainly I will
be collecting samples and browsing around the lake bottom,''
Buktenica said.
</TEXT>
