<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Angola-at-a-Glance     08-03 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Angola-at-a-Glance,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Facts And Figures On Angola</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Angola-Namibia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a thumbnail sketch of Angola, where South
Africa has proposed that a cease-fire in the 13-year-old civil war
begin on Aug. 10:
   TERRITORY: With 481,354 square miles in southeastern Africa,
Angola is the second-largest African country south of the Sahara.
But it has only 8 million people, most of them living in tribal
villages and rural areas.
   HISTORY: Portuguese settlers reached Angola in the 15th century
and ruled it as a colony until Angolan independence in 1975.
Virtually all the Portuguese fled at that time, leaving the country
more than 90 percent illiterate and woefully short of capital and
skilled workers.
   GOVERNMENT: The Marxist Popular Movement for the Liberation of
Angola, one of the guerrilla groups who fought the Portuguse, has
controlled the country since it seized Luanda, the capital, in
early 1976 with the help of Cuban troops. An estimated 50,000 Cuban
troops are aiding the Angolan government. President Eduardo dos
Santos has consistently refused negotiations with the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, known as UNITA, which
seeks a power-sharing agreement.
   REBELS: Jonas Savimbi's UNITA rebels fought the Portuguese until
they departed and now oppose the government. UNITA receives U.S.
and South African military aid. South Africa has an estimated 3,000
troops in Angola. UNITA says it controls about one-third of Angola
and claims widespread popular support.
   ECONOMY: Almost 200 oil wells in the Angolan enclave of Cabinda
supply more than 90 percent of the country's export earnings. U.S.
oil companies help run the petroleum fields. Cuban and Angolan
troops protect them from UNITA guerrillas, who use American weapons
in a bid to sabotage the facilities. Angola is also rich in
diamonds and has potential for mining other minerals including
uranium.
   REFUGEES: About 1.5 million Angolans have fled areas of fighting
and are registered as displaced persons in the country, according
to the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees. Neighboring Zambia has
given shelter to 97,000 Namibian refugees. A small number of
Angolan refugees are in Botswana.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880803-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0615EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Carver     08-03 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Carver,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Author, Poet Raymond Carver Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT ANGELES, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raymond Carver, a mill worker's son
who survived despair and drinking to become one of the nation's
leading writers of short fiction, has died of lung cancer. He was
50.
   ``He died very nobly,'' said his brother-in-law, Douglas Unger,
a creative writing professor at Syracuse University. ``He didn't
let on how bad his condition was.''
   Carver died at his home Tuesday of a disease that was diagnosed
after he completed his last short story collection, ``Where I'm
Calling From.'' He underwent surgery last fall, according to
Newsweek magazine.
   About the time Carver's last book was issued this year by
Atlantic Monthly Press, he was named to the American Academy and
Institute of Arts and Letters in New York.
   His first collection, ``Will You Please Be Quiet, Please?,'' was
published in 1976 and nominated in 1977 for a National Book Award.
   In January 1983, Carver became the one of the first recipients
of the Mildred and Harold Strauss Livings Award, a renewable,
tax-free stipend of $35,000 a year for five years from the American
Academy and Institute of Arts and Letters.
   He was awarded a Wallace Stegner fellowship in 1972, a National
Endowment for the Arts fellowship in 1971, a Guggenheim Foundation
fellowship in 1979 and a 1987 Governor's Writers Award from Gov.
Booth Gardner. His works won O. Henry awards for best short story
in 1974, 1975 and 1980.
   His books include ``What We Talk About When We Talk About Love''
(1981), ``Cathedral'' (1983), ``Fires'' (1983) and a poetry
collection, ``Ultramarine'' (1986).
   He recently completed another poetry collection, ``A New Path to
the Waterfall,'' Unger said.
   A native of Clatskanie, Ore., Carver grew up in Yakima. His
father was a saw-filer in a lumber mill, his mother an occasional
waitress or retail clerk.
   He took a correspondence course in writing while in high school.
After graduating in 1956, he worked for six months at a sawmill and
the next year married Maryann Burk. They later divorced.
   Carver moved to California in 1958, took an introductory
fiction-writing course from the late author John Gardner,
transferred to Humboldt State and earned his undergraduate degree
in 1963.
   After attending the University of Iowa from 1963 to 1964, he
worked for three years as a night janitor at a Sacramento hospital
and wrote during the day.
   ``I thought that he was dead in the early '70s,'' Unger said.
``He was as close to death from drinking as anyone I ever knew.
   ``He went 18 years ... unrecognized by the literary world. He
despaired and went through a period of really hard drinking. He
couldn't take the discouragement.
   ``Then a miracle happened _ he called it a miracle _ that
someone discovered his work.''
   Carver once said he did not believe fiction had to bring about
personal, moral or social change.
   ``It just has to be there for the fierce pleasure we take in
doing it. ... Something that throws off these sparks _ a persistent
and steady glow, however dim.''
   Carver taught writing at various schools and was an English
professor three years until 1983 at Syracuse University. His wife,
poet and short story writer Tess Gallagher, is on leave from her
teaching job at Syracuse.
   They lived in this northern Olympic Penninsula town from
December through August each year.
   In addition to Ms. Gallagher, survivors included his mother, son
and daughter.
   A graveside service was scheduled here Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
