<DOCNO> AP880803-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0615EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     08-03 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Destructive Thunderstorms in Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms rumbled over much of the United States today after
slashing Texas and the East with hail as big as golf balls and
winds up to 70 mph which destroyed barns and flooded a Utah town.
   Along with damaging thunderstorms Tuesday, scorching heat
snapped or tied temperature records for the date in 26 cities in 12
states.
   Thunderstorms lingered today in central Texas. Widely scattered
showers and thunderstorms also lingered in the upper Ohio Valley
and the Southeast.
   Widely scattered thunderstorms and showers extended from upper
Michigan to southern Iowa and from the central High Plains to
Nevada. Fair skies prevailed across the rest of the nation.
   On Tuesday, thunderstorms in north central Texas destroyed or
damaged barns, broke windows, downed trees and power lines, and
damaged or destroyed outhouses. Gusts of 70 mph were recorded in
Lubbock, and Kerrville got 3 inches of rain in only an hour.
   In Escalante, Utah, more than 2 inches of rain fell in half an
hour, flooding basements and overwhelming the town's new sewer
system.
   ``It was really something,'' said Police Chief Kent Robinson.
``You could have had a boat down Main Street, no problem.''
   In Georgia, thunderstorms downed trees in Douglas County and
winds gusting to 60 mph at Atlanta's Fulton County Airport.
   Thunderstorms dropped golf ball-size hail on West Virginia, and
downed trees or power poles in parts of that state and western
Pennsylvania.
   Temperature records up to 98 years old were broken or tied in
Iowa, Minnesota, Wisconsin, Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Ohio, West
Virginia, North Carolina, South Carolina, Tennessee and New York.
   It was 102 degrees in Alpena, Mich., where the old record for
the date of 84 was set in 1987 and 98 in Milwaukee, where the mark
of 96 had stood since 1890.
   The nation's high Tuesday was 109 degrees at Bullhead City, Ariz.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
along a stationary front from northern Utah to Wyoming, the
northern Plains, Minnesota, and northern sections of the upper
Great Lakes, with thunderstorms in North Dakota; showers and
thunderstorms in Florida, the eastern Gulf Coast and Alabama, north
central and southwest Texas; the mountains of central New Mexico;
southwest Colorado; and central Arizona; and showers in parts of
Maine.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 70s and 80s along the
California coast, and in the Pacific Northwest, the northern and
central Rockies, the northern Plains, northern Minnesota and
northern Maine; between 95 and 105 degrees over parts of the
central Plains, middle Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes and the
Ohio Valley; between 100 to 110 degrees in the desert Southwest and
the California valleys; and in the 90s in the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 51
degrees at North Bend, Ore., to 93 degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 75 foggy; Boston 75 hazy; Buffalo 79 partly
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 78 fair; Cincinnati 76 fair; Cleveland 70
fair; Detroit 79 fair; Miami 83 fair; New York 75 fair;
Philadelphia 76 foggy; Pittsburgh 71 fair; Portland, Maine 69
foggy; Washington 77 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 71 cloudy; Chicago 82 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
78 partly cloudy; Denver 76 partly cloudy; Des Moines 80 fair;
Indianapolis 76 foggy; Kansas City 81 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 71
partly cloudy; Nashville 72 foggy; New Orleans 76 fair; St. Louis
81 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 72 partly cloudy; Anchorage 53 partly cloudy;
Las Vegas 91 windy; Los Angeles 66 fair; Phoenix 93 fair; Salt Lake
City 71 cloudy; San Diego 69 cloudy; San Francisco 62 fair; Seattle
67 fair.
   _Canada: Toronto 75 hazy.
</TEXT>
