<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0706EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-SovietInspections     08-03 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Inspections,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inspection Teams To Visit Maryland, Oklahoma, Florida</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet inspectors today will visit current or
former missile facilities in Oklahoma, Maryland and Florida as part
of the procedure set up to verify arms reductions required under a
new U.S.-Soviet treaty, a Pentagon official said.
   Cmdr. Kendall Pease, spokesman for the U.S. On-Site Inspection
Agency set up under the treaty, said the Soviets notified U.S.
officials early today they would visit facilities at Cape
Canaveral, Fla.; Lawton, Okla.; and Middle River, Md.
   Three teams of 10 Soviet inspectors were expected to leave the
Washington area at midmorning for inspections of up to 24 hours
that could be extended by an additional eight hours if both sides
agree, Pease said.
   The Soviets were to notify the Pentagon later today of a fourth
inspection site. The Redstone Arsenal at Huntsville, Ala., was the
only other site available under the treaty, Pease said.
   Pease said the inspection teams, which arrived in Washington on
Monday, are expected to return to Washington on Thursday.
   In Maryland, the inspectors planned to visit a Martin Marietta
plant just outside Baltimore where missile launchers once were
produced. In Florida, they were to visit a former Army and Air
Force missile testing facility. In Oklahoma, the destination was an
Army base where missiles are housed.
   The Soviets completed two rounds of inspections at U.S.
facilities earlier this year.
   The inspections are called for under the Intermediate-range
Nuclear Forces treaty, signed by President Reagan and Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev at the Washington summit in December. The
treaty calls for the elimination of all intermediate-range missiles
within three years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880803-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0711EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Zeffirelli-Scorsese     08-03 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zeffirelli-Scorsese,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zeffirelli Demands Rescheduling Of Scorsese Film</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Director Franco Zeffirelli said today he will not
present his film ``Young Toscanini'' at the Venice Film Festival
unless the screening of Martin Scorsese's ``The Last Temptation of
Christ'' is rescheduled.
   The two films are due to be shown one day after the other, with
Scorsese's movie coming first on Sept. 7.
   ``I want more distance between the two films,'' he said in a
telephone interview with The Associated Press. ``I don't want to be
caught up in the fights, the storm, the polemics that will follow
the screening of Scorsese's film.
   ``It is a question of scheduling, and I put scheduling as a
condition'' for the presentation of ``Young Toscanini,'' he said.
   Zeffirelli, who directed the television mini-series ``Jesus of
Nazareth'' several years ago, added that his new film might not be
ready for Venice anyway because of ``technical reasons.''
   ``My film is not ready yet and in order to have it completed in
time for presentation at the festival there would have to be great
enthusiasm,'' Zeffirelli said. ``But enthusiasm has grown fainter
because of this recent controversy.''
   Zeffirelli said Scorsese's film is ``damaging to the image of
Christ. ... He cannot be made the object of low fantasies.''
   Scorsese's film also has prompted criticism from the Christian
Democrats, the dominant group in Italy's five-party government
coalition, for the portrayal of Jesus Christ fantasizing about
making love to Mary Magdalene.
   The film has also provoked pickets and protests in the United
States.
   Zeffirelli's ``Young Toscanini'' stars American C. Thomas Howell
as the conductor as a young man. Elizabeth Taylor plays a
supporting role.
   Both films are scheduled to be shown in the ``special events''
division, which is outside the competition category for films
eligible for the Golden Lion award.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
