<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0826EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-US     08-03 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-US,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Ignores Another World Court Deadline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has
ignored a deadline set by the World Court to determine how much the
United States should pay in war reparations to Nicaragua, a court
spokesman said today.
   In what was seen as another snub to the World Court, the
judicial branch of the United Nations, the U.S. government breached
the July 29 deadline to present its position in the case, which it
has been boycotting since 1984.
   ``The time limit ... has lapsed without the receipt of any
communication from the government of the United States,'' the
spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   He said the court would now consider the next step in the
procedure.
   Nicaragua's ambassador to the Netherlands, who represents his
nation at the World Court, could not be reached for comment. An
embassy spokeswoman told The Associated Press that ``all diplomats
involved in the case are currently on holiday in Managua.'' She
refused to give her name.
   The reparations procedure grew out of a 1986 World Court ruling
ordering the United States immediately to halt all support to the
Contra rebels fighting Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government.
   The ruling followed a 1984 complaint by Managua that the United
States was involved in attempts to overthrow the Nicaraguan
government. The court said Nicaragua was entitled to reparations,
but it did not indicate the amount.
   Instead, it ordered both parties in the dispute to negotiate a
settlement on the issue and said it would intervene only if such
talks failed.
   The Reagan administration, which said in 1984 that the World
Court has no jurisdiction in the dispute, has refused to consider
paying reparations to Nicaragua.
   In November, the court opened proceedings to establish the
amount of reparations Nicaragua would be entitled to. A month
later, John Shad, the U.S. ambassador to the Netherlands, sent a
letter to the court repeating the administration's position that
the court has no authority in the case.
   That letter was the last official communication received by the
court from the U.S. government, the court spokesman said.
   Managua has never stated how much it is seeking in compensation,
but Sandinista officials privately have estimated the economic
damage from the Contra war at $250 million to $300 million.
   Nicaragua's arguments in the reparations case were filed in
March. Under the court's statutes, they are not to be made public
before hearings are held on the issue. It was not immediately clear
whether the court was planning a public procedure.
   The court, officially known as the International Court of
Justice, has no enforcement powers and depends on voluntary
compliance with its rulings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880803-0088 </DOCNO>
