<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MedflyEradication     08-03 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Medfly Eradication,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Million Sterile Fruit Flies Released in Second Phase of
Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four million sterilized Mediterranean fruit
flies flooded a 16-square-mile area in the second stage of a
campaign to eradicate the threat to California's $14 billion-a-year
farm industry.
   The male flies, the first of a total of 20 million to be freed
through Friday, were released Tuesday by airplane and from
cardboard buckets by truck.
   The sterile flies, dyed fluorescent pink, will cause the
Medflies to breed themselves out of existence, said Robert Donley,
deputy director of the county Agriculture Commission.
   Last week, the suburban San Fernando Valley area was bombarded
with aerial and ground applications of the pesticide malathion
after six Medflies were found in traps.
   ``If there are any viable flies that emerge they will mate with
sterile flies and there will be no offspring,'' Donley said.
   The sterile flies' pink color is invisible to the eye but shows
up under a special light, Donley said.
   The Medfly lays eggs in more than 250 varieties of fruits and
vegetables. The flies are usually brought in from Hawaii on fruit
carried in by tourists.
   No new flies were found Monday or Tuesday, but inspectors
continued to monitor traps in trees.
   Flies will be released weekly for about two months _ about 20
million each week _ to cover two potential generations of Medflies,
said Donley. The average lifespan of a Medfly is about a month.
   The use of sterile flies helped eradicate a Medfly infestation
last summer in eastern Los Angeles County.
   The San Fernando Valley is about a 100-square-mile area that
includes a number of suburbs northwest of Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
