<HEAD>23 Reported Killed In Plane Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Soviet consul and two
Yugoslavs killed. Picks up 10th pvs, `It was...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bulgarian airliner crashed into a river
while trying to take off from an airport in Sofia, and at least 23
people were killed, including a Soviet diplomat, Bulgarian news
media said today.
   The YAK-40 propeller-driven plane of the state Balkan Airlines
crashed Tuesday while leaving the Bulgarian capital on a flight to
Varna on the Black Sea, the official Bulgarian news agency BTA said.
   The agency said a consul at the Soviet consulate general in
Varna and two Yugoslavs were among the dead. It identified the
Soviet as Yuri Evgeniyevich Cheryomin, 38.
   The Yugoslavs were identified as Momirka Radka Mitrovic, 21, and
her 1-year-old daughter, Maria. There were 33 passengers and four
crew members on board, the reports said.
   Diplomatic sources, reached by telephone from Vienna, said the
official Communist Party daily Rabotnichesko Delo reported that the
plane failed to take off, rolled off the runway and crashed into
the Iskar River about a mile east of the airport. They said the
cause of the accident was not known.
   The newspaper said 12 people were hospitalized.
   The agency said 14 people were hospitalized and the rest of the
37 people on board were killed.
   The newspaper report indicated two more people may have died
later, which would raise the total killed to 25.
   It was believed to be the worst Bulgarian air disaster since the
crash of a TU-134 aircraft of the Bulgarian airline in January
1984. All 50 people on board were killed when it crashed on landing
at Sofia airport after a flight from East Berlin.
   In March 1978, a Balkan aircraft en route from Sofia to Warsaw
crashed and killed 73 people.
