<HEAD>Teen-ager Says She Was Turned Away Because of Pink and Purple Hair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Beverly Hills teen-ager told a judge
she was barred from Disneyland because her hair was pink and purple.
   ``They don't know what the person's like. It's just not fair,''
Tonya Slobod said Tuesday.
   Superior Court Judge Tully Seymour, after the non-jury trial,
did not immediately rule on her request to find that her civil
rights were violated.
   Miss Slobod wants him to impose a maximum $250 fine under state
civil rights law plus $2,200 in legal fees and unspecified punitive
damages.
   Miss Slobod said she was 14 in 1986 when she was treated to a
trip to the theme park by her grandmother, Gladys Egelko. She said
a security guard stopped her at a turnstile.
   ``He said, `Well, your hair is multicolored and will detract
from our shows,''' Miss Slobod said. She said employees offered to
let her in if she would cover her head with a cap of some kind. She
said she refused and left.
   James Rettie, security supervisor for the park, confirmed
Disneyland has a policy of excluding guests so garish in appearance
that they detract from shows. But he testified that a guest would
not be excluded on hair color alone.
   Disneyland attorney Richard Claire said that the amusement park
has no record of their visit and that even if they did come to the
Anaheim park, Disneyland employees must have behaved legally in
barring Miss Slobod.
   Ms. Egelko produced Disneyland parking stubs as evidence that
the girl visited the park.
   The teen-ager since has abandoned exotic tints in favor of her
hair's natural brown.
</TEXT>
