<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TrainCrash     08-03 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Train Crash,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators: One Train Left Early</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY TABOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two freight trains collided head on 16
minutes before one was scheduled to leave its yard, according to
investigators. The fiery crash killed two crewmen and forced
evacuation of 2,000 residents.
   Iowa Interstate Railroad also told investigators that two
tankers containing 20,000 gallons of denatured alchool each should
have been at the end of the westbound train that burst into flames
after the crash near Altoona on Saturday. The tankers were the
second and third cars.
   Edward Dobranetski of the National Transportation Safety Board
declined to speculate whether the correct placement of the two
tankers would have prevented a fire.
   Surviving crew members from the eastbound train said they
believed they left the Altoona switching yard early, said Edward
Dobranetski of the National Transportation Safety Board.
   The crash occurred at 11:45 a.m., while the train had been
ordered by the company to stay in the yard until 12:01 p.m.,
Dobranetski said.
   However, he said, investigators are trying to determine whether
the train had actually left the yard because there were no signs
defining its limits.
   Federal investigators plan to conclude their on-site
investigation Friday by determining the distance between the trains
when they spotted one another.
   The investigator said urine and blood tests to determine whether
crew members used drugs or alcohol will be completed in several
weeks.
   Residents were allowed to return home Monday after workers
allowed the alcohol to burn off. The tracks were reopened Tuesday.
</TEXT>
