<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 1020EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Statue 1stLd-Writethru a0555 08-03 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Statue, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0555,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Museum's Rare Greek Statue May Have Been Stolen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 3rd graf pvs, ``Henley said...'' to
UPDATE with Italian official confirming probe, Subs 1 graf for 8th
graf pvs, ``In a... to CONFORM. Pickup 9th graf pvs, ``I have...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators are checking whether a rare Greek
statue bought by the J. Paul Getty Museum was taken from an illegal
archeological dig in Sicily, an Interpol official said today.
   Gordon Henley, director of the international art theft unit for
Interpol, said Italian authorities notified the Paris-based
international police agency on Tuesday that they were looking into
the origin of the statue, on display since last week at the museum
in Malibu, Calif.
   Henley said the Italian investigators reported in a cable that
they believe the 7-foot-6-inch statue, dating from the 5th century
B.C., was ``probably obtained from an illegal excavation in
Morgantina, Agrigento, Sicily.''
   In Rome, a senior official of the special Carabinieri art theft
squad today said the team has been investigating the origin of the
statue for a month.
   The probe was requested by Graziella Fiorentini, the
government's director of cultural affairs in Agrigento, said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. Miss Fiorentini
could not immediately be reached for comment.
   ``The Carabinieri are investigating all over Italy, and Interpol
is investigating too, in order to find out who sold the statue to
the Getty Museum,'' said the official. ``Once the Carabinieri
discover something, magistrates will be immediately informed.''
   Interpol's role is limited to waiting for Italian police to
confirm their belief that the statue was stolen, then relaying the
information to police in the United States, Henley said.
   The statue, believed to represent Nike, Aphrodite or Hera, was
described last week when it was put on display as the only such
full-size figure to have survived intact and the most remarkable
ancient sculpture to appear on the art market in years.
   The Getty Museum declined to say from whom it bought the work or
how much it paid, but said it tried to determine whether either
Italy or Greece had a claim to the statue.
   Henley said Interpol first became involved last week when it was
tipped by Connoisseur Magazine, whose editor-in-chief, Thomas
Hoving, was investigating the Getty acquisition.
   
   In a copyright story Tuesday, the International Herald-Tribune
reported that Miss Fiorentini told Connoisseur she sent the Getty
Museum telegrams warning that she thought the statue was stolen.
   
   ``I have no concrete evidence the piece came from our site,''
Miss Fiorentini was quoted as saying. ``But I couldn't rule it out,
either. Above all, I did not want to say anything that could be
remotely construed as approval or consent.''
   The Herald-Tribune said Miss Fiorentini spoke to Connoisseur on
Saturday, and that the magazine made available its findings, to be
published in full in a series beginning with the October issue.
   The newspaper quoted Getty Museum spokeswoman Lori Starr as
saying the report came as a surprise.
   ``We made formal inquiries a year ago about the history of the
statue with the ministry in Rome via our lawyer there,'' she was
quoted as saying. ``This is something we're just going to have to
look into.''
   The newspaper quoted Ms. Starr as saying Getty policy was to
return an item to the country of origin if a valid legal claim is
established.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
