<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Irish 2ndLd-Writethru a0545 08-03 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Irish, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0545,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Gunmen Kill Part-Time Soldier</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with IRA claiming today's
killing, details on attack. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``On Tuesday...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Irish Republic Army today
stepped up its campaign against British security forces by gunning
down a part-time soldier as he drove to his civilian job near
Belfast.
   The IRA claimed responsibility in a statement to the news media.
IRA attacks this week alone have killed four people and injured 33.
   On Tuesday, the IRA warned civilians to avoid British soldiers,
the primary target of its battle to end British rule in the
province. Since November, the IRA has killed 17 civilians in
botched attacks.
   In today's assault, a member of the British army's locally
recruited Ulster Defense Regiment, was gunned down in his car as he
slowed to cross a narrow bridge outside Cookstown, 40 miles west of
Belfast, police said.
   He was driving to work at an engineering plant.
   The 31-year-old victim, who was shot several times in the head,
died later in South Tyrone hospital, said a spokesman for the Royal
Ulster Constabulary, the province's police force. The spokesman
demanded anonymity.
   News reports said the guerrillas drove to the ambush point in a
car stolen from a family of five people who were held hostage
overnight.
   On Tuesday, an IRA bomb exploded under a car in a busy shopping
area in Lisburn near Belfast, killing a policeman and injuring 18
bystanders.
   About 20 minutes later, a part-time soldier was killed in front
of his wife and 2-year-old daughter after two IRA gunmen dragged
him from a Belfast store during a family shopping trip.
   Earlier Tuesday, six part-time soldiers in the mainly Protestant
Ulster Defense Regiment, were hurt when an IRA land mine blew up
their Land Rover in the County Tyrone village of Carland.
   Tuesday's attacks came a day after an IRA explosion tore through
a British army postal sorting center in north London, killing one
soldier and injuring nine.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA, which claimed responsibility for
the attacks, is fighting to unite this predominantly Protestant
province with the Irish Republic under socialist rule.
   Brian Feeny, a Belfast council member from the moderate Catholic
Social Democratic and Labor Party, called Tuesday's attacks ``an
attempt by the IRA to put right its cock-ups by the tried and
tested method of killing off-duty policemen and (Ulster Defense
Regiment) men who are easy targets.''
   The IRA issued its warning on civilians Tuesday through the
Irish Republican publicity bureau in Dublin, Ireland.
   ``We are issuing this warning because the close presence of
civilians often forces us to abandon operations,'' it said. ``No
one should travel close to or with clearly identified members of
the British forces.''
   The statement said the warning applied throughout Europe.
   British news reports quoted unidentified Irish nationalist
sources in Belfast as saying the warning particularly applies to
civilians who frequent discotheques and pubs used by off-duty
military personnel.
   That aroused fears the guerrillas may be planning attacks
similar to two 1974 pub bombings in and around at London and a 1982
pub bombing near Londonderry, Northern Ireland's second-largest
city.
   The three bombings killed 15 soldiers and nine civilians and
injured about 150 people. The IRA claimed responsibility for the
1974 bombings. The Irish National Liberation Army, a Marxist
offshoot of the IRA, said it staged the 1982 attack.
   Monday's blast was the first fatal attack in mainland Britain
since IRA guerrillas blew up Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
hotel during a political convention in October 1984. She narrowly
escaped injury, but five people were killed.
   It was the fifth IRA attack since May on British military
targets outside Northern Ireland. Three British servicemen have
been killed and 12 other people injured in four machine gun and
bombing attacks in West Germany and the Netherlands.
   On March 6, British commandos shot and killed three unarmed IRA
guerrillas in Gibraltar.
   The 17 accidental civilian deaths forced the IRA to issue a
series of embarrassing apologies to relatives of the victims, two
of whom were from an IRA stronghold in west Belfast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
