<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Greece-US 1stLd-Writethru   08-03 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-US, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0591,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greeks Want U.S.Air Force Base near Athens Closed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to ADD details and background. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said today it will close
the U.S. Air Force base near the Greek capital when a defense
agreement between Greece and the United States expires at the end
of the year.
   Government spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos told a news briefing
that ``one of the decisions reached by the Greek government is the
abolition of Ellinikon Air Base.''
   Ellinikon Air Base is one of four major military installations
the United States operates in Greece. It is 10 miles from Athens.
   The U.S. Embassy refused comment.
   On Tuesday, a ranking government official said the Ellinikon
base would either be closed or stay as it is, ruling out its
transfer or merger with another American base on the southern Greek
island of Crete. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Ellinikon is a support base used by reconnaisance planes to
monitor Soviet fleet movements in the Mediterranean Sea.
   Negotiations for a new defense and cooperation agreement to
replace the existing accord are scheduled to resume Sept.9. The
current treaty expires Dec. 31.
   The Greek government issued a formal shutdown notice on July 13
for all U.S. bases operating in Greece, but it does not necessarily
mean that all the installations will stop operating.
   If Greek and American officials are unable to reach agreement,
the present accord gives the United States 17 months to dismantle
their bases when it expires.
   The official at the briefing Tuesday conceded that there have
been differences of opinion during the negotiations. He said Greece
``wants to safeguard its paramount national interests. This
however, does not mean guarantees for its eastern borders (with
Turkey) but some guarantees on the question of balance of forces.''
   Congress maintains a 7-to-10 rato in military assistance to
Greece and Turkey. The Greeks receive $7 for every $10 given to
Turkey.
   Greece and Turkey have longstanding differences, despite being
members of the Western Alliance. Disputes between the two countries
range from claims to mineral seabed rights in the Aegean to Cyprus,
the divided Mediterranean island republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
