<1ST_LINE>u a PM-YonkersDeseg     08-03 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yonkers Deseg,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Officials Meet Over City's Financial Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge suggested Gov. Mario Cuomo
remove members of Yonkers' City Council for voting down a
court-ordered housing desegregation plan, and a state board today
considered whether to take over the city's finances.
   U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand found the city and three
council members in contempt Tuesday and slapped the city with a
$100 fine that will double daily. The city's $337 million budget
would be wiped out by the 22nd day.
   A meeting of the Yonkers Financial Control Board was called for
this afternoon to prepare for another session on Thursday. The
board, appointed by Cuomo to oversee spending when Yonkers faced
bankruptcy four years ago, can take over the power to disburse
funds.
   ``We want Yonkers to work itself out of its problems,'' said
Bill Brown, spokesman for Secretary of State Gail Shaffer, who
heads the board. ``We'd rather that there be no control board at
all. But obviously this (the court decision) changes things
immensely.''
   Sand on Tuesday noted that the governor has the power to remove
elected officials for misconduct and malfeasance.
   ``When a city of almost 200,000 totters on the brink of
bankruptcy, makes itself a symbol of defiance to a federal court
and acts in a manner so devastatingly adverse to the interest of
its citizens,'' it is the state's responsibility to intervene, the
judge said.
   Tom Conroy, a spokesman for the governor, said that Cuomo's
office was monitoring the situation. Earlier, Cuomo had refused a
request from city officials to intervene on the city's behalf,
saying such action would be inappropriate.
   Brown said Shaffer has been in ``constant touch'' with Cuomo
aides about the situation.
   The desegregation plan was defeated 4-3. Three council members
who voted against the plan were fined $500 a day. The fourth had
his contempt proceeding delayed because he had no lawyer.
   Council members who refuse to endorse the plan face jail Aug. 11
unless they change their stand.
   Sand's action comes after two years of repeated threats against
the state's fourth-largest city for its failure to build low-income
and affordable housing. In 1985, the judge found the city liable
for intentionally segregating housing and schools over a 40-year
period.
   The precipitating action came Monday night when the City Council
refused to endorse a package of bonuses, financial incentives and
zoning variances to attract developers to build 800 units of
affordable housing throughout the city.
   The vote came after Sand warned the council that failure to pass
the resolution would result in fines and possible imprisonment.
Only those council members voting against the resolution were
subject to contempt.
   The fines against the city will be deposited into the U.S.
Treasury rather than in a separate account, meaning the fines will
be non-refundable, Sand said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
