<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru   08-03 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0605,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Official Says Hostage Deal in Works</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 7 grafs to ADD U.S. denial. Pick up 6th pvs, `In
the...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior PLO official said today that the
United States and Britain are in contact with Iran in efforts to
release Westerners held hostage by pro-Iranian groups in Lebanon.
   The United States denied it.
   ``There are American-British-Iranian contacts under way for
release of the hostages,'' said the PLO official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. The PLO has been informally allied in
Lebanon with the pro-Iranian Hezbollah militia.
   Hezbollah is believed to be an umbrella group for extremists
holding most of the 18 foreigners missing in Lebanon. The hostages
include nine Americans. The PLO official said he did not know where
the contacts were supposed to be taking place.
   ``I think this time it's serious because Iran is trying to win
over these Western powers by creating an impression it's not Iran
that's hardline, it's Iraq,'' he said in an interview with The
Associated Press.
   Iran and Iraq are trying to negotiate a cease-fire in their war.
The talks were deadlocked over Iraq's demand for direct talks.
   In Washington, a State Department official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the report was ``false.'' ``There are
no direct contacts between the United States and Iran,'' he said.
   In the past, U.S. and British officials have denied similar
reports about negotiations with Iran on the hostages.
   In Beirut, the conservative daily Al-Anwar reported today that
two British hostages and a West German, all held by pro-Iranian
Shiite Moslem kidnappers, will be released soon. The newspaper
quoted the privately-owned Al-Sohofiah newsletter as saying
``intense efforts have lately reached agreement on arrangements to
set the three hostages free in a short time.''
   The names of the three hostages were not reported. The
newsletter, which has not reported on the hostages before, quoted
unidentified sources.
   Among those missing, Anglican Church envoy Terry Waite and
journalist John McCarthy are both British, and university professor
Brian Keenan holds both British and Irish passports. British
journalist Alec Collett was reported killed in 1986, but no body
was ever found.
   The only West German hostage is businessman Rudolf Cordes.
   The hostage held longest is Terry A. Anderson, 40, chief Middle
East correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March
16, 1985.
</TEXT>
