<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 1121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Administrator'sSuicide     08-03 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Administrator's Suicide,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Official: Police Probe Of Man Who Killed Self Was Proper</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents of 8th graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-age girl who accused a school
administrator of sexual misconduct days before he committed suicide
did not recant, as her mother had claimed, police said.
   Douglas Tarrant was arrested on a charge of lewd and lascivious
behavior four days before he killed himself July 15 in the garage
of his Clearwater home. He left a videotape saying he was innocent
of the charge.
   The girl's mother said that the 15-year-old told police and
school officials her daughter had changed her story but that no one
told Tarrant. However, a state attorney's report released Monday by
the police disputed that. Police spokesman William Doniel said
newspaper stories ``gave the impression to the public that, `Why
didn't the detective contact the guy and tell him it wasn't true?''
   The state attorney's report ``was a way to ... make people aware
that she did not recant her story,'' Doniel said.
   The report called the girl ``a credible witness who was
straightforward in her responses, had an accurate memory and has no
(conflict of) interest in the outcome of this case.''
   The report also said Tarrant had a history of soliciting
teen-age girls for sexual acts.
   Tarrant was arrested after the girl called police and reported
that Tarrant asked her to get into his car. She said she could see
the man masturbating.
   Family members said that Tarrant probably took his own life
because of depression over severe health problems but that the
arrest added more stress on the Pinellas County school system's
assistant superintendent for finance.
   The mother denied the contention in the report that she
pressured the girl to recant.
   ``I did not pressure that child into changing her story,'' the
woman told the St. Petersburg Times. ``The police frightened her.
They're embarrassed because so many people were notified (the girl
changed her story), and they never told the man.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
