<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma-Future 2ndLd-Writethru a0516 08-03 0818</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma-Future, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0516,0843</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burma: From Frying Pan To Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with martial law in capital.
Pick up 6th pvs, `Virtually the...</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A brief moment of change in a Burma, a
country beset by a quarter century of authoritarian rule, appears
to have shattered with the emergence of a leader even more
hard-line than his predecessor, analysts say.
   Western diplomats, academics and Burmese emigres fear that the
already troubled Southeast Asian nation could more face civil
disorder in reaction to retired army general Sein Lwin's taking the
reins of power from Ne Win.
   The Burmese government today imposed martial law on the capital,
Rangoon. Diplomats said the order came after thousands of masked
students marched through downtown shouting slogans denouncing Sein
Lwin.
   A few days after Sein Lwin emerged as Burma's president and
ruling party chairman, authorities arrested Burma's most respected
dissident, Aung Gyi, and other potential leaders around whom
mounting opposition could have rallied.
   Leaflets have been circulating in Rangoon calling for Sein
Lwin's overthrow.
   Almost daily, peaceful demonstrations are being held by students
and some monks at the Shwedagon Pagoda, Burma's holiest shrine and
a traditional center for political protest.
   Today, saffron-robed Buddhist monks and large numbers of workers
joined students in the downtown demonstration, said Western
diplomats in Rangoon.
   Virtually the only optimistic note sounded by analysts is that
the new leaders will attempt some economic reforms while trying to
keep a lid on dissent that has boiled over into bloody street riots
three times since October.
   The short-lived expectations of change were sparked July 23 when
Ne Win, who had wielded power since seizing it in a coup 26 years
ago, resigned as chairman of the Burma Socialist Program Party.
   He also called for a referendum that could have replaced
one-party rule with a multi-party system. A special party congress
subsequently was held and proposals for major economic reforms were
debated.
   But just three days later _ and for reasons still unclear _ the
77-year-old chairman was replaced by Sein Lwin, who is widely held
responsible for ruthlessly suppressing student demonstrations in
March.
   The referendum was also turned down.
   Only the economic reform package remained, but some analysts
express skepticism about how far and how effectively it can be
implemented.
   ``I don't see any prospect for progress, but rather for
resistance, violence,'' says Robert Nathan, a Washington-based
economist who follows Burmese developments.
   ``In a place where there hadn't been any hope for change,
expectations were suddenly raised. Now, that's been dashed, down
the drain.''
   Whatever the changes at the top, the country is still run
day-to-day by several hundred active duty or retired military
officers, a group that over the past quarter century has turned
perhaps Southeast Asia's potentially richest nation into one with a
per capita income of less than $200.
   With little economic expertise at senior echelons, there is
skepticism whether the wide-ranging and complex economic reforms
proposed can be pushed through even if genuine political will
exists.
   The economic package includes allowing private foreign
investment for the first time since 1962 and sweeping privatization
of sectors previously controlled by the state.
   The slumping economy appears to have been a key fuel to tensions
and disillusionment widely expressed by people in Rangoon and
elsewhere.
   But some analysts also see recent changes as having heightened
the potential for internal discord.
   John Badgely, a Burma expert at Cornell University, said in an
interview that a past pattern is being duplicated: Ne Win perhaps
allowing a potential rival to rise only so high before cutting him
off.
   The American professor said Ne Win has opted for support from
more reform-minded military officers and those who have benefited
from the limited economic reforms he instituted last year, while
Sein Lwin represents the conservative old guard.
   Badgely foresees a possible confrontation between the two men if
Sein Lwin strikes out too far on his own.
   Others, however, believe an ailing and old Ne Win has simply
lost control of the situation and Sein Lwin has staged a kind of
coup against his former commander.
   Still others note that close bonds between the two go back to
the early 1940s, when the poorly educated Sein Lwin joined Ne Win's
outfit, the Fourth Burma Rifles, as a private.
   Sein Lwin served Ne Win as a personal aide and later as a
commander, when an iron fist was required. In 1962, the year Ne Win
seized power, Sein Lwin headed troops that put down a campus riot
in a hail of bullets.
   These analysts view recent events as a well-orchestrated plot by
the two in which the secretive Ne Win will now play a
behind-the-scenes role.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Denis Gray, bureau chief in Bangkok, Thailand,
has covered Southeast Asia for The Associated Press since the early
1970s.
</TEXT>
