<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua 2ndLd-Writethru   08-03 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0601,0746</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Attack Boat, Kill Two, Wound American Clergman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to CORRECT Walker's age to 57 and name of
river to Escondido. ADDS quote from information minister, no
comment from Contras. Pick up 11th graf pvs: `Witnesses said...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels fired mortars and rifles at a
crowded passenger boat on a remote southeastern river, killing two
people and wounding 27, the government and witnesses said. An
American clergyman was among the wounded.
   About a dozen members of a New York-based religious group were
on board the vessel when it was attacked. The wounded American was
identified as the Rev. Lucius Walker, a Baptist minister from
Demarest, N.J.
   Newspapers today ran banner headlines condemning the attack and
featured pictures of Walker.
   The government also accused the United States of trying to
thwart regional peace efforts through Secretary of State George P.
Shultz' visit to the region this week.
   ``Criminal Attack,'' the Sandinista government newspaper El
Nuevo Diario said. ``There Were Moments Of Terror,'' the Sandinista
National Liberation Front's paper Barricada said, quoting the
clergyman.
   Walker, 57, received stitches after a bullet grazed his buttocks.
   His daughter, Gail Walker, 29 of Patterson, N.J., said in a
telephone interview this morning that her father ``was O.K. He's
well.''
   The Defense Ministry said the passenger boat was attacked at 4
p.m. Tuesday as it traveled upstream on the Escondido River. It was
heading to the town of Rama after leaving the Caribbean port of
Bluefields.
   The ministry said in a communique that the raid occurred near
the village of El Mango, about 150 miles southeast of Managua.
   It said all the victims were civilians, but gave no other
details.
   ``Who is obstructing peace?'' Information Minister Manuel
Espinoza asked in a telephone interview today. ``It shows the
American administration, through the Contras, are continuing the
war.''
   In Miami, Contra spokesman Jorge Rosales said the rebels were
still gathering information on the incident and had no immediate
comment.
   Witnesses said about 200 civilians and several Sandinista
soldiers were aboard.
   ``The boat was crowded with passengers, among them women,
children and adults when it was attacked,'' said Walker.
   The river links the recently built Managua-Rama road with
Bluefields, where Nicaragua receives the bulk of its military
supplies from the Soviet Union, Cuba and other Soviet bloc nations.
   ``I dove down the stairs,'' Ms. Walker said. ``I figured bruises
were better than bullet holes. The bullets came through the walls.''
   Walker is executive director of the Inter-Religious Foundation
for Communication Organizations, an interdenominational group. Ms.
Walker, 29, is its communications programing director.
   ``As Americans we think its barbarous that our government arm
these people (the rebels),'' Walker said as a doctor patched up the
wound on his left buttock.
   Ms. Walker said about 20 Sandinista soldiers were on the top
deck when the attack occurred, but she said most of the Contra fire
was aimed at the section of the vessel where civilians were
standing.
   She said she and her father came to Nicaragua on July 26 with
the religious group, which does not support President Reagan's
Central American policy, ``to find out first hand the actual
situation of the country.
   ``Now we're all in agreement on condemning Contra aid. This was
a civilian boat,'' she added.
   No confirmation or claim of responsibility had surfaced by late
Tuesday from the U.S.-supported Contras, who have tried to cut the
Managua-Bluefields supply link several times.
   In January, they seized several towns and villages along the
Managua-Rama road to stop the supply flow but later retreated.
   Tuesday's attack violates a fragile cease-fire the two sides
agreed to March 23. Negotiations have since failed to forge a
lasting peace in the 7-year-old war, and Reagan is seeking to renew
military aid to the Contras, which Congress cut off in February.
   Meanwhile, the Sandinista newspaper Barricada said Shultz'
meeting in Guatemala Monday with the foreign ministers of Costa
Rica, Guatemala, El Salvador and Honduras marked ``a new level of
North American pressure and blackmail aimed at blocking the Central
American peace process.''.
   The United States sought but failed to obtain from the four
nations a statement denouncing Nicaragua on the grounds it has
failed to comply with a peace plan the five Central American
presidents signed one year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
