<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 1206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   08-03 0904</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0946</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: released now.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 2
   The Seattle Times on compensation for interned
Japanese-Americans:
   For thousands of Japanese-descent Americans in the Seattle area
and elsehwere across the nation, that long-dreamed-of event seems
near: Congress is poised to give final approval to a redress bill
that would provide some compensation to those remaining of the
120,000 such citizens who were interned during World War II. ...
   A most significant feature is the bill's apology to those loyal
Americans whose lives were terribly disrupted and who suffered
unjust economic and other punishment because of their origin.
   A spokesman for Rep. Mike Lowry, D-Seattle, an early champion of
the legislation, notes there is speculation that President Reagan
will eventually sign the bill, ``but do it very quietly.''
   To ``do it very quietly'' would be a mistake. Reagan should sign
the measure soon _ with a flourish and a declaration that the
United States is a nation that can acknowledge it once erred.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 30
   St. Petersburg (Fla.) Times on pollution control:
   Sen. Tim Wirth, D-Colo. summed up the fate of our hothouse
planet at a news conference held to promote new pollution control
legislation proposed recently:
   ``The evidence from the world's leading scientists is
compelling: As the Earth's atmosphere gets warmer, our global
climate is changing dramatically in ways that will seriously
disrupt nature and human society. ... We must change course.''
   The potentially disastrous global warming trend is caused by
gaseous pollution in the atmosphere, namely carbon dioxide released
by the burning of fossil fuels.
   Since the United States is the leading world offender, it is our
responsibility to act immediately by reducing wasteful energy
consumption and tightening energy standards for automobiles and
factory smokestacks.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 29
   Albuquerque (N.M.) Journal on President Aquino and Ferdinand
Marcos:
   Philippine President Corazon Aquino faces a tough decision.
Should she welcome former President Marcos home _ no questions
asked, no criminal charges leveled _ in exchange for an infusion of
$5 billion?
   Marcos also pledges an infusion of good will. His support for
the Aquino government would heal the rift between his compatriots
and the new regime, ushering in an era of national reconciliation,
according to Marcos' spokesman.
   Surely to deny his request would prolong the enmity between
Marcos partisans and Aquino supporters.
   Those appear to be powerful incentives, but one has to wonder if
the ex-president could support (Mrs.) Aquino, actually swinging his
still substantial political following behind a leader they perceive
as a usurper. Or does ``support'' translate to ``not actively
oppose''?
   What cannot survive, if this deal is cut, is the electorate's
faith in the integrity of government, any sense that government
officials are there to serve instead of loot.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 2
   The Baltimore Sun on Michael Dukakis' promises:
   Contrary to Democratic oratory through the ages, President
Herbert Hoover never promised two chickens in every pot, or even
one chicken.
   But Gov. Michael S. Dukakis is promising ``good jobs at good
wages for every single citizen of this country,'' and therein lies
a danger of some chickens coming home to roost.
   There is simply no chance Dukakis could deliver on this promise.
   On the subject of ``full employment,'' hyperbole comes easily to
Democrats. Their Humphrey-Hawkins bill, passed a decade ago,
decreed that by 1983 there would be 4 percent unemployment and zero
inflation.
   At the time of enactment, we suggested a better name for
Humphrey-Hawkins would be ``hogwash, hooey and hokum,'' and nothing
that has transpired has changed our mind.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 2
   The Philadelphia Inquirer on Lloyd Bentsen's financing:
   Republicans are fuming that it's unfair to let Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen, D-Texas, use millions in privately raised funds to win
re-election to the Senate while he runs for vice president on a
ticket that, like the GOP side, gets $46 million in federal funding
and can spend no more than that.
   Because items such as ads on Texas television will help Bentsen
in both campaigns at once, the GOP complains that the $10 million
or so that the senator may spend on his re-election will give the
Dukakis-Bentsen ticket an unfair advantage in trying to win Texas,
one of the main battlefields of what could be a close election.
   The Republicans are right.
   Whether or not the Bentsen twofer is illegal is a murkier
question. ... The practice smacks of unfairness.
</TEXT>
