   July 27
   The Knoxville (Tenn.) News-Sentinel on political conventions:
   In rejecting complaints that Atlanta's Omni was too small for a
national convention, Democratic National Committee Chairman Paul
Kirk said it was appropriate for the purpose: to serve as a
television studio.
   Television officials complain that the audiences are being
turned off by the conventions. TV's star reporters complain that
they don't get enough air time.
   As the Democrats wound up their show in Atlanta, ABC News
president Roone Arledge called conventions obsolete and said it is
time for the parties ``to look at whether they want to have a
four-day anachronistic meeting where no business is transacted, or
very little.''
   There is even talk in some quarters of abolishing conventions,
now that the television networks have reduced their coverage to a
few hours a night. That would be a mistake.
   Rather than complain about conventions, the networks ought to do
some self-examination. ...
   Fortunately, the networks no longer have a monopoly, and
interested citizens can find convention coverage on public
broadcasting, cable and local stations.
