   July 30
   Evening Express, Portland, Maine, on investigating Jim Wright:
   The appointment of former Chicago Bar Association president
Richard J. Phelan as independent counsel for an ethics committee's
probe into the actions of House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, was a
wise and necessary step in keeping the public's confidence that the
investigation will be fair and complete.
   But the panel should rescind immediately an unnecessary
restriction it imposed by limiting his inquiry to a two-month-old
list of six charges without allowing him to follow further
allegations unless he gets special permission.
   The committee has also retained control over public release of
Phelan's findings, another unnecessary and potentially harmful
decision. ...
   There's no reason that (Phelan) can't conduct an honest
investigation. But the ethics committee shouldn't restrict its
scope and should let him speak out freely about his findings.
   Otherwise, the charges of political favoritism just won't go
away.
