<TEXT>
   July 31
   The Duluth (Minn.) News-Tribune on Congress' drought relief
bills:
   We don't like the way Congress is going about its efforts to
provide drought relief.
   The drought, of course, was unexpected _ so the drought relief
has to come from money not provided for in the federal budget.
   But recent budget figures indicate there's only $5.9 billion
standing between the 1988 budget and the $146 billion deficit that
will trigger the across-the-board budget cuts everyone hates.
   So what are our drought-hating lawmakers doing these hot days in
D.C.? Farm state lawmakers are pushing for a quick compromise on
the $4.4 billion House version and the Senate drought aid package
with a price tag ranging from $5.9 billion to $6.6 billion.
   Why the rush? Because other things like nutrition aid programs
and the war on drugs are threatening to take a slice of the $5.9
billion.
   If lawmakers could bring themselves to stay within $146 billion
of a black-ink budget, they wouldn't face this dilemma or have to
make such unseemly haste on this important program.
</TEXT>
