   July 31
   Delta Democrat Times, Greenville, Miss., on giving to political
campaigns:
   In the midst of a spate of bad rulings handed down recenlty, the
U.S. Supreme Court somehow got it right on one issue.
   All Americans now have the right _ as they always should have _
not to be forced to give money to political candidates or causes.
   Twenty non-union workers of the American Telephone and Telegraph
Company sued the Communications Workers of America to recover money
the union had spent on political advocacy.
   A trial court determined that CWA could prove only 21 percent of
``agency fees'' collected had been used for collective bargaining,
and had ordered the other 79 percent rebated. ...
   Ironically, the court's majority opinion was written by Justice
William J. Brennan, its most liberal member, while the allegedly
conservative Reagan administration argued that workers have no
right to withhold their money from unions' political activities.
</TEXT>
