<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ElectionTie     08-03 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Election Tie,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Candidates Finish in Third Tie for Mayor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSBY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This little town is having big problems
electing a mayor.
   When Hattie M. Shelton announced she would not seek another term
because of health problems, Thomas Ledford and Harold Hartman
campaigned in the April election to head the town of 264 residents.
They finished with 17 votes apiece.
   They tried again in June, this time drawing 20 votes each.
   The mayor's race was on the ballot again in the primary election
Tuesday. Again the only difference was the number of votes _ 34 for
Hartman, 34 for Ledford.
   ``I can hardly believe it. It just doesn't seem possible that it
could happen again like that,'' said Hartman, 56, a supervisor at a
manufacturing plant.
   Hartman and Ledford said they would run again _ whenever there's
another election _ for the $50-a-month position. Mrs. Shelton
agreed in April to stay on as mayor until a successor was chosen.
   ``We've made the effort and neither of us wants to quit at this
point. We just keep plugging along,'' said Ledford, 50, a
landscaper. ``We've been trying to contact as many people as we
can. I think we'll have to talk to everybody in town the next
time.''
   The town 25 miles northeast of Kansas City has 109 registered
voters.
</TEXT>
