<1ST_LINE>u a PM-NudePolice     08-03 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nude Police,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>7 Metro-North Officers Suspended for Cavorting Half-Naked in Grand
Central</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven Metro-North police officers were suspended
today after a videotape surfaced that showed them cavorting nearly
nude around Grand Central station, the commuter railroad said.
   The tape was reportedly made during a 1983 strike by railroad
workers that did not involve police, according to Dan Brucker, a
spokesman for the Metro-North Commuter Railroad.
   ``I am morally outraged by their actions. I am insulted and I am
embarrassed,'' Metro-North President Peter Stangl said in a
statement. He called the officers' conduct ``unprofessional and
unacceptable.''
   He said that the officers depicted on the tape have been
suspended without pay and that the railroad will seek to have them
fired and stripped of their commissions to prevent them from
joining another police force in New York state.
   A railroad source who spoke on condition of anonymity said the
tape showed the officers harassing the homeless and was derogatory
toward blacks. In the tape at least one of the officers was
completely naked, the source said.
   Stangl said the videotape was brought to his attention Monday
and he viewed it on Tuesday.
   ``In my opinion, these individuals have demonstrated by their
conduct, a lack of good moral character and fitness to hold a
police commission,'' he said.
   Brucker said he did not know who made the tape or why and how
Stangl received it.
   Capt. Peter A. Nyland, the acting chief of the department, did
not immediately return calls today. The Metro-North Patrolmen's
Benevolent Association, which represents some of the officers, did
not return a call.
   Chief John Esposito was suspended last month after his
indictment on charges that he misused computers to do background
checks on job applicants and people who sued the railroad. Esposito
pleaded innocent.
</TEXT>
