<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 1229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Volcanoes-Ozone     08-03 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Volcanoes-Ozone,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Volcanoes May Contribute to Ozone Destruction, Report Says
^Eds: For release at 6 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Volcanic eruptions may contribute to depletion
of the Earth's ozone layer by belching an average of up to 1.4
million tons a year of ozone-destroying gases into the
stratosphere, a report says.
   But volcanoes pose far less threat to ozone than man-made
chemicals called chlorofluorocarbons do, said researcher William
Rose.
   The ozone layer in the stratosphere blocks ultraviolet radiation
from the sun that can cause skin cancer. Destruction of ozone by
chlorofluorocarbons has caused worldwide concern, leading to a
treaty signed recently by two dozen countries to curtail emissions.
   The new study is presented in Thursday's issue of the British
journal Nature by Rose and Robert Symonds of Michigan Technological
University in Houghton, with Mark Reed at the University of Oregon
in Eugene.
   They estimated concentrations of various gases from past
volcanic eruptions and used the results to project annual worldwide
totals.
   On average, volcanoes release a total of up to 15.4 million tons
of hydrogen chloride and hydrogen fluoride to the atmosphere a
year, but less than a tenth reaches the stratosphere, they
calculated.
   Gases from cataclysmic volcanic eruptions can rise more than 15
miles high, so they should encounter the maximum concentration of
ozone at about 15 miles, they wrote. But more work is needed to
tell just what such eruptions actually do to the ozone, they said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
