<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Baby'sFingers     08-03 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby's Fingers,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baby Whose Fingers Reattached Goes Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROBBINSDALE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An infant, two of whose fingers were
severed during a Caesarean section, has left the hospital with
surgeons confident the reattached digits will survive.
   Eleven-day-old Kristen Meckle left North Memorial Medical Center
with her mother, Diane, on Tuesday to fly home to Wildrose, N.D.
They will return in two weeks to have the cast on Kristen's left
hand removed.
   Kristen was rushed to North Memorial from Trinity Medical Center
in Minot, N.D., after a surgeon accidentally severed most of her
index finger and more than a third of the middle finger with a
surgical stapler during delivery, hospital officials said.
   During five hours of surgery, a team used tiny wires to
reconnect the bones, stitched together seven severed blood vessels,
reattached five tendons and some nerves and finally sewed the outer
skin closed.
   ``The fingers are healing very well and circulation is
excellent,'' said surgeon Martin Adson. So these fingers that are
so important in picking up things ``almost certainly will survive
now,'' he added.
   He said only time will tell how much stiffness will remain. ``In
general, children do better than adults, so we are hoping a newborn
will do even better,'' he said.
   Mrs. Meckle said she harbors no ill feelings over what happened
during the delivery, calling it ``just an unfortunate accident.''
She declined to name the doctor involved but said, ``I'd go back to
him anytime.''
   Finger loss or other serious injuries during Caesarean sections
are extremely rare, said Theresa Malone, spokeswoman for the
American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists in Washington.
But she said no records are kept on the number.
</TEXT>
