<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Airliner, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0611,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>International Team in Iran to Investigate Shooting Down of Plane</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS grafs 5-6, `A report...and reparations' with 4 grafs to
change attribution. Pick up 7th pvs, ``The findings...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A delegation from the International Civil
Aviation Organization is in the Iranian city of Bandar Abbas to
investigate the downing of an Iran Air jetliner by the U.S. Navy,
Iranian press reports said today.
   The team arrived in the southern port city late Tuesday for a
three-day visit to ``inspect the scene of the crash, wreckage of
the Airbus, Bandar Abbas airport and searching operations,'' said
the official Islamic Republic News Agency.
   The team will help supervise the search for the plane's flight
recorder and victims of the July 3 downing, said the reports
monitored in Nicosia.
   The jetliner was shot down over the southern Persian Gulf while
on a flight from Bandar Abbas to Dubai in the United Arab Emirates.
All 290 people on board were killed. The Navy said the missile
carrier Vincennes fired two missiles at the plane, mistaking it for
an F-14 jet fighter on attack formation.
   In Washington today, defense officials said that Pentagon
investigators believe human error led to the missile attack on the
jetliner. The investigators believe the ship's computerized radar
and tracking equipment were apparently operating properly, said
defense officials who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The officials said the military investigators were advancing the
theory that crewmen aboard the USS Vincennes, under stress from
their first combat action, misinterpreted the radar data presented
by the ship's Aegis defense system.
   ``There were no problems with Aegis,'' said one official.
   Iran's delegation to U.N. peace talks today called again for a
clear U.S. apology and reparations.
   ``The findings ... once again prove that what we said from the
very beginning was actually what happened,'' said Mohammad Javad
Zarif, counsellor at the Iranian Mission and spokesman for the
delegation.
   ``Now it is time for the United States to act responsibly,'' he
said. Zarif, speaking by telephone, said that the United States
should pay reparations and issue ``a clear apology for the murder
of 290 innocent people.''
   The full report on the investigation from the U.S. military is
not expected until mid-August.
   The International Civil Aviation Organization team will report
to the organization's council, IRNA reported. The group is based in
Montreal, Canada.
</TEXT>
