<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel Bjt   08-03 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, Bjt,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rightists Urge Israel to Annex West Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JRL2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALLENBY BRIDGE, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators of a small
right-wing party stood near this bridge to Jordan on Wednesday and
urged Israel to annex the West Bank now that King Hussein is
breaking formal ties with the territory.
   In a closed Cabinet session, Industry Minister Ariel Sharon
recommended that Israel apply its law in parts of the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip where Jewish settlers live, an aide said.
   Also on Wednesday, the army blew up or sealed 12 homes of West
Bank families whose sons are accused of firebombing Israeli targets
during the rebellion that began eight months ago among the 1.5
million Palestinians in the occupied territories.
   Hospital officials said soldiers shot and wounded five
Palestinians in two West Bank cities but the army confirmed only
three wounded. At least 236 Palestinians have been killed since the
uprising began Dec. 8, and four Israelis also have been slain.
   Hussein announced Sunday he would sever legal and administrative
ties with the West Bank, which Israel captured from Jordan in the
1967 Middle East war. The Israelis took the Gaza Strip from Egypt
in that war.
   Legislators of the small Tehiya party and their supporters held
the 30-minute rally at a checkpoint half a mile from the Allenby
Bridge. It delayed hundreds of Palestinian travelers bound for
Jordan, who endured the sweltering desert heat in taxis, trucks and
vans.
   One demonstrator raised a placard saying ``Good riddance King
Hussein.'' Yuval Neeman, a nuclear scientist and Tehiya parliament
member, said: ``Thank you for abandoning your claim here, King
Hussein. This is now the historic moment for Israel to declare
sovereignty in this area.''
   Lawmaker Geula Cohen said Israelis might seek to annex parts of
Jordan if it ever went to war with Israel again. She contended
parts of Hussein's kingdom were settled by Israelites in biblical
times.
   She and the other legislators said they would press their
demands for annexation with Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, whose
right-wing Likud bloc considers the West Bank part of the historic
land of Israel.
   About 850,000 Palestinians and 65,000 Jewish settlers live in
the West Bank.
   Hussein has not been specific about how he will end Jordan's
links with the territory, to which his government has provided more
than $200 million a year for for schools, farms, Islamic
institutions and hospitals. Palestinians in the West Bank also have
Jordanian passports.
   He said the area will be the responsibility of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, which Arab countries and the United
Nations have designated the sole legal representative of the
Palestinian people.
   Shamir has taken Hussein's decision to mean the king is
relinquishing Jordan's claim to the West Bank.
   Sharon, a former general and defense minister, urged the
government to annex part of the occupied territories. He spoke
during a two-hour Cabinet meeting about Hussein's announcement.
   ``Israel must apply Israeli law to areas in Judea and Samaria
(biblical names for the West Bank) and Gaza where there are Jewish
settlements and where there is sparse Arab population,'' the aide
quoted him as saying.
   The Knesset decided to interrupt its summer recess for a debate
next Monday about Jordan's new policy.
   A second day of Palestinian protest was reported Wednesday in
Nablus, the largest West Bank city. An official of Al Ittihad
hospital said soldiers wounded four young Arabs who threw stones.
   He said troopers later tried to arrest Taner Abu Salah, 24, who
had an arm wound, but doctors would not let him be moved. An army
spokesman said three people were wounded and he could not confirm
the attempted arrest.
   Another hospital official said a fifth Palestinian, 17-year-old
Abed Rabu Jawabreh, was wounded in the stomach. Both hospital
officials spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The 12 homes blown up or sealed before dawn were in four
villages and belonged to families of young Arabs who threw
firebombs at soldiers, civilians or suspected Arab collaborators,
the army said. Two reserve officers were reported seriously burned
in one attack in June.
   Families said they were given two hours to remove belongings.
Witnesses said women in Beit Ummar shouted ``This is for the
redemption of Palestine!'' as four houses were leveled.
</TEXT>
