<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContinentalCo-Pilot     08-03 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Continental Co-Pilot,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NTSB Report Shows Co-Pilot Of Crashed Jet Was Fired By Other
Airline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The co-pilot at the controls of a Continental jet
that crashed Nov. 15, killing 28 people, was fired by another
airline in 1985 for failing flight tests, a National Transportation
Safety Board report shows.
   Lee Bruecher, 26, was fired from Able Aviation in Houston,
Texas, ``as a result of his failure to successfully complete the
flight examination after at least two attempts,'' said the report
obtained by the Rocky Mountain News.
   The Continental DC-9 crashed in a snowstorm at Stapleton
International Airport with 82 people aboard. Bruecher and pilot
Frank Zvonek, 43, were among the victims.
   The NTSB has not yet determined what caused the crash, although
pilot error, wing icing, wing design, air traffic control and
possible turbulence are among the factors the agency said it was
examining.
   NTSB spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz said a final report on the cause
is expected to be released at an NTSB meeting Sept. 13.
   Bruce Hicks, Continental spokesman, said Tuesday that
Continental did not learn about Bruecher's dismissal during its
background check of Bruecher.
   But he added, ``The issue of Able Aviation four or five years
ago and Lee Bruecher flying for Continental is irrelevant. He was a
well-experienced pilot.''
   The NTSB report said Gary Guillet, Able's chief flight
instructor, reported that Bruecher ``had a chronic problem of
stepping on the wrong rudder, becoming disoriented, and described
(Bruecher) as tense, and unable to cope with deviations from the
routine.''
   Bruecher, who worked at the commuter airline flying small
turboprop planes from February 1984 to March 1985, was fired after
failing the test three times, the report said.
   Bruecher was hired as a pilot for Rio Airways of Killeen, Texas,
in March 1985. The NTSB said that while flying for Rio, Bruecher
had problems with approaches and takeoffs during flight checks but
received overall satisfactory ratings in June and December 1986 and
was promoted to captain.
   Hicks said Bruecher was hired by Continental from Rio in July
1987 and was trained until Sept. 14. He had completed about 25
flights with Continental _ with 36 hours flying time _ at the time
of the Nov. 15 crash, officials said.
   ``He was a good student,'' said Hicks. ``He passed all tests at
Continental ... (and) we have a good training program.''
   Moreoever, he said, Bruecher passed ``Federal Aviation
Administration tests, was certified by thePFas very
qualified with a DC-9. That's the pertinent facts.''
   Continental officials testified at a four-day NTSB hearing in
March that Bruecher had problems with takeoffs and landings and
crashed once during simulator tests but was certified to fly DC-9s.
</TEXT>
