<HEAD>With PM-Red Square Flier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher discussed the case of pilot Mathias Rust with Soviet
officials during Genscher's visit to Moscow last week, officials
said today.
   Earlier in the day, the 20-year-old West German pilot was
released from a Soviet prison where he was serving a four-year
term. Rust was imprisoned after flying through Soviet airspace and
landing in Moscow's Red Square last year.
   The development comes at a time of efforts by Soviet and West
German officials to improve relations.
   Genscher was in Moscow last weekend to prepare for the scheduled
October summit between Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Michael Gerdts, Genscher's spokesman, told reporters that
``Mathias Rust was a topic in talks between the foreign minister
and (Soviet) Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze'' in Moscow.
   In a statement to the news media today, Genscher said he ``sees
with this decision (to release Rust), efforts by the Soviet
officials to solve humanitarian questions.''
   ``The federal chancellor welcomes the decision by the Soviets to
set Mathias Rust free,'' said Norbert Schaefer, spokesman for the
West German government.
   Schaefer said several people had been involved in the effort to
win Rust's freedom, including West German President Richard von
Weizsaecker and Genscher.
