<HEAD>`Very Potent' Hurricane Approaching Hawaii</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with latest position, gusts increasing to
175. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Fabio, ``a very potent and dangerous''
storm with 175 mph gusts, moved toward Hawaii, but it was too early
to tell whether it would threaten the island chain, a forecaster
says.
   At 2 a.m. HST Tuesday (2 a.m. EDT Wednesday), the storm was
1,000 miles east southeast of Honolulu, moving west at 14 mph, said
Hans Rosendal, a meteorologist at the National Weather Service here.
   Clarence Lee, lead National Weather Service forecaster in
Honolulu, said Fabio ``is now a very potent and dangerous
hurricane,'' accompanied by damaging winds, destructive waves and
torrential rain.
   ``This is one of the strongest hurricanes in the area in quite a
while,'' Rosendal said.
   Fabio's maximum sustained winds were estimated near 145 mph. The
storm was expected to continue moving west at 14 mph for the next
24 hours with little change in strength, Rosendal said.
   If the storm remained on its present course and speed, the
center would pass about 50 miles south of Hawaii Island on Friday,
according to the weather service.
   The last major storm to hit Hawaii was Hurricane Iwa, which
brushed the island of Oahu and roared over the top of Kauai with
winds up to 117 mph in November 1982, causing $234 million damage.
</TEXT>
