<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Israeli Citrus,0117</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Fruit Taken Off Japanese Market; Fear Fungicide
Contamination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health officials Wednesday ordered more than 6 tons
of Israeli citrus fruit taken off the Japanese market, saying they
are contaminated with a fungicide.
   Inspectors found unacceptably high levels of the fungicide
diphenyl in random samples of Israeli grapefruit, oranges and
lemons sold in 24 Japanese stores, according to Koji Notoya, a
public health official.
   The fruit, tested between June 20 and Aug. 1, contained up to
about .002 ounces per pound of diphenyl above the maximum .0011
ounces per pound allowed by Japanese health standards, Notoya said.
   Large doses of diphenyl can cause liver damage, he said.
</TEXT>
