<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NYCHeat Bjt   08-03 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NYC Heat, Bjt,0730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beaches No Answer As Heat Bakes New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The temperatures are in the 90s, the humidity is
brutal, and the beaches are closed. All in all, Lester Rawitz
figures, a pretty good New York summer.
   ``This is the biggest year I ever recall. We're completely
cleaned out,'' said Rawitz, a Manhattan air conditioner retailer
for the past 34 years, speaking from his air-conditioned office.
``There's no question it's been good.''
   Good for Rawitz; good and hot for almost everybody else. On 13
occasions last month, the mercury climbed above 90 degrees; in an
average New York July, the temperature breaks 90 just seven times.
The forecast for the current week calls for temperatures to crack
100.
   ``If we didn't get two weeks with a tremendous amount of rain,
it would have been extremely warm last month,'' said National
Weather Service meteorologist Joe Harrison, pausing for a moment.
``Not that it wasn't warm enough.''
   How hot was it?
   Hot enough to make the asphalt mushy, making city streets like
flypaper; hot enough to make people look forward to riding the
subway, where at least there's air conditioning; hot enough to be
the ninth hottest July since the weather service began keeping
track in the 1860s.
   The temperature-humidity index is considered ``uncomfortable for
everyone'' when it reaches 79; on Monday and Tuesday, it broke 80.
   ``I've used my air conditioner more in the last month than I
have in my whole life,'' said Martha Lipfert, a public relations
worker for Consolidated Edison. ``I'm sure I'm not the only one,
either.''
   Worst of all, there has been no relief at the beaches.
   As temperatures climbed, so did the number of beaches closed by
waves of medical waste and other garbage. Other beaches were closed
when sewage escaped from a Staten Island treatment plant.
   ``The heat and humidity have been stifling. I can't remember a
summer like this in the 12 years I've been here,'' said Joseph
Lecinski, supervisor of Jones Beach State Park. Despite that,
Lecinski says crowds are off about 50 percent on the beaches.
   At Jones Beach, there were 865,000 visitors in July 1988; the
year before, there were 1.75 million. At Robert Moses State Park,
attendance was down to 366,000 from 650,000. It was the same story
at the Gateway National Recreation Beaches: Riis Park, down to
515,000 from 1,079,740, and Great Kills, 10,071 from 23,450.
   There were no attendance figures at city fire hydrants, which
desperate city dwellers opened for relief, but the city received
6,431 calls reporting such ``beach parties.''
   ``People are sweltering in their apartments because they can't
go to the beach,'' said Andrew McCarthy of the Department of
Environmental Conservation, which oversees the hydrants.
   That hasn't kept baseball fans at home. At Shea Stadium, the New
York Mets have drawn crowds of more then 45,000 for each of the
last five days, including sell-outs for four games against the
second-place Pittsburgh Pirates this past weekend.
   The heat may be keeping people away from other city attractions
_ about 6,000 fewer tourists went to the Statue of Liberty last
month compared to July 1987.
   In midtown Manhattan, the city's ban on street vendors made it
difficult for sweat-soaked pedestrians to grab a Dove Bar or find
the Good Humor man.
   As a result, many New Yorkers turned to the great indoors for
relief: A tour of midtown taverns on Tuesday showed a heavy turnout
of visitors escaping the heat and enjoying a cold brew or two.
   ``It's been packed in here all day,'' said bartender John
McDermott of McAnn's between trips to the beer taps Tuesday
afternoon. ``From what I hear, tomorrow's going to be worse.''
   The temperature climbed into the 90s again on Wednesday, which
meant another day off for the horses which pull carriages in
Central Park. It was another day for tourists to sit in the spray
of a fountain outside the Exxon Building, and for Lester Rawitz to
smile inside the offices of Economy National Sales Inc.
   ``I just got a call from a woman in Washington, wants us to send
an air conditioner to her mother up here,'' Rawitz said. ``The last
six weeks _ just constant demand.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
