<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--TV-MacNeil-Lehrer     08-03 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--TV-MacNeil-Lehrer,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PBS News Show Bags $57 Million Funding Commitment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour has secured
corporate funding commitments totaling $57 million over five years,
the producers said Wednesday.
   AT&T, which had been the sole corporate funder of the hourlong
newscast since it began in 1983, joined with PepsiCo and the John
D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation in the commitment to the
1988-92 financing.
   AT&T's share is $36 million for 1988-92, PepsiCo's $15 million
for 1989-92 and the foundation will contribute $6 million for
1988-90.
   The $11 million pledge for the season starting this fall is the
same as the corporate funding for the current season,
MacNeil-Lehrer spokesman Christopher Ramsey said.
   ``We think the major advantage is that when you have stability,
you can plan more effectively,'' Ramsey said. ``What this
guarantees is that public broadcasting will be able to maintain its
uniqueness in the news field.''
