<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 1450EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PrimariesRdp     08-03 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Primaries Rdp,0736</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young Foes Take Heart From Casino Ban; Missouri Lottery Officials
Rejoice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Detroit's rejection of casino gambling proves voters don't all
``walk in lockstep'' with Mayor Coleman Young, an opponent said,
while Missouri's lottery chief rejoiced at passage of an amendment
aimed at boosting sagging sales.
   In other voting Tuesday, Missouri state Rep. Betty Hearnes _
wife of a former governor _ won the Democratic nomination to oppose
Republican Gov. John Ashcroft, and former Michigan congressman Jim
Dunn won a GOP primary battle for a chance to face Democratic Sen.
Donald Riegle.
   Elsewhere in Missouri, Democratic voters handed Rep. Richard
Gephardt the nomination for a seventh term, and sent farm activist
Wayne Cryts into a November rematch against Republican Rep. Bill
Emerson.
   In Kansas, GOP Rep. Jan Meyers easily fended off a primary
challenge from Charles B. ``Bat'' Masterson, a retired school
adminstrator.
   In Detroit, with all precincts reporting, an ordinance outlawing
casinos was approved 82,271 to 50,890, or 62 percent to 38 percent.
   Young has long advocated a plan for construction of 12 casino
hotels, which would be taxed at a rate of 13 percent to raise money
for neighborhood development, improved police protection and a tax
cut.
   ``We want revitalization, but we do not want the crime and all
that goes with it,'' said Tom Barrow, president of Citizens for
Detroit's Future.
   He said the vote showed ``all black people do not walk in
lockstep with what Coleman Young says,'' said Barrow, who like
Young is black.
   Barrow challenged the mayor's last re-election bid and is
expected to try again next year, when Young is likely to run for a
fifth term.
   It is possible the ordinance could be challenged as an
unconstitutional attempt by a city to supersede state law. Gambling
cannot become legal without action by the state Legislature.
   The Missouri measure allows lottery officials to spend more on
prizes and advertising to compete with neighboring lotteries, which
have been making inroads into local sales.
   ``It's like the sun's come out after a long rain,'' Mike Morris,
the lottery's executive director, said Wednesday. ``Now it's our
job to deliver a fun, entertaining lottery to the people.''
   The first games that feature more prizes _ totaling 50 percent
of sales, instead of 45 percent _ are to begin in mid-September.
Under the original restrictions, advertisements had to include
disclaimers saying they were not intended to induce people to play.
Voters removed those restrictions.
   With 96 percent of precincts reporting, 455,068 voters, or 57
percent, had voted in favor and 337,182, or 43 percent, voted
against the amendment.
   Mrs. Hearnes, 61, whose husband, Warren, was governor from
1965-73, will attempt to become Missouri's first woman governor by
unseating Ashcroft, who did not face a primary.
   With 97 percent of precincts reporting, Mrs. Hearnes had 368,390
votes, or 81 percent, and Lavoy ``Zaki'' Reed, a St. Louis-area
teacher, had 84,123 votes, or 19 percent.
   Gephardt, who dropped his presidential bid just before the
deadline to file for re-election, won 82 percent of the vote
against three little-known Democrats. He will face Thor Hearne, a
former Education Department official who won the GOP primary.
   Cryts, who became a folk hero in 1981 when he took his family's
soybeans from a padlocked, bankrupt grain elevator, also swamped
three opponents. He lost narrowly to Emerson in 1986.
   In Michigan, Dunn defeated Robert Huber _ like him, a former
congressman and a millionaire _ for a chance to face Riegle, who
had no primary opposition in his bid for a third term. With all
precincts reporting, Dunn had 244,909 votes, or 61 percent, to
Huber's 159,616, or 39 percent.
   ``Don Riegle has been representing Michigan in Washington for 22
years,'' Dunn said. ``He's done very well for himself ... He's
accumulated power and wealth. I just have one question to ask the
voters of the state of Michigan: How have you done over the last 22
years?''
   Riegle, regarded as one of the nation's most liberal senators,
responded that he would campaign ``on the issues in Michigan,
issues that affect families, working families in particular,
day-care, education, home ownership.
   ``I've been very aggressive in fighting for Michigan,'' he said,
``and that's what people want and that's what's needed for
Michigan.''
</TEXT>
