<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Fair Bjt   08-03 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Fair, Bjt,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought's Effects Have Exhibitors Sweating Out Competition</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only the camels at the Ohio State Fair,
one of the largest fairs in North America, weren't suffering from
the heat and drought. Less exotic livestock had to be hosed down,
and the vegetables hardly looked like prize-winners.
   ``This is the worst display I have ever had,'' Tony Misich of
Clinton, near Akron in northeast Ohio, said of his produce. ``I've
had nothing but trouble this year.''
   The effects of the nation's worst drought in more than 50 years
were apparent as the Ohio State Fair prepared to open Thursday for
an 18-day run, making it the longest-running fair in the nation
this year.
   It will have 69,000 exhibits and the world's largest midway,
with an estimated 100 rides, said spokesman Shane Jenkins.
   The temperature Wednesday, reaching 89 degrees by noon, was a
steamy reminder of weeks of heat and too little rain, and the
forecast for Thursday and possibly beyond was no better: 95-100
degrees with high humidity.
   Fair officials said despite the summer's drought, they do not
anticipate any drop in attendance or the number of agricultural
exhibitors. But those displaying their fruits, vegetables and
livestock concede that they are not up to the standards of the past.
   Misich said his potatoes, cucumbers, green peppers and onions
are not only smaller than normal but do not look as good as others
he has displayed in his 10 years at the fair.
   The neighboring display of cabbage, potatoes, squash, pumpkins,
melons and green peppers by grower Francis Byers looked slightly
better, an observation he welcomed with a grin.
   ``The rain in the last couple of weeks made all the
difference,'' said Byers of Greenville, about 30 miles northwest of
Dayton. ``But it's still not like normal. That cabbage is big, but
it gets a lot bigger than that.''
   Across the fairgrounds in the Cattle Barn, 18-year-old Rob Pence
of Piqua, north of Dayton, and his father, Richard, were fighting
nature and a power outage in their efforts to keep Rob's beef cows,
Spuds and McKenzie, cool.
   ``They're not too bad this year. They're a good size,'' said Rob
Pence, who raised the pair as a 4-H project. ``At least they've got
hair.''
   Pence and other 4-H members in the barn planned to stay near
their animals around the clock to make sure they keep cool, using
electric fans hooked up to generators. Most exhibitors were hosing
or spraying their cows to beat the heat.
   John James of Mount Gilead, who stood watch over the beef cow
raised by his 18-year-old daughter, Kindra, was worried for the
animal because he said cows do not eat well in intense heat.
   ``If they go off feed, you got to work with them a lot more,''
he said.
   But the three camels in an exotic-animal display seemed
oblivious to the brutal heat. The ``ships of the desert'' being
shown by Bob Jones Attractions basked in the sun and calmly ogled
passers-by.
   ``They like it, it's just like the desert,'' said one of their
keepers.
</TEXT>
