<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Hinckley     08-03 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hinckley,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Lawyers Ask to See Presidential Assailant's Papers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government lawyers want to see John Hinckley's
correspondence with convicted mass murderer Theodore Bundy and
other materials before the man who shot President Reagan is allowed
to leave a mental hospital on a day trip.
   Prosecutors said they need to review the materials so they will
be able to ask pertinent questions about a conclusion by officials
at St. Elizabeths Hospital here that Hinckley would benefit from a
supervised, recreational outing.
   Hospital officials have suggested that Hinckley might benefit
from a day outing that might include bowling or a picnic. U.S.
District Court Judge Barrington Parker has scheduled a hearing on
the proposal Aug. 9.
   In a court motion filed late Tuesday and released Wednesday,
prosecutors said they need to see Hinckley's letters, including
correspondence with Bundy, who is awaiting execution in Florida, to
``cross-examine the hospital's interpretation of relevant facts.''
   Other materials include a letter Hinckley received from Lynette
``Squeaky'' Fromme, who was convicted of trying to assassinate
President Ford.
   One of Hinckley's psychiatrists also indicated Hinckley had
sought the address of Charles Manson from an unidentified person,
the motion said. Manson led a California cult that killed several
people; Fromme was one of his followers.
   Revelations about Hinckley's correspondence surfaced in April
1987 when the government successfully opposed a plan by St.
Elizabeths to allow Hinckley to spend an Easter vacation with his
parents.
   At the time, Parker refused to allow prosecutors to read the
materials, though they were seen by the court and doctors at St.
Elizabeths.
   ``In short, all parties except the government have had an
opportunity to examine the materials,'' the motion said.
   But prosecutors said they need to look at Hinckley's letters
because they are important and apparently prompted hospital
officials to cancel the proposed Easter event. ``The hospital, as
soon as the materials were discovered, realized their potential
relevance,'' the motion said.
   The Secret Service opposed the outing in a July 19 letter to
Parker.
   Hinckley, who shot and wounded Reagan and three other men on
March 31, 1981, was acquitted by reason of insanity. He has been at
St. Elizabeths since 1982.
</TEXT>
