<HEAD>Two Candidates Finish in Third Tie for Mayor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSBY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Mayor Hattie M. Shelton decided to step
down because of health problems, she agreed to stay on until voters
could pick a successor for the $50 a month job.
   Three elections _ and three tie votes _ later, she's still
waiting.
   Thomas Ledford and Harold Hartman campaigned in the April
election to head the town of 264 residents. They finished in a tie
with 17 votes apiece.
   They tried again in June. The result was 20 votes for Ledford
and 20 for Hartman.
   The mayor's race was on the ballot again in the Missouri primary
election Tuesday. This time: 34 for Hartman, 34 for Ledford.
   ``I can hardly believe it. It just doesn't seem possible that it
could happen again like that,'' said Hartman, 56, a supervisor at a
manufacturing plant in North Kansas City.
   Mrs. Shelton said after Tuesday's vote that she would ask the
Board of Aldermen to wait until the April 1989 election to fill the
post to avoid more money being spent on special elections.
   Ledford, 50, a landscaper, said Wednesday he's not sure what he
and Hartman can do about breaking the tie next time around.
   ``We've been trying to contact as many people as we can. I think
we'll have to talk to everybody in town the next time,'' he said.
The town has 109 registered voters.
   ``We've made the effort and neither of us wants to quit at this
point. We just keep plugging along,'' Ledford said.
   Mosby is about 25 miles northeast of Kansas City.
</TEXT>
