<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brochures     08-03 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brochures,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brochures Say `Buy America,' But Are Made In Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURANGO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brochures distributed by a concessionaire
at Mesa Verde National Park were made in Japan and a congressman
wants to know why.
   ``Gosh dang, I tell you what, there's something wrong with that,
isn't there?'' said Rep. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, D-Colo. ``We have
real nice printing industries right in the state of Colorado, 20
miles from the front gate of Mesa Verde park.''
   Until recently, visitors to the southwestern Colorado park
received a full-color brochure listing the hotels, restaurants and
campgrounds run by ARA Mesa Verde Co.
   What caught visitors' eyes were three tiny words on the back
page: ``Printed in Japan.''
   In a letter to National Park Service Director William Penn Mott,
Campbell asked why the agency ``is sending taxpayers' money to
overseas producers like Japan?''
   Karen Whitney, agency spokeswoman in Denver, said no tax dollars
went to Japan, because the brochure was not an official parks
publication. The agency produces its official brochures and maps in
Harper's Ferry, W.Va.
   Rather, ARA ordered the brochures through a California printing
company, which in turn subcontracted the job to a Japanese firm,
Whitney said.
   ARA executives did not realize the brochures were printed in
foreign countries until they were delivered, she said.
   ``The California printer said he could get the job done at a
higher quality and a better price in Japan than otherwise,''
Whitney said.
   ARA has changed its regulations to require that subcontractors
be American companies, and it recently received a new supply of
brochures _ printed in Farmington, N.M.
</TEXT>
