<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz     08-03 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Pressed For Ideas On Argentina's Economic Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P.
Shultz was pressed on Wednesday for new ideas about Argentina's
economic problems during the second day of his visit to this South
American capital.
   Alvaro Alsogaray, presidential candidate of the Center Alliance
political party, said he told Shultz that if inflation and
Argentina's foreign debt are not brought under control, ``that
could affect democracy itself.''
   In March, Argentina stopped paying even the interest on its $53
billion foreign debt, the third highest in the developing world.
Inflation, fueled by government overspending, stood at 121 percent
for the first six months of 1988.
   Economy Minister Juan Sourrouille planned to unveil an economic
program later Wednesday based on reduced federal subsidies for
public services, voluntary wage and price restraints, and a
devaluation.
   After lengthy meetings the day before with President Raul
Alfonsin and top aides, Shultz's plans for Wednesday included a
cookout at a ranch, a tour of the historic Colon Theatre, Buenos
Aires' 80-year-old opera house; and a private dinner with Alfonsin.
   In the morning, he met for a third time with Foreign Minister
Dante Caputo. The topics were Central America and Latin America's
foreign debt, Caputo told reporters. He did not elaborate. Shultz
is a former economics professor.
   Meetings also were scheduled with Defense Minister Horacio
Juanarena and Eduardo Angeloz, the governing Radical Civic Union's
presidential candidate in next year's elections.
   In talks on Tuesday with Sourrouille, Shultz was receptive to
Argentina's request for a $500 million bridge loan, the newspaper
La Nacion reported Wednesday, citing unidentified sources at the
Treasury Ministry.
   The bridge loan would help pay interest on the foreign debt
while a $1.2 billion stand-by loan is arranged with the
International Monetary Fund.
   An aide to Shultz refused to comment specifically on the issue,
but said:
   ``The basic position of the United States, of course, is to be
helpful in whatever ways we can as the Argentine government
addresses these problems. That is what the secretary (Shultz) told
the minister (Sourrouille). That's also what he told the
president.''
</TEXT>
