<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HudsonSwimmer     08-03 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hudson Swimmer,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>River Was Delicious, Says Albany-to-New York Marathoner</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY99</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAYNER PIKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An environmental investigator completed a swim
down the Hudson River on Wednesday and became the first person ever
known to stroke the 153 miles from Albany to the Statue of Liberty
in New York Harbor.
   When it was over, Skip Storch, who drank from the river en
route, declared: ``It tasted delicious.''
   Storch's in-water time was 54 hours and 50 minutes over seven
days, said his coach, Jane Katz, a physical education professor at
Bronx Community College. He covered 20 to 25 miles a day and slept
aboard his pace boat.
   Storch entered the water at 5:28 a.m. on July 28. Overcoming
injury and illness, he began the final leg of 11 miles at 4 a.m.
Wednesday from just below the George Washington Bridge and finished
at 7:27 a.m.
   ``I did it basically to let New Yorkers know that the waters are
a lot cleaner than they have been and for everybody not to become
complacent, but keep at it,'' Storch, 31, of Monsey, said when he
met reporters later at the South Street Seaport in lower Manhattan.
   He said the Hudson was fine north of Manhattan, but bacterial
levels in the water adjacent to the city made that part of the
river unsafe for swimmers.
   Storch earns his living by testing the waters around New York
City for the Interstate Sanitation Commission, a tristate and
federal watchdog body.
   During his swim he encountered none of the horrors, such as
medical wastes, that have closed ocean beaches throughout the
metropolitan area, he said.
   ``I saw a few plastic cups. Also some logs, but that's
natural,'' he said.
   Pointing to garbage floating off the seaport in the East River,
he said there was a distinction between unsightly debris and
health-threatening pollution.
   He said isolated instances of barges ``taking the shortcut and
just dumping their waste right in the river'' were deplorable and
also condemned recreational boaters as ``probably the least
courteous to the river and to our waters.''
   As he spoke to interviewers, he ate a plum and later tossed the
pit into the river.
   A stocky 5-foot-10, he described himself as having only average
speed for a swimmer, but ``I go and go and go.''
   He said he swam around Manhattan island last summer to get in
shape for this effort.
   Storch is prone to ear infection, so he carried eardrops with
him and was ready when it struck around Poughkeepsie. ``I also got
headaches. I vomited, that sort of thing. That always happens,'' he
said.
   In 1937, Charles Zimmy came within about 10 miles of completing
an Albany-to-Liberty Island swim. He made it to 129th Street in
Manhattan before being stopped by exhaustion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880803-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 1539EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-ChildLabor     08-03 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Child Labor,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Child Labor Rampant In Chinese City</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China-Birth, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children as young as 10 are working under
sweatshop conditions in foreign-owned companies in the city of
Shenzhen, it was reported Wednesday.
   The China Youth News daily said 44 of 206 foreign-owned
companies or joint ventures in the southeastern city employ
children under 16 years of age _ a practice illegal in China.
   Shenzhen, a growing city of half a million near Hong Kong, was
in 1980 designated one of four special economic zones for foreign
investment. About 80 percent of its foreign capital comes from Hong
Kong.
   The daily said that among the children working in Shenzhen, more
than 1,000 were recruited from the nearby rural province of
Guangxi. The youngest was aged 10 and the oldest 16.
   Against a setting of worker strikes, sexual promiscuity and
unwanted pregnancies among about 250,000 women who work part-time,
conditions for the children can be ``incredibly bad,'' the daily
said.
   In one factory producing silk flowers, girls as young as 12 work
14 or 15 hours a day, interrupted by a few hours of sleep in a tent.
   One 16-year-old girl showed a reporter a flower-shaped burn mark
left on her hand by a factory machine. She said she didn't earn
enough money to buy a $6 train ticket home to Guangxi.
   The report said the children received $22 to $27 a month _
considerably less than adults _ and that they had to pay for their
own room and board, as well as training fees.
   The report did not identify the factory or the foreign investors.
   Government officials in Guangxi charge $20 for false ID cards
for children seeking work in Shenzhen, who can then claim they are
of legal age, the daily said.
   ``Confusion in the management of our labor system provides a
hotbed for child labor,'' the report said.
   It said the manufacturing industry in Shenzhen ``will gradually
become a world of children.''
   China's official press has in recent months focused on the
growing problems of child labor, particularly in the countryside,
where many parents take their children out of school and put them
to work in small rural factories.
</TEXT>
