<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpaceShuttle 1stLd-Writethru a0663 08-03 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Shuttle, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0663,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leak Not Found, But Countdown On For Shuttle Engine Test</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with hunt for leak ended, new
quotes; Picks up 5th graf, `The leak ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA technicians Wednesday failed to
find the source of a launch pad hydrogen gas leak, but a countdown
proceeded for the crucial test firing of space shuttle Discovery's
engines on Thursday.
   ``They did everything they could do, but they couldn't locate
the leak,'' NASA spokesman George Diller said.
   ``We disassembled the hydrogen umbilical but could not pinpoint
the leak,'' launch director Bob Sieck said. ``We've changed out the
seals and debris plate. We've done everything we can ... but it's
still lurking out there.''
   Shuttle managers ordered the countdown to continue toward a 7:30
a.m. firing of the spaceship's three main engines. The test is
vital to certifying Discovery for the first shuttle flight since
Challenger and its crew of seven were lost in an explosion Jan. 28,
1986.
   Sieck said if the leak, which he described as very small,
develops again during the fueling of Discovery's fuel tank late in
the count, the launch team hopes to control it enough with
pressurization techniques to complete the fueling.
   ``If we get a leak beyond a hazardous level, we will
terminate,'' Sieck told a news conference.
   Engineers believe the leak is temperature related and shows up
only when liquid hydrogen at 423 degrees below zero is flowing
through the fuel line into Discovery's external fuel tank, Diller
said.
   The leak is in a launch pad service mast and not on the shuttle
itself.
   It was detected Monday during a practice countdown after the
tank was 67 percent full.
   Officials said they hoped the leak would not reappear when they
started pumping 385,000 gallons of liquid hydrogen into the tank in
the final hours of the countdown.
   If only a small leak showed up, they said they probably could
continue loading the fuel. To eliminate the chance of a fire, they
would neutralize the fuel line with an inert gas, nitrogen.
   Too big a leak would force a fifth postponement of the important
test firing.
   The 20-second ignition will be an overall test of shuttle
systems, as the main engines, computer software, ground support
equipment, communications links and the launch team will get a
thorough workout. Modifications have been made to the engines and
other systems since the Challenger accident.
   Instruments have been placed on joints in the redesigned solid
fuel booster rockets to measure stresses when the three main
engines generate total thrust of 1.1 million pounds.
   The booster rockets will not be fired during the test but will
be subjected to the same bending moments that led to a leak in one
of the joints during Challenger's liftoff. That leak allowed flame
to escape and led to the destruction of the shuttle 73 seconds
after launch.
   Officials believe the engine test delays, combined with an
unresolved leak in the spaceship's steering thruster system, could
slip Discovery's launch date from mid-September into October.
   NASA has deferred action on the thruster leak until after the
main engine test, when engineers will enter Discovery's cargo bay
and cut a hole through the rear bulkhead in an effort to reach and
repair the problem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880803-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 1520EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Irish Bjt   08-03 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish, Bjt,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Kills Soldier in New Campaign Against Security Forces</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   IRA gunmen ambushed and killed
a part-time soldier as he drove to work Wednesday, claiming their
fourth victim in three days of attacks on military targets in the
British province.
   Thirty-three people have been wounded.
   Ken Maginnes, a ranking Protestant lawmaker, urged Britain to
arrest about 40 people suspected of being Irish Republican Army
ringleaders and hold them without trial. British authorities
abandoned that policy, called internment, in 1975.
   Guerrillas fired on Pvt. Raymond McNicholl of the Ulster Defense
Regiment, the locally recruited British army unit, as he slowed his
car to cross a narrow bridge outside Cookstown, 40 miles west of
Belfast.
   McNicholl, 31, was on his way to work at an engineering plant.
Police said he was hit several times in the head and chest, and
died later at South Tyrone Hospital.
   Spokesmen for the Royal Ulster Constabulary, the police force of
the Protestant-dominated province, said the guerrillas drove to the
ambush in a car stolen from a family of five held captive overnight.
   An IRA statement to Belfast news media claimed responsibility
for the killing. On Tuesday, the IRA warned civilians to stay away
from British servicemen because they were targets in Northern
Ireland and abroad.
   The IRA, most of whose members are Roman Catholic, is fighting
to drive Britain out and unite the province with the Irish
Republic. It is outlawed on both sides of the border.
   Its latest campaign began Monday with the bombing of an army
barracks in suburban London that killed one soldier and wounded
nine. Police said Wednesday they were investigating the possibility
of a woman having smuggled the bomb into the Inglis barracks
Saturday night during a disco dance.
   In three separate attacks Tuesday in Northern Ireland, the IRA
killed a police detective and a part-time soldier and wounded 33
people. Gunmen dragged the off-duty soldier from a Belfast store
and killed him in front of his wife and 2-year-old daughter.
   Gunmen ambushed McNicholl near the spot where a land mine blew
up an Ulster Defense Regiment vehicle Tuesday, wounding six
soldiers.
   Protestant and Catholic leaders, and the British and Irish
governments, condemned the new IRA blitz. Military and police
chiefs ordered reviews of security.
   Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King, the top British official
for the province, declared: ``Terrorism will be beaten'' and did
not rule out reviving internment without trial. ``We keep these
matters under review,'' he said.
   Britain stopped internment in December 1975, six years after
sectarian violence began in Northern Ireland, following worldwide
condemnation.
   In Dublin, Prime Minister Charles Haughey said Wednesday that
``violence can do nothing to bring about a solution to the tragic
problems of Northern Ireland.''
   Referring to possible talks between politicians on both sides of
the border, the Irish Republic's premier said the attacks were
particularly deplorable ``in the present context, with hopes of
political progress being encouraged.''
   Col. Peter MacIntyre, a senior officer of the Ulster Defense
Regiment, said its members would have to review their personal
security arrangements.
   The IRA has killed 10 regiment members, three policemen and 12
British soldiers in Northern Ireland so far this year. Outside the
province, the guerrillas have killed the soldier at the Inglis
barracks and three British servicemen in West Germany and The
Netherlands.
   Seventeen civilians have lost their lives since November because
of attacks on security forces bungled by the IRA. Its warning
Tuesday said civilians should keep away from British military
personnel because their close presence ``often forces us to abandon
operations.''
   King described the IRA warning as ``absolutely hypocritical and
utterly evil.''
   British media quoted IRA sources in Belfast, not identified, as
saying civilians should shun pubs and discos frequented by British
military personnel.
   The IRA bombed three pubs in England in 1974 and its Marxist
offshot, the Irish National Liberation Army, bombed a pub in
Northern Ireland in 1982. Servicemen were among the casualties in
all the attacks.
</TEXT>
