<HEAD>$300 in Cash Washed Up On Long Island Beach; Sewage in Miami</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC BEACH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long Islanders thought they'd seen
everything wash up on their shores in recent weeks _ until a beach
cleaner collected $300 in faded bills from a beach Wednesday
morning.
   ``I couldn't believe my eyes,'' said Singleton Moorer, who
collected the cash while cleaning the beachfront at the Silver
Point Club. ``I just kept picking it up and the tide kept washing
it back out. I was so excited.''
   Moorer reported collecting a $100 bill and an assortment of
$20s, $10s, $5s and singles trapped in clumps of seaweed along the
tide line _ quite a switch from the syringes, blood vials and
garbage which have closed beaches this summer.
   Moorer, 38, said he and two colleagues found the money around
5:30 a.m. Most of it was faded to white and light green by the salt
water and sunlight, he said.
   Moorer took the cash and bought a big breakfast for himself and
his colleagues. The eight-year veteran of the beach-cleaning crew
said last year he found about $50.
   ``This is a great job,'' Moorer said, adding the money is more
than a week's pay for him.
   Money has been found washed up on the beaches occasionally, said
beach club spokesman William Baumert.
   ``It's probably from some poor guy off his boat,'' Baumert said.
``One thing is for sure _ this is a nice kind of pollution to have
wash up for a change.''
   Raw sewage washed up on some Miami-area beaches on Wednesday,
following a weekend pipeline rupture that spilled millions of
gallons of sewage into Florida's Intracoastal Waterway.
   The decision to close beaches was made after tests taken from 12
sites along shoreline parks in northeastern Dade County showed
three of them with coliform bacteria counts above safety levels.
