<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brezhnev     08-03 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brezhnev,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Leader's Son-In-Law to Go on Trial in September</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son-in-law of the late Soviet leader Leonid I.
Brezhnev will go on trial Sept. 5, charged with taking bribes worth
more than $1 million, the Tass news agency said Wednesday.
   Tass said Yuri Churbanov, who held the post of first deputy
interior minister while Brezhnev was alive, will be tried in open
court by the military collegium of the Soviet Supreme Court.
   Eight others _ many of them generals of the Interior Ministry _
will be tried along with Churbanov, Tass said. It quoted Alexander
Sboyev, who is said would be the prosecutor at the trial.
   It said Churbanov had pleaded guilty.
   Churbanov married Brezhnev's daughter, Galina, and held a
position of power until Brezhnev died in 1982.
   ``Churbanov is charged with taking bribes in the late 1970s
early 1980s from the leaders of Uzbekistan's Ministry of the
Interior, heads of a number of regional departments of the interior
in the same republic, and other officials,'' Tass said.
   The Interior Ministry oversees the police, as well as travel and
emigration visas.
   Tass said the total value of the bribes Churbanov was alleged to
have accepted was equivalent to $1.1 million at the official
exchange rate.
   The charges against Churbanov were the result of a wide-ranging
investigatio n of corruption in Uzbekistan, a republic of Soviet
Central Asia.
   Brezhnev ruled the Soviet Union from 1964-82. He has been
condemned by the current leader, Mikhail S. Gorbachev, for
fostering corruption and stagnation in Soviet society.
   Tass said the other defendants also pleaded guilty, but that
only one of them has turned in the money he is charged with
obtaining illegally.
   Two other suspects committed suicide, Tass said.
</TEXT>
