<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 1527EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Hastings 6thLd-Writethru a0725 08-03 0980</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hastings, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0725,900</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last graf to add Boulter and Wright as not voting.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House, with only three dissenting votes,
today impeached U.S. District Judge Alcee L. Hastings of Florida
and told the Senate to try him for ``high crimes and misdemeanors.''
   On a vote of 413-3, the House sent a resolution containing 17
articles of impeachment to the Senate, which might not take up the
matter until next year. If found guilty by a two-thirds majority,
Hastings, the first black federal judge in Florida, would be
removed from his $89,500 job.
   Following the vote, Hastings held a quick news conference on the
steps of the federal courthouse in Miami and said he would not step
down from the bench. He called the vote ``a dark day for myself and
the judicial process,'' but added that he expects to prevail in the
Senate.
   ``The vote today, in my humble opinion, is a disgrace,'' said
Hastings. ``Many congresspersons voted with no knowledge of the
voluminous record that has taken seven years to compile.''
   Hastings downplayed his previous complaints that the
investigation was racist, saying ``this isn't about racism, it's
about fairness.''
   The resolution charges that Hastings:
   _Conspired with Washington attorney William Borders to receive a
$150,000 bribe from two convicted racketeers;
   _Lied about the bribe during a criminal trial, and
   _Compromised three FBI investigations by leaking wiretap
information over which he had jurisdiction.
   One article says that Hastings, required as a judge to enforce
and obey the Constitution and the laws of the United States, did
``undermine confidence in the integrity and impartiality of the
judiciary and betray the trust of the people of the United States''
and had thus brought ``disrepute on the federal courts and the
administration of justice by the federal courts.
   As the vote approached, Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., chairman of
the Judiciary subcommittee that held hearings on the Hastings
impeachment, said that black public officials should meet the same
standards as white public officials.
   ``Lower standards would be patronizing; higher standards,
racism,'' he said. ``The problems created here were created by
Judge Hastings himself. (Hastings) has failed to measure up (to
standards applicable to all judges.''
   Conyers, a black, received a standing ovation from other members
when he finished.
   Hastings had few defenders on the House floor.
   Rep. Joseph D. Early, D-Mass., voted ``present'' because, he
said, Hastings had been acquitted by a jury.
   ``Here we have an individual who wasn't convicted,'' Early said.
``What are we going to do with other judges? Are we going to have
the Judiciary Committee come in with impeachment charges every time
a judge is just accused?''
   The House Judiciary Committee, in its report supporting the
resolution, said:
   ``Impeachment protects our society by insuring that those in the
highest positions of public trust are held accountable. This is
especially true with respect to members of the federal judiciary
who, barring impeachment, enjoy life tenure in office. ...
   Before the vote, Hastings said House members who vote to impeach
him will ``rubber stamp racism.''
   The House impeachment vote ``marks another dark and dangerous
day in the House of Representatives,'' Hastings said in Miami on
Tuesday.
   ``It is expected that a number of congresspersons will
rubber-stamp racism and stand the Constitution and American
jurisprudence on its head,'' Hastings said in a telephone interview.
   Two weeks ago, the House Judiciary Committee voted 32-1, in
three separate votes, on the articles of impeachment against
Hastings, the first black appointed to a federal judgeship in
Florida.
   Although Hastings has said he is a victim of double jeopardy, of
``blind ignorance'' and racism, he failed to convince the
committee, which has two black members, that he did not conspire
with a Washington attorney to take a bribe.
   The two black members _ Conyers and Rep. George W. Crockett Jr.,
D-Mich., a former city judge in Detroit _ said they were skeptical
about the bribery charges at first and wondered whether racism
could be the source of the allegations against the flamboyant
Hastings.
   After the hearings, Conyers said: ``I couldn't find any.''
   Conyers said the failure by Hastings and Borders to testify was
one of the many things that led him to vote for impeachment.
   The Senate trial might not begin until next year, when a new
Congress will be seated.
   The principal charge against Hastings is that he conspired with
Borders to obtain $150,000 from two convicted racketeers in return
for reducing their sentences.
   Borders was convicted in a federal court trial, but Hastings was
acquitted of the charge in 1983. The issue was raised again by
judges of the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals, which conducted an
investigation. The judges said Hastings had engaged in the
conspiracy and had lied at his trial.
   The findings were endorsed by the Judicial Conference of the
United States, the administrative office of the federal courts.
   Hastings has said he is innocent. His attorney, Terence J.
Anderson, said during the congressional hearings: ``I believe the
judge will be acquitted in the Senate.
   ``The House has voted 10 impeachments _ they've only won five''
in the past, he said. ``One jury was unanimous in its decision _
not guilty. I don't think it's fair that he must go before a new
jury seven years and $2 million later. Once is enough.''
   Others voting present were Reps. Harold E. Ford, D-Tenn., and
Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas.
   Voting no were Reps. Gus Savage, D-Ill., Mervyn M. Dymally,
D-Calif., and Edward R. Roybal, D-Calif.
   Eleven members did not vote in addition to Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, who customarily refrains from voting. They were Reps.
Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., Hal Daub, R-Neb., Butler Derrick, D-S.C.,
Wayne Dowdy, D-Miss., Jack F. Kemp, R-N.Y., Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
Buddy MacKay, D-Fla., Dan Mica, D-Fla., Floyd Spence, R-S.C., Gene
Taylor, R-Mo., and Beau Boulter, R-Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
