<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ShrimpRecall     08-03 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shrimp Recall,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDA Recalls Some Frozen Shrimp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration said
Wednesday that a New York company is recalling some of its
precooked, frozen shrimp after routine sampling found potentially
harmful bacteria in the product.
   Distributed by Queen `O' the Ocean Inc., of Jamaica, N.Y., the
frozen shrimp was distributed in the New York City area primarily
in five-pound plastic bags, six to a carton, bearing the lot number
8955. The agency said the company reported that 41 cartons of those
bags were distributed and that some three-pound bags also may have
been distributed.
   The FDA said New York State has embargoed 31 additional cartons
at the company's warehouse.
   The FDA sampling found listeria monocytogenes in the shrimp, a
bacteria that can call listeriosis, a normally brief ailment with
mild-to-moderate flu-like symptoms such as fever, headaches and
vomiting.
   Although usually not a major danger for adults, listeriosis can
be life-threatening to fetuses and newborns, the FDA said.
</TEXT>
