<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     08-03 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Accuses Iraq Of Using Chemical Weapons Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said Wednesday an Iraqi chemical
bomb attack wounded more than 1,000 civilians, and Tehran called
for a ban on the export of materials used in the weapons.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency also reported that
Iranian anti-aircraft batteries shot down an Iraqi jet fighter that
attacked an industrial plant on Wednesday near the southern city of
Bushehr.
   Iraqi warplanes also attacked an industrial target in the
western province of Khuzestan, the news agency reported in
dispatches monitored in Cyprus.
   It said both targets were damaged in the Iraqi attacks, but no
casualties were reported. It gave no further details on the targets.
   Iraq said it attacked an Iranian oil-pumping station and a
natural-gas facility, in a war communique carried by the official
Iraqi News Agency.
   The communique denied that an Iraqi jet was downed. Both news
agencies were monitored in Nicosia. Their contents could not be
independently verified.
   Peace talks aimed at reaching agreement on a cease-fire based on
U.N. Security Council Resolution 598 made little headway Wednesday,
with Iraq continuing to insist on face-to-face talks, which Iran
has refused.
   At the United Nations, Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
continued efforts to break the deadlock over Iraq's demand.
   He did not schedule formal meetings with Iranian or Iraqi
officials. But aides said contacts with both sides were continuing.
The talks began July 27.
   In the Gulf of Oman, a small cargo vessel exploded and sank on
Wednesday, but the blast appeared to be caused by an explosion on
board and not a mine, gulf-based shipping executives said. No
serious injuries were reported.
   The Greek captain and eight Asian seamen aboard the 1,870-ton
Fatima were rescued by helicopters from a French missile destroyer.
The executives said heat in the area may have caused the vessel's
cargo of gas bottles to explode.
   In Paris, the son of the late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi issued
an appeal on Wednesday calling on his countrymen to overthrow
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's ``reign of darkness'' in Iran.
   IRNA said 1,031 civilians in the northern province of West
Azerbaijan were wounded on Tuesday when Iraqi warplanes dropped
chemical bombs on the town of Oshanaviyeh. It said most victims
were treated for minor injuries.
   In an interview with Iranian television from the United Nations,
Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati called on Tuesday for a ban on
the export of materials used to manufacture chemical weapons.
   Velayati was reacting to a U.N. report released Monday that
documented massive use of outlawed chemical weapons by Iraq.
Velayati's remarks were carried by Tehran Radio on Wednesday.
   The late shah's son, who calls himself Reza Shah II, invited
Iranians of all walks of life to partake in the establishment of
``popular government.''
   He cited ``the impotence of the Islamic republic to bring
honorable peace and reconstruction, noting the imminent collapse of
the reign of darkness.''
   ``In this life and death struggle for democracy my destiny is
intertwined with yours ... the time is now to break your silence,''
said Reza Shah, who has some support among exiled Iranians. His
remarks were released in Paris, where his monarchist movement is
based, on the occasion of the anniversary of the defunct royal
constitution.
</TEXT>
