<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Vietnam 1stLd-Writethru a0715 08-03 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Vietnam, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0715,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Asks Vietnam Not To Suspend Search For MIAs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts dropped word ``the'' in 2nd graf; deletes extranous
word ``a'' in 3rd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department urged Vietnam on
Wednesday to continue cooperating in the search for missing
American military personnel and the resettling of thousands of
former political prisoners in the United States.
   The official Voice of Vietnam radio said the Hanoi government
was temporarily suspending its participation in the programs. It
cited as a ``hostile policy'' the State Department's opposition to
a move in Congress to establish a low-level diplomatic mission in
Hanoi.
   Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley did not retreat from the
stand taken by Assistant Secretary of State Gaston Sigur in
testifying last month against creation of a so-called U.S. interest
section in the Vietnamese capital.
   She said the two sides had agreed that humanitarian issues
``should not be linked to broader political questions, such as
normalization or economic aid.''
   Mrs. Oakley urged Vietnam to continue its cooperation with the
United States in trying to account for the nearly 1,800 Americans
missing in action since the Vietnam War.
   Sigur had testifed that the Reagan administration opposed
normalization of relations with the communist government in Hanoi
until an acceptable solution was found to Vietnam's military
presence in neighboring Cambodia.
   ``The State Department still continues to make foreign policy,''
Mrs. Oakley said.
   Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach informed retired
U.S. Army Gen. John W. Vessey, President Reagan's special emissary,
of Hanoi's decision in a letter Sunday.
   The Hanoi radio broadcast described Sigur's testimony as
evidence of ``hostile policy'' and said Vietnam ``is compelled to
suspend temporarily'' joint efforts ``in the search and exhumation
of remains of missing in actions as well as the resettlement of
camp inmates in the United States.''
   The State Department says it has received about 11,000
applications requesting resettlement of former Vietnamese political
prisoners and their families in the United States. Vietnam said the
resettlement could involve hundreds of thousands of Vietnamese.
   Thach and Vessey agreed a year ago in Hanoi that Vietnam would
accelerate its accounting of the MIAs while the United States would
help with humanitarian programs, such as for those disabled in the
war.
   In letters to Vessey last month, Thach promised to try to
resolve by the end of the year 70 MIA cases which the United States
has given high priority. Thach also welcomed joint excavations for
remains.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
