<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 1552EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India 1stLd-Writethru a0653 08-03 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0653,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Two Death Sentences In Gandhi Slaying</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs after last graf to UPDATE with 12 killed and
massacre foiled.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Wednesday upheld
the death sentences of two Sikhs convicted in the 1984
assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi. A third conviction
was overturned.
   A three-judge panel rejected appeals by Police Constable Satwant
Singh, convicted of the killing, and Kehar Singh, a government
official found guilty of conspiracy, after a six-month review.
   But it acquitted for lack of evidence police sub-inspector
Balbir Singh, who had been convicted and sentenced to death.
   The judges announced their decision to a packed courtroom ringed
by policemen armed with automatic rifles. Security measures, aimed
at deterring attacks by Sikh terrorists, included frisking
spectators and metal-detector checks.
   Mrs. Gandhi was assassinated Oct. 31, 1984, at her home by two
Sikh bodyguards, Satwant Singh and Beant Singh, apparently in
revenge for ordering an army raid four months earlier on the Golden
Temple in Amritsar, Sikhism's holiest shrine. The temple was used
by Sikh rebels as a base in their violent struggle for an
independent homeland in the northern state of Punjab.
   Minutes after the slaying, Beant Singh was killed and Satwant
Singh injured in a shootout with other security men.
   Police arrested Kehar Singh, an uncle of Beant Singh, and Balbir
Singh, a guard at the prime minister's residence.
   The three defendants are not related. ``Singh,'' meaning lion in
the Punjabi language, is part of every Sikh male's name by doctrine
of faith.
   The defendants, held in New Delhi's central jail, were not
present for the ruling. Under Indian law, defendants are brought to
their trials but are represented by counsel during appeals.
   ``I am very pleased with the judgment,'' said Swaran Singh,
Balbir Singh's brother. ``They caught an innocent man but now
justice has been done.''
   In January 1986, a trial court sentenced the defendants to death
by hanging and New Delhi's High Court upheld the decision. The
hearing of the appeals began the next month at the Supreme Court,
India's final court of appeal.
   The two condemned men may request a second review by the same
judges and file a petition for mercy to Indian President Ramaswamy
Venkataraman.
   Sikhs represent 2 percent of India's 800 million people but form
a majority in Punjab. Radical Sikhs have been agitating for an
independent Sikh state in Punjab since 1982, claiming
discrimination by India's majority Hindus.
   More than 1,200 people, most of them Sikhs, died in the army
attack on the Golden Temple.
   Mrs. Gandhi's slaying triggered anti-Sikh riots in New Delhi and
other cities in which more than 2,000 people were killed, most of
them Sikhs.
   In separate incidents Wednesday in Punjab's Amritsar district,
eight people were shot and killed, including a member of the Sikh
Temple Management Committee, United News of India reported. It also
said two people were killed in Gurdaspur district and two others in
Ferozepur district.
   After the court ruling was issued, security forces were on alert
throughout northern India against possible attacks by Sikhs, the
agency said.
   Police in the Faridkot district, 203 miles northwest of New
Delhi, foiled an attempt by militants to carry out simultaneous
massacres in towns in Faridkot and Ferozepur, said Police Chief
Govind Ram.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
