<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Hastings Bjt   08-03 0899</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hastings, Bjt,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Impeaches Federal Judge Hastings Despite Acquittal in Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an unprecedented case, the House approved
17 articles of impeachment Wednesday against U.S. District Judge
Alcee L. Hastings of Miami despite his acquittal in a previous
bribery trial.
   The House action, which is tantamount to an indictment, sent the
case to the Senate for trial, where conviction by a two-thirds
majority is required for Hastings' removal from the federal bench.
The Senate has not announced a trial date.
   The 413-3 vote marked the first time the House has ever
impeached a federal official who was acquitted of similar charges
in a criminal trial.
   It also was the first time that a black official has been
defendant in impeachment proceedings.
   Hastings, who is the first black U.S. district judge in Florida,
retreated Wednesday from his previous contentions that the
impeachment proceedings were racially motivated. ``This isn't about
racism, it's about fairness,'' he said.
   At an impromptu news conference on the steps of the federal
courthouse in Miami, Hastings said his impeachment was ``a dark day
for myself and the judicial process,'' but that he is confident he
will prevail in the Senate.
   At stake is Hastings' $89,500-a-year, lifetime job on the
federal bench. He was nominated by President Carter in 1979.
   ``The vote today, in my humble opinion, is a disgrace,''
Hastings said. ``Many congresspersons voted with no knowledge of
the voluminous record that has taken seven years to compile.''
   He added: ``I am petrified at their uncaring, undignified and,
in my judgment, unconstitutional approach to this matter.''
   Hastings accused the House of acting hastily so its members
could concentrate on re-election campaigns.
   With Wednesday's vote, the House has impeached 15 federal
officials in its history. Twelve cases have gone to trial in the
Senate. Two officials resigned prior to Senate proceedings and five
_ all federal judges _ have been convicted by the Senate and
removed from office.
   The last to be ousted was U.S. District Judge Harry E. Claiborne
of Las Vegas, Nev., who was convicted of ``high crimes and
misdemeanors'' in October 1986 while serving a federal prison term
for tax evasion.
   The basic charge against Hastings, contained in Article 1,
paralleled the criminal charges on which he was acquitted in 1983.
   Article 1 accused Hastings and Washington attorney William
Borders of conspiring in 1981 to obtain a $150,000 payment from two
convicted racketeers in exchange for lenient sentencing and return
of forfeited assets.
   Borders was convicted and Hastings acquitted at separate
criminal trials.
   Articles 2 through 15 accused Hastings of lying at his 1983
trial on various aspects of the case.
   Article 16 says Hastings, in a separate case, revealed ``highly
confidential information'' obtained through a wiretap to Dade
County Mayor Stephen Clark.
   The 17th article said Hastings' actions ``undermine confidence
in the integrity and impartiality of the judiciary'' and bring
``disrepute on the federal courts and the administration of justice
...''
   After Hastings' acquittal, a special panel of judges from the
11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which covers Florida,
recommended that the House consider impeaching Hastings. The
panel's conclusions were endorsed unanimously by the Judicial
Conference, the policy-making body of the federal judiciary.
   Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., a black whose House Judiciary
subcommittee investigated Hastings, said racists are probably
``gloating'' and ``delighted'' over the charges against Hastings.
But Conyers strongly defended the articles of impeachment.
   Conyers said he was initially ``very suspicious'' of the Reagan
administration's prosecution of Hastings because it had nominated
only a half-dozen blacks as lower court judges and only one as an
appeals court judge.
   But Conyers said he concluded after his investigation that ``the
problems created here have been created by Judge Hastings himself.''
   He added, ``Black public officials must be held to the same
standard as all other public officials. A lower standard would be
patronizing. A higher standard would be racist. Just as race should
never disqualify a person from office, race should never insulate a
person from the consequences of wrongful conduct.''
   Rep. Peter W. Rodino Jr., D-N.J., chairman of the full Judiciary
Committee, dismissed suggestions that Hastings was the victim of
double jeopardy, the legal prohibition against being tried twice on
the same charges.
   Rodino said an impeachment trial is not a criminal proceeding,
and therefore the two are ``separate and distinct.''
   Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa., said, ``This look that we have just
given into the conduct of Alcee Hastings makes one sick in the
stomach.''
   Voting against impeachment were Reps. Gus Savage, D-Ill., Mervyn
M. Dymally, D-Calif., and Edward R. Roybal, D-Calif.
   Rep. Joseph D. Early, D-Mass., voted ``present'' because, he
said, Hastings had been acquitted by a trial jury.
   ``Here we have an individual who wasn't convicted,'' Early said.
``What are we going to do with other judges? Are we going to have
the Judiciary Committee come in with impeachment charges every time
a judge is just accused?''
   Also voting ``present'' were Reps. Harold E. Ford, D-Tenn.,
Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, and E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla.
   A dozen members did not vote. They were Reps. Mario Biaggi,
D-N.Y.; Hal Daub, R-Neb.; Butler Derrick, D-S.C.; Wayne Dowdy,
D-Miss.; Jack F. Kemp, R-N.Y.; Trent Lott, R-Miss.; Buddy MacKay,
D-Fla.; Dan Mica, D-Fla.; Floyd Spence, R-S.C.; Gene Taylor, R-Mo.;
Beau Boulter, R-Texas, and Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, who
customarily does not vote.
</TEXT>
