<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SovietInspectors-Cape     08-03 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Inspectors-Cape,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Inspect Pershing 2 Missile Launch Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet military team inspected old
Pershing 2 missile facilities Wednesday under terms of the
Intermediate Nuclear Force treaty.
   The 10-person group arrived at nearby Patrick Air Force Base in
an Air Force transport and immediately accompanied 10 American
escorts in vans to Cape Canaveral.
   Two other Soviet teams were inspecting sites Wednesday in
Maryland and Oklahoma under the terms of the INF treaty signed in
December by President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Under the treaty, all nuclear missiles with a range of 300 to
3,400 miles must be eliminated within three years of the date the
treaty became effective. The U.S. will destroy 867 Pershing 1A,
Pershing 2 and ground-launched cruise missiles in Europe, while the
Soviets will destroy 1,752 SS-4, SS-12 and SS-20 missiles.
   Soviet and American inspection teams are permitted under the
treaty to visit selected missile sites to check on compliance with
the document.
   At Cape Canaveral, the Soviet team toured Launch Complex 16,
where Pershing 2 missiles were test-launched as recently as last
February, and an area where the missiles were assembled.
   The Soviets were briefed by the head of the American team, Air
Force Maj. Warren Greene, who told them both facilities are now
mothballed and that there are no longer any Pershing 2 missiles
here.
   The Pershing 2 missiles will be destroyed by stationary fring at
bases in Colorado and Texas.
</TEXT>
