<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DroughtContinues     08-03 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Continues,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Severe Drought Persists Despite Rains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recent rains in the Ohio and Mississippi
valleys haven't ended the nation's severe drought and the outlook
remains bleak, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
reported Wednesday.
   Some areas remain more than 10 inches short of normal rainfall
since April, the agency reported. Significant amounts of rainfall
over large areas are needed to promote any long-term relief.
   The latest 30-day forecast indicates that hot weather will
continue in drought areas, although there is some chance of
increased moisture over the next three months, NOAA's latest
drought advisory said.
   The rains that did occur took place when the high-altitude jet
stream, a powerful wind moving weather patterns across the nation
from the west, moved closer to normal conditions, NOAA reported.
   While the jet had been split in June into two streams passing
north and south of the United States, trapping hot, dry weather in
between, the southern portion faded in July.
   With the decline of the southern jet some wetness from the Gulf
of Mexico was able to move into the Central and Southeastern states.
   The northern jet edged southward, closer to its normal route but
still carrying most Pacific Ocean wetness north of the Canadian
border, the agency said.
   ``The most obvious needs, as indicated by regions with less than
50 percent of normal (rain) since April 1, are in the northern and
southern Mississippi Valley as well as much of the Missouri
Valley,'' NOAA said.
   Despite recent rains, many parts of the nation remain below 50
percent of normal rainfall and continued dryness will expand that
area considerably, officials said.
   In addition, the advisory said, ``dryness in sections of the
northern Rocky Mountains and the High Plains has increased
significantly within the past week and these conditions have been
associated with a number of major forest fires.''
   As of July 23, the agency reported, 59 percent of the nation's
corn and soybean growing areas were suffering from severe or
extreme drought, still below the 89 percent posted in July 1934.
   Even so, drought conditions are comparable with some of the
worst in the 1930s, the agency said.
   Streamflow remains at very low levels over much of the nation,
affecting river traffic, and reservoir levels are generally below
normal, the report said.
</TEXT>
