<1ST_LINE>u i PM-RedSquareFlier 18thLd-Writethru a0766 08-03 0890</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Red Square Flier, 18th Ld-Writethru, a0766,0914</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>German Pilot Rust Released From Prison</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Rust saying his flight was
``not responsible'' action. PICKS up 3rd graf pvs bgng, The Soviet
news ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mathias Rust, the young West
German pilot whose landing in Red Square triggered a Soviet
military shake-up, arrived in Frankfurt today after being freed
from a Soviet prison earlier in the day.
   Rust admitted that his daring flight more than a year ago was
``not responsible'' but contended that his experience had improved
Soviet-West German relations.
   On the flight from Moscow, Rust told The Associated Press that
his landing on Red Square was ``only the beginning'' of his efforts
to draw East and West together.
   ``I will continue the work, but no crimes, only legal things,''
he told the AP.
   Asked if he had it do over again if he would make the
unauthorized flight that drew the Kremlin's ire, he answered: ``No,
not again. It was not responsible.''
   Airport spokesman John Sturm told The Associated Press the
Lufthansa jetliner carrying Rust landed in Frankfurt at 9:24 p.m.
(3:24 p.m. EDT).
   The Soviet news agency Tass earlier reported that Rust ``has
just taken a flight from Moscow to the FRG (Federal Republic of
Germany).''
   A spokesman for the West German Embassy confirmed that Rust was
aboard a Lufthansa jet that left Moscow's Sheremetyevo Airport
shortly after 8 p.m.
   The embasssy spokesman, who demanded anonymity, said Rust was
taken directly to the airport from Lefortovo Prison, where he had
been held since his flight in May 1987.
   Tass said the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the country's
highest executive body, decreed earlier in the day that the
20-year-old Rust ``be freed from further serving his term and
expelled from the Soviet Union.''
   Tass said Rust's release after having served just over a quarter
of a four-year sentence demonstrated the Soviet Union's
``humaneness.'' There was no further explanation for the early
release.
   Tass quoted Rust as saying, ``I realize that I have committed
serious criminal offenses and the fact that the Presidium of the
USSR Supreme Soviet freed me from punishment before I served my
term is an act of humanism.''
   ``I think this also attests to the overall improvement of
relations between our two countries,'' Rust was quoted as saying.
   On May 28, 1987, Rust, then 19, flew a Cessna aircraft to Moscow
from Helsinki, Finland, landing on Red Square.
   He was found guilty Sept. 4, 1987, of illegally entering the
Soviet Union, violating international flight rules, and malicious
hooliganism, and sentenced to four years in a Soviet labor camp.
   He had been at Moscow's Lefortovo Prison until today.
   Tass said Rust told one of its correspondents that he had no
complaints about his treatment in captivity but was eager to return
to his family and friends.
   ``Mathias Rust is Free!'' West Germany's Frankfurter Rundschau
newspaper trumpeted in a banner headline after Rust's release was
announced.
   But West Germany's ZDF television network quoted the
prosecutor's office in the West German city of Itzehoe as saying
that an investigation against Rust was still open. The prosecutor
has been investigating possible charges of endangering air traffic
and fraud against Rust.
   Rust comes from the town of Wedel, six miles west of the
northern port city of Hamburg. An Associated Press reporter tried
to speak with Rust's mother, Monika, today but was turned away from
the family home by three reporters from West Germany's Stern
magazine. The magazine has an exclusive contract with Rust's family
for the rights to Rust's story.
   The family has an unlisted telephone number.
   Officials in West Germany said that West German Foreign Minister
Hans-Dietrich Genscher discussed the case of Rust with Soviet
officials during Genscher's visit to Moscow last week.
   Genscher was in Moscow to prepare for the scheduled October
summit between West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Michael Gerdts, Genscher's spokesman, told reporters that
``Mathias Rust was a topic in talks between the foreign minister
and (Soviet) Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze'' in Moscow.
   A West German government spokesman in Moscow, who spoke on
condition he not be indentified, said the Soviets contacted the
embassy early today to say that Rust would be freed. The source
would not discuss any reasons behind the early release.
   In Bonn, West German government spokesman Norbert Shaefer told
The Associated Press, ``The federal government is pleased with this
step.''
   Rust's dramatic flight shook the foundation of Soviet security
and oiled the way for the ouster of Defense Minister Sergei L.
Sokolov and Air Defense chief Alexander Koldunov.
   Soviet jets scrambled to intercept Rust's light plane when it
was detected crossing into Soviet airspace, but no action was taken
to halt the flight and apparently no word of warning about the
incident was sent forward to Moscow.
   Gorbachev and Sokolov were in Berlin at the time. Two days after
Rust's landing and arrest, Sokolov was sent into retirement for the
lapse and Koldunov was fired.
   Rust told the Soviet court during his trial that he made the
flight to advance understanding between East and West, but the
court ruled that he acted in the interest of self-promotion and
issued a guilty verdict on all counts against him.
</TEXT>
