<2ND_LINE>AM-Refinery Explosion,0331</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Corroded Pipe Caused Explosion That Killed Seven
^By MARK SEGHERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORCO, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corrosion in an 8 inch-wide pipe caused the
May 5 explosion at a Shell Oil refinery that killed seven workers,
the company said Wednesday.
   The pipe, in equipment used break down oil into gasoline,
ruptured, releasing 20,000 pounds of hydrocarbons and causing a
fire and an explosion felt as far as 20 miles away in New Orleans.
   Investigators are trying to find out why the pipe corroded
faster than it should have, plant manager Fred Foster told
reporters during a tour of the refinery Wednesday.
   Checks at other parts of the plant show no danger of a similar
explosion, he added.
   Seven workers died, and 22 were injured, six critically. Shell
said all but one of those critically injured will return to work
soon. The sixth is still recovering from burns over 75 percent of
his body.
   The refinery remains all but shut down, according to Phil
Schwin, superintendent of the Shell Norco complex. Foster said
repairs are being completed and various refinery units would be
phased into use over the next two months.
   ``Now until the latter part of September, we'll be staggering
all these units back on stream,'' Foster said.
   The explosion damaged dozens of homes in Norco and even caused
some window damage in New Orleans, and Shell said Wednesday it has
provided temporary housing to about 200 Norco residents at a
$250,000 cost.
   To date over 9,000 insurance claims have been filed. Of those,
5,200 have been settled at a total cost of $24 million, the company
said.
   The company said about 300 of the 1,600 workers at the Norco
complex went through counseling concerning causes and effects of
the explosion of the catalytic cracker.
   The company said about 300 of the 1,600 workers at the Norco
complex went through counseling concerning causes and effects of
the explosion.
