<HEAD>Explosion Near Military Headquarters Rocks Downtown Johannesburg</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with police saying no injures and
only minor damage; details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion near a military
headquarters rocked downtown Johannesburg Wednesday night, but
caused no injuries and only minor damage, police said.
   The blast occurred about 9:30 p.m. (3:30 p.m. EDT) outside the
Witwatersrand Command, a complex of brick buildings housing the
Johannesburg area military headquarters, police said.
   No one was injured and the blast caused only minor damage to the
buildings, police said, adding that they did not know what caused
the explosion.
   The blast was heard in the downtown offices of The Associated
Press, more than a mile from the scene.
   Police cordoned off several blocks around the site and searched
for bombs, witnesses said.
   In July 1987, a bomb exploded outside the military headquarters
injuring 68 people.
   There have been about 100 bombings in South Africa since a
nationwide state-of-emergency was declared in June 1986. Police
have blamed virtually all of the attacks on the outlawed African
National Congress, the main black guerrilla group attempting to
overthrow the white-led government.
   The ANC, based in Lusaka, Zambia, rarely confirms or denies any
involvement in such attacks.
