<2ND_LINE>AM-Tennessee Primary,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blanton's Comeback Try Highlights Thursday Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL RAWLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Ray Blanton's attempt at a
political comeback highlights Thursday's Tennessee primary ballot,
which also includes a race between two Republicans seeking to
challenge Democratic Sen. James R. Sasser.
   Blanton, 58, who served two years in federal prison for liquor
license conspiracy, faces three other Democrats in the 8th
Congressional District, where Rep. Ed Jones is retiring after 19
years. Jones is backing one of Blanton's opponents.
   ``I have very great expectations,'' Blanton said Wednesday in a
telephone interview. ``I'm very confident.''
   Added his campaign manager, Will J. Pillow: ``It's going to be
the biggest political upset since Truman beat Dewey'' in 1948.
   Blanton, who served six years in Congress from another west
Tennessee district, was elected governor in 1974 and left office in
1979 amid a clemency-for-cash scandal.
   He was never charged in that scandal, but served two years
following his conviction on conspiracy, mail fraud and extortion
charges. He was released in 1986. Blanton's mail fraud convictions
were vacated in line with a U.S. Supreme Court decision. He is
appealing the conspiracy and extortion convictions. His rights to
vote and hold office were restored last year by a state judge.
   In the GOP Senate primary, Alice Algood, a party activist from
Columbia, faces Bill Andersen, a Kingsport lawyer. Sasser, seeking
a third term, is unopposed for renomination.
   In other congressional primaries, Democrat Harold Ford, the
state's only black congressman, is opposed in the all-Memphis 9th
District for the eighth time by Mark Flanagan, a businessman. Ford,
whose trial on bank fraud charges has not been scheduled, has said
his indictment hasn't caused him any problems in the campaign.
   And Democratic Rep. Marilyn Lloyd, seeking her eighth term from
the 3rd District, faces opposition from newcomers Lamar Lasley and
Walter Ward. All are from the Chattanooga area.
</TEXT>
