<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WestBankDeath     08-03 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-West Bank Death,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Probing Death of First American in Palestinian Uprising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is investigating the death
of a man believed to be the first American to die in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank since the Palestinian revolt began last
December, the State Department said Wednesday.
   ``We deeply regret the death of Mr. Ribhi Barakat Kayed on July
30 in an incident involving Israeli soldiers,'' said department
spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley.
   She said the U.S. consulate in Jerusalem was in contact with
members of Kayed's family and was interviewing witnesses in an
attempt to determine what happened last Saturday. Kayed is from
Columbus, Ohio.
   The U.S. Embassy in Tel Aviv ``has raised this tragic incident
with the government of Israel'' and will do so again once the
investigation is completed, she said.
   Mrs. Oakley said Kayed was the first American of Palestinian
origin to die in the uprising that began Dec. 8. Since then, more
than 260 Palestinians have been killed in clashes with Israeli
soldiers.
   Kayed's family alleges that the 67-year-old man was pulled out
of his house by Israeli soldiers and ordered to clean up
anti-Israeli graffiti on a nearby wall. While complying, Kayed
collapsed and died, they said.
   His relatives said the soldiers refused to allow Kayed to get
his medication although they were told he had a heart condition.
   The Israeli army, disputing the claim, said soldiers had told
Kayed's grandson to clean the slogans and that Kayed himself was
asked to go into the house. He probably died of a heart attack, the
army said.
   George Moses, chairman of the Council of Presidents Of National
Arab American Associations, said the State Department's response
was inadequate.
   Moses accused Richard Schifter, assistant secretary of state for
human rights, of failing to take a more forceful public stance on
Israeli human rights abuses. ``We believe this abject failure led
directly to this incident,'' he said.
</TEXT>
