<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Palestinian     08-03 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Palestinian,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Confirmed As Man Sought By United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals council ruled Wednesday that a
Palestinian held here is the man wanted in the United States for
the 1982 in-flight bombing of a Pan Am jetliner, opening the way
for his eventual extradition.
   Police have said his imprisonment may have figured in the
terrorist attack on a Greek cruise ship last month.
   Palestine Liberation Organization officials said they would
fight extradition.
   ``The Palestinian held in prison and whose extradition is being
sought by the United States, is Mohammed Rashid ... not Mohammed
Hamdan as he claims,'' said the ruling, issued by the three-member
council after a closed-door session.
   The council decides whether cases should proceed for action. It
was convened to determine the identity of the prisoner, arrested by
police at Athens airport May 29 after a tip from the U.S. Embassy.
   The United States has asked for the extradition of Mohammed
Rashid, 39, on charges of planting a bomb aboard a Pan Am jumbo jet
in 1982. The blast killed a Japanese teen-ager and injured 15
people as the jet flew over Hawaii.
   The appeals council accepted the finding of District Attorney
Ioannis Lambropoulos and rejected Rashid's claim that police had
arrested the wrong man.
   An extradition hearing was set for Thursday. Under Greek law,
however, Rashid cannot be extradited until he has served a
seven-month jail sentence for entering Greece on a forged Syrian
passport in the name of Mohammed Hamdan. The Palestinian was
convicted of the passport charge and sentenced on July 11.
   Police theorized that a machine-gun and hand grenade attack
aboard the City of Poros cruise ship on July 11 may have been a
failed attempt to take passengers hostage and force the
Palestinian's release. The attack killed nine people and injured
98. The vessel was carrying 471 foreign passengers.
   Greek authorities have been stymied in their investigation of
the attack.
   U.S. officials have said Rashid also was involved in a bomb
blast aboard a TWA jetliner flying over Greece in 1986. Four
Americans were killed in the explosion, but the TWA bombing is not
mentioned in the extradition request.
   The diplomatic adviser of the PLO mission in Greece, Anwar
Akraa, told the appeals council the Palestinian was a member of the
PLO, which knew him as Mohammed Hamdan.
   Rashid, dressed in tan trousers and shirt, refused to comment
after testifying before the appeals council.
   He was identified when his fingerprints matched those of
Mohammed Rashid, jailed in Greece from 1973-76 on narcotics
smuggling charges. His prints also matched Interpol records, police
said.
</TEXT>
