<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissingExplosives     08-03 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missing Explosives,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Police Boost Effort To Find Military Explosives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COVENTRY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divers searched the Willimantic River on
Wednesday for missing military explosives, including a projectile
that could kill people within 150 feet, authorities said.
   State police said some of the explosives, discovered Monday
night by a passer-by on the side of the river, could have been
picked up by souvenir hunters.
   ``We've called all the newspapers and radio stations to try to
get the word out that people shouldn't go near these things,'' said
police spokeswoman Marcy Stamm.
   Some explosives were recovered on the bank of the river in a
remote area Tuesday after the man who found them brought police to
the site.
   The man, whom police would not identify, had apparently taken a
60mm mortar and a TNT-packed cannon round home with him before a
friend advised him to notify police.
   When he took police back to the site, the man said some of the
explosives were missing.
   Stamm said state police believe an additional 60mm mortar, eight
smoke cannisters and seven detonators remain missing. The 60mm
mortar is a 13-inch, cone-shaped projectile with fins that is
packed with three-quarters of a pound of high explosives, she said.
   About four or five divers and the state police Emergency
Services Unit bomb squad were searching the river and the area
around its banks, she said.
   Agents from the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
and U.S. Army bomb technicians were trying to trace the origin of
the explosives.
   Authorities believe the explosives were stolen and recently left
along the banks of the river. The recovered explosives, marked with
serial numbers, were not rusty and appeared new, state police
Trooper John Duley said.
