<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Chavez     08-03 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chavez,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctor Says Labor Leader's Health In Danger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DELANO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A water-only fast by United Farm Workers
President Cesar Chavez is endangering his health and he faces the
threat of kidney failure, a doctor who examined him said.
   Chavez's uric acid is three times the acceptable level, said Dr.
Augusto Ortiz, who also examined Chavez during a 1972 fast. The
fast entered its 18th day Wednesday and Chavez has not said how
long it will continue. He went 25 days without food in 1968 and
again in 1972 to advance farm worker issues.
   ``If this level is not brought down, it can lead to serious
complications, including kidney failure,'' Ortiz said in a
statement released by union officials.
   Chavez is fasting to promote the union's boycott of California
table grapes. He has no contract among those growers and is
demanding that use of five pesticides be abolished. In a July 25
statement, Chavez said he began the fast after becoming
disillusioned about the problems created by pesticide use.
   He claims pesticides have poisoned croplands and caused cancer
in residents in farm towns, such as nearby McFarland where 13
children have been diagnosed with cancer.
   Children of the late Sen. Robert F. Kennedy plan to visit Chavez
on Thursday in this community 150 miles north of Los Angeles to
support the fast, union spokeswoman Lorena Parlee said. Kennedy was
with Chavez in 1968 when he broke his fast.
   Chavez has lost 10 pounds since he began the fast on midnight
July 16, Dr. Fidel Huerta said.
</TEXT>
