<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Central America,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Claims Diplomatic Victory On Latin America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high State Department official, disputing
news accounts, said Thursday the foreign ministers of four Central
American countries shared a U.S. commitment to ``authentic
democracy'' in Nicaragua.
   Morris Busby, special U.S. envoy to the region, said the United
States was pleased with the results of the session Monday in
Guatemala with Secretary of State George P. Shultz. ``Reporting
this was a failed initiative just wasn't true,'' he said.
   Busby said the statement issued after Shultz's meeting with the
four ministers represented ``a shared commitment to authentic
democracy'' even though it addressed issues in broad terms.
   The communique did not mention Nicaragua and was limited to
general support for democratic principles. News accounts from
Guatemala said Shultz and the foreign ministers of Costa Rica, El
Salvador, Guatemala and Honduras had failed to agree on a strong
denunciation of Nicaragua.
   Shultz will return to the region next Wednesday after touring
South America for meetings with the leaders of the four Central
American countries.
   Busby told reporters at a briefing that the ministers had
decided not to issue an ``analysis'' of the Nicaraguan situation.
``There was a disagreement over whether it was too bold,'' he said.
   But, Busby said, ``I would disagree that we came away
disappointed. The results the meeting produced were important.''
   Shultz did not seek a meeting with Nicaraguan President Daniel
Ortega and does not plan to talk to him when they attend a
presidential inauguration ceremony in Ecuador or when Shultz
returns to Central America.
   Busby said U.S. policy rules out a meeting with Sandinista
officials until progress is made in their negotiations with the
U.S.-backed guerrillas, known as Contras.
</TEXT>
