<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL-Bakker,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bakker Says PTL Documents Destroyed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PTL founder Jim Bakker said under oath
that thousands of internal ministry documents and letters have been
altered, buried or destroyed since he resigned in March 1987.
   Bakker, who PTL records say received nearly $8.3 million in
salary, bonuses and perks in 1983-87, also said he was underpaid.
   Bakker made the comments in a sworn deposition as he prepared to
defend himself against a $52 million lawsuit by PTL, which charges
he grossly mismanaged the TV ministry.
   ``I have reason to dispute all records of PTL at this time ...
because of hostile people who took over Heritage USA,'' Bakker said
in a July 18 deposition, sworn answers to attorneys' questions. He
also was deposed on July 22.
   The Charlotte Observer said in a story in Wednesday's editions
it obtained the depositions, which have not been filed court.
   The PTL lawsuit alleges that Bakker and former aide David
Taggart took millions of dollars from PTL for their personal use,
although they knew the ministry was in financial trouble. Bakker
resigned following revelations of his tryst with former church
secretary Jessica Hahn.
   The ministry has been reorganizing under Chapter 11 bankruptcy
proceedings since June 1987 and must sell the Heritage USA theme
park and its other assets to pay debts. Bankruptcy trustee M.C.
``Red'' Benton has said he expects to recommend a buyer this month.
   The suit is scheduled for trial Sept. 12 in U.S. Bankruptcy
Court in Columbia.
   In his deposition, Bakker stated:
   _ ``People ... have come to my office to tell me that they have
lied under oath to destroy me.''
   _ ``Corporate records were destroyed wholesaley (sic).''
   _ ``Also, tens of thousands of letters personally addressed to
me ... are buried on these grounds.''
   Bakker said the destruction of documents and letters was ordered
by subordinates of the Rev. Jerry Falwell, who became PTL's
chairman in March 1987, after Bakker resigned in a sex and money
scandal. Falwell served until October 1987.
   Falwell spokesman Mark DeMoss denied Bakker's allegations.
   ``It would not have been in our best interest to destroy any
documents,'' DeMoss said. ``We couldn't get our hands on documents
fast enough, that we were trying to preserve, because so much of
the documents and records there are not the kinds of things, I
think, Jim Bakker would want preserved. ... A lot of them were
pretty incriminating.''
   Bakker attorney Jim Toms told PTL lawyers that he will seek a
court order to excavate the site where Bakker claims many documents
are buried.
</TEXT>
