<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 2140EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TreasuryBorrowing     08-03 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Treasury Borrowing,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Treasury Announces Quarterly Auctions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department announced Wednesday it
will borrow $29 billion to replenish government coffers next week,
but for the first time in six years will not issue 30-year bonds.
   Every three months, the government holds three debt sales to
finance the $2.5 trillion national debt. It sells three-year notes,
10-year notes and 30-year bonds.
   Charles O. Sethness, assistant Treasury secretary for domestic
finance, said the government will not issue 30-year bonds this time
because it has used practically all of its congressional authority
to do so.
   House and Senate bills that include provisions freeing the
Treasury to issue long-term debt have passed committees in both
chambers. However, the bills must pass both the full House and
Senate and any differences would have to be reconciled in
negotiations between the two bodies.
   ``We are hopeful the Congress will act soon,'' Sethness said.
``... When bond authority legislation is enacted, we expect to
return to our regular schedule.''
   The auctions next week call for:
   _$11 billion in three-year notes in minimum denominations of
$5,000 to be auctioned Tuesday.
   _$11 billion in 10-year notes in minimum denominations of $1,000
to be auctioned Wednesday.
   _$7 billion in 248-day cash management bills in minimum
denominations of $1,000 to be issued Thursday.
   The $22 billion in notes includes $14.8 billion to pay off
maturing securities and $7.2 billion in new cash.
   The note auctions are about in line with analysts' expectations
and represented a $4 billion reduction from the last quarterly
auctions, when $26 billion was raised.
   Sethness said the cash management bills will be repaid on April
20 and are intended help smooth government revenue flows, which
normally surge in April as people pay their income taxes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
