<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Bush Not `Morally Fit' for Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL ANN RIHA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Democratic presidential candidate Jesse
Jackson said Wednesday that George Bush is not ``morally fit'' to
be president because the likely Republican nominee has failed to
support civil rights legislation.
   ``Throughout 7{ years of the most miserable civil rights record
of any recent administration, Mr. Bush has chosen not to say a
mumblin' word,'' Jackson told a crowd of about 4,000 at the
National Urban League Convention.
   ``Mr. Bush opposed the Civil Rights Restoration Act. Anyone who
opposed the Civil Rights Restoration Act is not morally fit to lead
this nation.''
   Jackson listed his ``10 clear reasons'' why he supports
Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis over Bush and urged those in
attendance to vote Democratic in November.
   Jackson cited Dukakis' support for civil rights, child care,
education, statehood for the District of Columbia and total
economic isolation of the apartheid South African government by the
world community. He also noted Dukakis' opposition to aid to the
Nicaraguan Contra rebels and unreasonable defense spending.
   ``Like Moses, if we use our rod we can part the seas and move
closer to Canaan Land,'' Jackson said. ``But if we don't use our
rod, our vote, and drop it, it will turn into a snake and go to
Washington and bite us.''
   Jackson said he agrees with Dukakis' view of government, saying
it is an instrument of public service. On the other hand, Bush
believes government is ``an instrument to enrich the few and starve
the many,'' he said.
   The former Democratic candidate said his unsuccessful bid for
the presidential nomination was a victory. ``Victory is that the
reasonable expectations of our leaders and our children have been
raised,'' he said.
   The crowd stood and cheered as Jackson shouted, ``I may not get
to the White House, but our children will, our children will, our
children will ...''
   Jackson wouldn't detail his plans for the future, but told the
crowd, ``I don't want a job.'' He said his job is taking their case
before the people.
   Asked after the address to be more specific, he told reporters,
``Unemployed people need a job. I don't need a job.''
