<1ST_LINE>u a AM-YonkersDeseg Bjt   08-03 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yonkers Deseg, Bjt,0755</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Considers Layoffs in Light of Contempt Finding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city and three councilmen paid $1,600
in contempt fines Wednesday, while the mayor warned that city
workers could be laid off this month unless Yonkers complies with a
federal housing desegregation order.
   U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand found the city and three
council members in contempt Tuesday for refusing to build
low-income housing units. Yonkers' $100 fine will double daily and
would wipe out the city's $337 million budget in 22 days.
   With a majority on the council opposed to the order _ and
unmoved so far by their own $500-a-day fines _ the city hoped to
get a quick stay of the contempt finding.
   State officials, meanwhile, considered a plan to seize control
of the city's purse strings and remove members of the Yonkers City
Council.
   Yonkers, the state's fourth-largest city with a population of
just under 200,000, has been in a legal tug-of-war with Sand since
1985, when the judge found the city liable for intentionally
segregating its housing and schools over a 40-year period.
   Abutting New York City, Yonkers is 21 square miles of diversity,
ranging from rundown tenements to homes with lush lawns in
neighborhoods proud of their Scarsdale and Bronxville ZIP codes.
   Some residents opposed to the desegregation plan have
aggressively battled the council. Members were sent bullets in the
mail when the council approved a consent decree in the case in
January.
   ``If you don't want to change your environment, a judge
shouldn't do it, for you,'' said Vincent DeMarco, a resident for
all his 21 years. ``We want to keep this place decent. I don't know
how the judge can say a vote isn't right.''
   Allen Cunningham moved here two years ago from Brooklyn.
   ``I don't think what he (Sand) did was really right,'' said
Cunningham, who is black. ``We can only look, listen and learn. It
can help blacks who are trying to make a decent life. My 3-year-old
son should have a decent place to play, not some drug-infested
place. But it may make matters worse between black and white.''
   A school integration program is entering its third year, but
city officials have refused to build 200 units of low-income
housing on the city's predominantly white east side and 800 units
of low- and moderate-income housing throughout the city.
   On Monday, the City Council voted 4-3 not to endorse a package
of bonuses, financial incentives and zoning variances to attract
developers to build the 800 units. Three of the four council
members voting in the majority were found in contempt; a decision
on the fourth is pending because he asked the court for time to get
a lawyer.
   Yonkers' counsel, Paul Pickelle, said a transcript of Tuesday's
contempt hearing and other documents on the city's request for a
stay were sent to Judge J. Daniel Mahoney of the 2nd U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals.
   Mayor Nicholas Wasiscko, one of the three council members who
voted for the housing plan, warned that two-week layoff notices
would be sent to municipal workers Friday, but City Manager Neil
DeLuca said he would wait at least a week before preparing what he
calls a ``doomsday scenario'' for layoffs of the city's estimated
1,800 municipal workers.
   ``I don't want to scare everyone,'' DeLuca said. ``Come Aug. 16
or Aug. 17, I will notify 70 to 80 percent of the non-essential
work force that they're laid off. We won't get to police or
firefighters until Aug. 22.''
   The city manager's office has ordered city workers not to talk
to reporters.
   Wasiscko said Monday's defiance was the result of
``frustration'' over the issue. He noted that Yonkers has 6,800
units of low-income housing while neighboring suburbs such as
Scarsdale have none.
   DeLuca said he was hoping for action by the Emergency Financial
Control Board, the fiscal watchdog installed by the state after
Yonkers' 1984 brush with bankruptcy.
   The Control Board can take over the power of spending from the
City Council to implement the housing plan and can recommend
council members' removal from office. The board planned to meet
Thursday.
   Sand urged Gov. Mario Cuomo, who has the power to remove elected
officials from office, to step in and help resolve the crisis.
   But Cuomo spokesman Gary Fryer said, ``At the moment, there is
no need for us to act.''
</TEXT>
