<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Teamsters 1stLd-Writethru a0758 08-03 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0758,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Teamsters Chief Fires 2 Top Regional Officials, Attorney</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds. Subs graf 4, ``Mathis, who, to CORRECT election date</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than three weeks after assuming office in
a hotly contested election, new Teamsters President William J.
McCarthy has fired two of the union's top regional officials along
with its chief attorney.
   Teamster officials confirmed Wednesday that McCarthy a day
earler replaced Robert Holmes and Edward Lawson as directors of the
union's central and Canadian conferences.
   Both men, who retain their elected seats on the union's
18-member, policy-setting executive board and titles as
international vice presidents, had supported Secretary-Treasurer
Weldon Mathis for the top Teamsters job after the death last month
of Jackie Presser.
   Mathis, who was Presser's designated heir and had served as
interim president while Presser was undergoing brain surgery, was
defeated by McCarthy on a 9-8 vote by the Teamsters' executive
board July. 15.
   At a board meeting Tuesday, McCarthy won approval on a 10-8 vote
to replace Holmes, 76, of Detroit, as director of the union's
13-state, 600,000-member Central Council with Daniel C. Ligurotis
of Chicago.
   Ligurotis, who started his Teamster career 44 years ago as a
truck driver's helper in Chicago, was elected to the union's
executive board last summer.
   He had voted for McCarthy in a successful bid by old guard East
Coast Teamster leaders to deny the presidency to Mathis, who worked
with Presser in trying to attack the corruption stigma that has
plagued the union for decades through gradual reforms and
aggressive public and government relations.
   Holmes, a confidant of the former Teamster President James R.
Hoffa since the early 1930s organizing wars in the Midwest, had
favored calling a special convention of 2,000 union delegates from
around the country to pick a successor for Presser.
   Lawson, 57, of Vancouver, British Columbia, had been head of the
union's 200,000-member Canadian Conference since its creation in
1976 and has been a vice president and board member of the union
since 1971.
   McCarthy engineered his replacement by Louis Lacroix of
Montreal, who has been head of the union's brewery and soft drinks
division in Canada since 1975.
   Lawson said Wednesday he was ``very angry'' and added: ``It's
not the kind of thing you'd expect a trade union to do.''
   The new Teamsters president also succeeded Tuesday in elevating
his top assistant at Local 25 in Boston, which McCarthy also heads,
to the vacant seat left on the union's board by Presser's death
last month.
   Frank Hackett, 54, of Sommerville, Mass., a business agent in
the Boston local since 1973, was elected as the union's 16th vice
president on a 9-8 vote, with Mathis loyalists opposing him.
   Immediately upon Hackett's election, McCarthy then won 10-8
votes from the board approving his ouster of Holmes and Lawson,
according to sources in the union who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Officials at the Teamsters' headquarters here would not comment
on details of the continuing power struggle within the union's
heirarchy.
   But spokesman Duke Zeller said the conference chairmen, unlike
elected board members, serve at the will of the union's president.
   ``He has the right under the union's constitution to select who
serves under him,'' Zeller said of McCarthy. ``This is not unusual;
it's been done, I think, with every change in the presidency.''
   Last week, McCarthy fired Cleveland attorney and Presser
loyalist John R. Climaco as the union's general counsel and
replaced him with James T. Grady.
   Climaco had been in charged of preparing the union's defense to
a civil suit filed by the Justice Department in May to replace its
entire executive board, which the government contends is under the
control of mob figures, with a court-appointed trustee.
   He also was Presser's chief defense lawyer on a criminal
embezzlement and racketeering case that never went to trial because
of the former Teamster president's long illness.
   Meanwhile, Zeller said the union will reopen talks next week in
Washington with the car haulers industry. A new proposed three-year
contract covering some 20,000 Teamsters who work for automobile
transporters was rejected by 3-1 vote last month.
   Zeller said 12-member negotiating committees for the two sides
are scheduled to meet next Thursday for the first time since the
contract's rejection.
</TEXT>
