<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen-Finances     08-03 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen-Finances,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Upholds FEC Decision to Release Funds to Dukakis-Bentsen
Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Wednesday upheld the
payment of federal campaign funds to Democrat Michael Dukakis'
presidential campaign even though running mate Lloyd Bentsen is
also seeking re-election to the Senate.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia
rejected a challenge to the Federal Election Commission action
releasing $46 million in federal funding due the Dukakis-Bentsen
ticket.
   Bentsen's Senate campaign opponent, Republican Rep. Beau
Boulter, and the National Republican Senatorial Committee, which
helps GOP Senate candidates win election, asked the court to block
the Democrats from spending the money, saying the dual campaign
gave Bentsen an unfair financial advantage.
   The FEC, however, said the Republicans failed to show that there
is anything illegal about Bentsen's decision to run for both the
vice presidency and re-election to his Senate seat, as allowed
under Texas law.
   Because of the dual campaign, Bentsen would be able to spend the
$4 million in private money raised for his Senate contest on top of
the federal money for his vice presidential campaign, which is
limited for both parties.
   Blocking the Democrats from spending their federal money would
``irreparably harm'' their campaign, the FEC said.
   The committee asked the FEC to withhold the $46 million in
federal funding due the Dukakis-Bentsen ticket, but the commission
two weeks ago voted 6-0 to reject that request. The money was then
transferred from the Treasury to the campaign.
   The three-judge panel rejected the Republican group's contention
that the FEC's action was arbitrary and capricious.
   ``We conclude that petitioners' allegations are insufficient on
their face to warrant a revocation of the certification'' of
payment of money to the Dukakis-Bentsen campaign, the court said.
   The brief order was issued by Circuit Judges Spotswood Robinson,
Laurence Silberman and Douglas Ginsburg.
</TEXT>
