<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 2132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SuperfundCollection     08-03 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Superfund Collection,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Announces Largest Cost Recovery to Date in Superfund History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government said Wednesday it has
reached a $33.1 million settlement with 48 companies over illegally
dumped waste at four New England sites. The agreement includes the
largest cost recovery ever won under the Superfund law.
   The settlement, the culmination of a nine-year joint state and
federal investigation, was disclosed in a civil complaint filed
Wednesday by the Environmental Protection Agency seeking damages
from 25 other companies that did not cooperate with authorities.
   ``We're sending a message that says if you illegally dispose of
illegal waste, you're going to get found, you're going to get
caught and you'll have to pay for it,'' said Daniel S. Greenbaum,
commissioner of the state Department of Environmental Quality
Engineering.
   The settlement is described technically as a ``proposal''
because federal law requires a 30-day public comment period, though
the parties involved have already agreed to the conditions.
   The settlement involves major companies who were customers of
Cannons Engineering Corp., and the cleanup of Cannon hazardous
waste sites in Bridgewater and Plymouth, Mass., and Nashua and
Londonderry, N.H. It includes the recovery of $17 million in
cleanup costs spent by the government at the sites, the largest
recovery amount in Superfund history.
   Although Cannons conducted the illegal dumping without notifying
its customers, officials said, Superfund law holds that all parties
connected with illegal dumping of hazardous waste are liable for
cleanup costs.
   Cannons, which has gone out of business, is one of the companies
that has refused to settle with federal officials and is named in
the U.S. district court complaint.
   The settling parties also agreed to finish cleaning up three of
the four sites, work estimated to cost $16.1 million.
   The EPA previously reached $14.6 million in settlements with
companies responsible for smaller amounts of waste dumping at the
sites.
   ``This should slam dunk them (illegal dumpers) to the fullest
extent of the law,'' said EPA regional administrator Michael
Deland. ``We're saying we can't tolerate this anymore.''
   In Washington, D.C., Assistant Attorney General Roger J.
Marzulla of the Justice Department's Land and Natural Resources
Division said the ``four sites involved some of the most urgent
hazardous waste problems in New England and the government took
decisive action.''
   The illegal dumping stemmed from problems that began shortly
after Cannons bought property in Bridgewater in 1974 to handle,
store and incinerate chemical waste.
   A few years later, Cannons began taking in more waste than it
could handle in Bridgewater and began illegally shipping the
overflow to the three other sites, in Plymouth and New Hampshire.
However, Cannons officials reported to authorities that the excess
waste was actually being incinerated at Bridgewater.
   According to EPA spokesman Michael Thomas, the surplus waste was
moved stealthily out of the Bridgewater site after dark and taken
to Nashua, where it was dumped in the ground near a stream.
Officials first discovered the problem in 1979 when groundwater
contamination became so severe that emissions were noticeable in
the air rising from the stream.
   The dumping of waste in Londonderry was discovered when
residents notified environmental authorities of a peculiar
``frothing'' at a stream. Residential drinking water supplies were
threatened and had to be replaced at both sites.
   The waste in Plymouth was contained in storage tanks that began
leaking, Thomas said.
   In 1980, state officials revoked Cannons' hazardous waste
license because of alleged reporting and hazardous waste
violations. Five people associated with Cannons, including J. Scott
Cannon, one of the owners, served brief terms in state prison,
Thomas said.
   Among the companies included in the settlement announced
Wednesday were Globe Newspaper Co., Polaroid Corp., Monsanto Co.,
Clean Harbors of Braintree and Natick, Atlantic Richfield Co. and
the General Electric Co.
   EPA officials said they have spent $30 million so far in initial
cleanup of the sites and described them all as ``stabilized.'' The
money recovered by the EPA will cover those costs and go toward
finishing the cleanup.
</TEXT>
