<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola-Anglicans 1stLd-Writethru a0750 08-03 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola-Anglicans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0750,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anglican Bishops Support South African Withdrawal From Namibia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with report urging better relations
between Jews and Christians. No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Angola, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTERBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's Anglican bishops on
Wednesday passed a resolution calling for South Africa's withdrawal
from South-West Africa.
   Also Wednesday, a report to the bishops urged Christians to
develop closer links with Jews to prevent another Nazi holocaust.
   The resolution on South Africa, adopted at the bishops'
conference in Lambeth, came a day after South Africa proposed an
Aug. 10 cease-fire in the Angolan war. The truce would lead to
withdrawal of foreign troops and independence for South
African-administered South-West Africa, also known as Namibia.
   The bishops' resolution was proposed by the Bishop of Stepney,
Jim Thompson, in the name of the 70 million members of the Anglican
Church.
   The archbishop of Canterbury, Dr. Robert Runcie, is to send the
message of support to the Geneva peace talks.
   Thompson claimed South African troops in Namibia were fighting
close to schools, involving children in the crossfire.
   ``Young people have been kidnapped or seduced into joining
armies. Attacks on the church have brought a severe crisis,'' he
said.
   Bishop David Russell, of Grahamstown in South Africa, seconded
the resolution and called on the conference to urge Western
governments to monitor peace in Namibia.
   The report calling for improved Judeo-Christian relations
stemmed from a proposal by Bishop of Oxford Richard Harries to
broaden dialogue among the Anglican community, Jews and Moslems.
   The proposal said the three religions have much in common and
should work together to promote human rights and prevent prejudice
leading to tragedies like the World War II holocaust, when six
million Jews were killed.
   ``In order to combat centuries of anti-Jewish teaching,
Christians must develop programs of teaching, preaching and common
social action which eradicate prejudice,'' the report said.
   The holocaust had seeds in centuries of ``anti-Jewish prejudice
promulgated by leaders, church and state ... in which the evil weed
of Nazism was able to take root,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
