<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Homeless     08-03 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House OKs Two-Year Extention of Homeless Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Wednesday overwhelmingly approved
legislation to extend federal aid for the homeless for two years.
   The bill, passed 333-80, authorizes $642.5 million for the 1989
fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1, and ``such sums as may be
necessary'' for fiscal 1990.
   The measure reauthorizes the Stewart B. McKinney Homeless
Assistance Act, enacted last year, for emergency shelter and food,
health care, education and job training. The law is named for a
late Republican congressman from Connecticut.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, said before the vote: ``The
homeless initiatives passed by Congress last year are working. But
far more needs to be done.
   ``While many homeless citizens are being helped, the total
homeless population continues to increase at an annual rate of 20
percent in major urban areas,'' he said. ``Two out of three cities
have to deny services to homeless applicants because of a lack of
public resources.''
   Wright said homelessness, unlike other afflictions, can be cured.
   ``We have located the cause of this condition in the large cuts
that were made in low-income housing and mental health services,''
he said. ``And we have found the remedy in the programs for
affordable housing, health care and edcuation programs contained in
homeless assistance acts.''
   The House approved the measure after defeating, 215-203, an
amendment introduced by Reps. Marge Roukema, R-N.J., and Thomas J.
Ridge, R-Pa., that would have combined all the funds for housing
and shelter programs into a single block grant, effective in the
second year of the authorization.
   Similar legislation is pending in the Senate.
</TEXT>
