<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HurricaneFabio     08-03 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane Fabio,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forecasters Call Hurricane Potential Threat to Hawaii</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Fabio, packing 155 mph wind gusts, was
labeled a potential threat to Hawaii Wednesday but forecasters said
it was too soon to tell whether the storm would reach the island
chain.
   At 8 a.m. Wednesday (2 p.m. EDT), the storm was 900 miles
east-southeast of Honolulu, moving west at 15 mph, said Clarence
Lee, a National Weather Service forecaster in Honolulu.
   ``Hurricane Fabio continues to be a very potent and dangerous
hurricane and is considered to be a potential threat to the
Hawaiian Islands,'' Lee said.
   Fabio's maximum sustained winds were estimated near 125 mph with
hurricane force winds of at least 74 mph extending out 75 miles
from the center. Tropical storm strength winds _ 39 mph to 73 mph _
extended out 180 miles from the center.
   ``This is one of the strongest hurricanes in the area in quite a
while,'' said Hans Rosendal, a weather service meteorogist.
   The storm was expected to continue on its current course for the
next 24 hours with little change in strength, Lee said.
   The last major storm to hit Hawaii was Hurricane Iwa, which
brushed the island of Oahu and roared over Kauai and Niihau islands
with winds up to 117 mph in November 1982, causing $234 million
damage.
   If Fabio stays on course, Lee said, the National Weather Service
would consider issuing hurricane watches or warnings later
Wednesday.
   The center of the storm would pass 50 miles south of Hawaii, the
southernmost island in the chain, on Friday if the storm maintains
its heading and speed, Rosendal said.
   Officials expect to have an updated satellite reading of the
hurricane's position around 4 p.m. Wednesday (10 p.m. EDT).
   While the storm was still hundreds of miles away, the islands
were expected to begin feeling its effects. Surf as high as 15 feet
was expected on the southeast shore of Hawaii Island and
larger-than-normal waves were forecast for all Hawaiian islands.
</TEXT>
