<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Iran-Contra     08-03 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran-Contra Prosecutor Asks Ruling On Classified Documents
Disclosure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecutor in the Iran-Contra case asked
the judge Wednesday to order Oliver L. North to get more specific
about what government secrets he wants to disclose at his trial or
bar the ex-White House aide from revealing any classified
information.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh said the 265-page notice
that North had filed Monday under the Classified Information
Procedures Act flouted both the law and an order issued earlier by
U.S. District Court Judge Gerhard A. Gesell.
   ``This telephone book-size submission is merely the latest move
in the defendants' struggle to have this trial postponed and to
subvert the procedures of this court,'' Walsh said in a brief filed
in U.S. District Court.
   Walsh said the notice ``merely recites an inventory ... of
virtually all of the hundreds of thousands of classified documents
the defendant has received in discovery.''
   Walsh contended that the classified information statute requires
a specific notice of the exact nature of top secret information the
defendant intends to introduce at trial.
   The law was enacted by Congress to prevent defendants in
criminal cases from scuttling the prosecution by threatening to
disclose unspecified government secrets at trial.
   Walsh said the vague nature of North's filing was tantamount to
the so-called ``gray-mail'' that the law was intended to prevent.
   ``North has failed to describe even one piece of classified
information that he expects to disclose in trial,'' Walsh said.
``The index reveals no more than an obvious fact that the court and
the government already knew: many of the documents produced in
discovery contain classified information.''
   North, a former National Security Council aide, is charged with
conspiring with former national security advisor John M.
Poindexter, and arms dealer Albert Hakim and retired Air Force Maj.
Gen. Richard V. Secord to illegally divert U.S.-Iran arms sales
profits to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   Gesell has already ruled that North should be allowed to examine
vast quantities of classified documents to try to show he was
acting with permission of higher officials in the Reagan
administration.
   The problems posed by the classified documents prompted Walsh on
Tuesday to suggest holding two trials for North. The prosecutor
suggested deferring action on the central conspiracy charges while
efforts are made to devise procedures for disclosing classified
information in court.
   Walsh suggested that Gesell proceed to try North on 13 other
charges of making false statements to Congress, obstructing justice
and illegally enriching himself.
   The North trial is set to begin Sept. 20 but Gesell is
considering a defense motion to postpone it until after the
presidential election campaign.
   Separate trials have already been ordered for his co-defendants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880803-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 1930EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Gulf     08-03 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Asks U.S. Apology in Light of Findings on Airliner Downing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's delegation to U.N. peace talks said
Wednesday that the reported findings of human error in the downing
of an Iranian airliner prove Iran's contentions and called again
for a U.S. apology and reparations.
   ``This report has proved what we have said until now ... and so
we believe the United States has full responsibility in this
connection,'' Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati told
reporters in answer to a question.
   Also on Wednesday, Velayati lodged a formal protest with the
Security Council over Iraq's latest alleged use of chemical warfare
and said the council should impose sanctions against the Baghdad
government.
   Velayati met Security Council President Li Luye of China for
more than an hour on the issue.
   Reporters asked Velayati about reports that U.N. peace talks
with Iran and Iraq were deadlocked.
   ``No comment,'' he said, but added that Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar has not said a stalemate existed in efforts to end
the 8-year-old war.
   Iraq demands immediate, face-to-face talks with Iran before a
truce. Iran is resisting and the U.N. chief is seeking a compromise.
   The U.S. envoy to the United Nations, Ambassador Vernon A.
Walters, told a news conference Wednesday that Perez de Cuellar was
concentrating on obtaining Iraq's agreement before declaring a
cease-fire.
   Iraq says it won't stop shooting if the secretary-general
declares a truce without its consent.
   In the airliner disaster, the United States says the warship
Vincennes shot down an Iranian Airbus on July 3, killing all 290
people aboard, because the crew mistakenly believed it to be a
hostile Iranian F-14 warplane.
   But a Navy investigation, as reported by ABC and the New York
Times, found that the crew misinterpreted correct data from the
ship's sophisticated detection system and believed they were about
to be attacked.
   Iranian Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati would not say
Wednesday if he thought the airliner's destruction was
premeditated, as Iran charged earlier.
   ``Those people reponsible for reading instruments should have
had sufficient training. Otherwise we wonder why they were put
before that Aegis (system of radar and identification),'' he said.
   ``The findings ... once again prove that what we said from the
very beginning was actually what happened,'' said Mohammad Javad
Zarif, counselor at the Iranian Mission and delegation spokesman.
   He said the reported findings prove ``there could be no mistake
with regard to the nature of the plane, the fact that it was
ascending, rather than descending, that it was flying at a
prescribed altitude within (assigned) corridors.''
   ``All claims have come true and now it is time for the United
States to act responsibly,'' he said.
   Zarif, speaking by telephone, said the United States should pay
reparations and issue ``a clear apology for the murder of 290
innocent people.''
   He said the United States also should remove the source of
tension, referring to the presence of U.S. warships in the Persian
Gulf.
   The United States already has expressed deep regret and said it
was willing to pay compensation to victims' families, but not to
the Tehran government. It said Iran must share responsibility
because it let a civilian airliner fly in a war zone.
   Velayati told reporters outside U.N. headquarters Wednesday that
he requested that a U.N. expert team investigate the alleged
chemical attack by Iraq in which 1,000 people were hurt with the
outlawed weapons in northern Ajerbaijan.
   On Monday a report by a U.N. expert team concluded that Iraq has
made repeated and extensive use of chemical warfare in violation of
international law.
   It also found that nine Iraqi soldiers were poisoned recently by
chemical weapons, but left open the question of whether Iran was to
blame.
</TEXT>
