<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 2157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Campaigner'sDiscovery     08-03 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaigner's Discovery,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Representative, Going Door to Door, Uncovers Dead Body</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEICESTER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state representative who stopped by a
supporter's house while campaigning door to door made a grisly
discovery: The elderly man had been dead for weeks.
   State Rep. John J. Binienda said he saw swarms of black flies
inside the windows of the closed house of Guido G. Dizacomo. ``It
scared me, and I gasped and smelled a terrible odor,'' he said. He
summoned authorities who found the badly decomposed body.
   Dizacomo, 76, apparently had died of a heart attack a couple of
weeks earlier, officials said.
   Binienda said Dizacomo, whom he described as somewhat of a
recluse, had allowed him to post signs on his lawn across the
street from a polling station in 1984 and 1986, so he stopped by
Tuesday.
   The discovery of the man's body ``put a damper on my day,''
Binienda said Wednesday. ``Everything had been going so nicely. I
had knocked on 40 doors before I got to his.''
   ``One thing you can say about door-to-door campaigning: You
never know what you'll discover,'' the politician said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
