<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 2159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congressmen'sTestimony     08-03 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congressmen's Testimony,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Solons To Talk in Koreagate Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four congressmen who collected speechmaking
fees from a rice broker linked to the Koreagate scandal are not too
busy now to testify in a civil suit against the businessman, a
judge ruled Wednesday.
   U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth rejected arguments that
Majority Whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif., Reps. Bill Alexander, D-Ark.
and Vic Fazio, Calif. and Sen. John Breaux, D-La. couldn't take
time out of their busy schedules to be questioned in pre-trial
depositions in an antitrust suit against Connell Rice and Sugar Co.
and its president, Grover Connell.
   Lamberth sided with lawyers for California rice growers suing
Connell Rice and two California rice mill cooperatives. The lawyers
cited thousands of dollars that the four Democrats made in
honoraria for giving seminars at the company's headquarters in
Westfield, N.J. in the early 1980s.
   ``They were not so busy in their legislative duties that they
were not able to take these trips,'' Lamberth said at the
conclusion of a hearing on the issue.
   Steven Ross, counsel to the House clerk, argued that lengthy
depositions would take the four lawmakers away from important
legislative business. Ross suggested that the plaintiffs could
submit questions in writing to the congressmen rather than tie the
lawmakers up in the depositions.
   ``Requiring these members to attend depositions for several
hours or a better part of a day or more is very intrusive into
their official functions,'' Ross said.
   But Lamberth ruled that an oral deposition, rather than the
submission of written interrogatories, would be a more useful way
to question the lawmakers. The plaintiffs agreed to limit the
depositions to four hours for each congressman.
   Among other things, the plaintiffs want to question Breaux about
his relationship with Tongsun Park, a South Korean rice dealer who
was the central figure of the Koreagate bribery scandal of the late
1970s.
   Howard Langer, the plaintiffs' attorney, said he wants to
question Breaux and other lawmakers about efforts they made to
persuade the South Korean government to purchase more U.S. rice and
to buy it from Connell Rice.
   The judge expressed agreement with Langer's prediction that the
congressmen would be hostile witnesses.
   Although there is no allegation the four acted improperly,
Langer said the questioning is needed to develop evidence ``these
congressmen were utilized in the overall scheme to influence the
Korean government to purchase (rice) at certain prices.''
   The lawsuit contends that Connell Rice conspired with the two
cooperatives, the Rice Growers Association of California, and the
Farmers Rice Cooperative, to drive competitors out of business by
lowering the price of rice.
   Connell was indicted _ but never convicted _ in the Koreagate
scandal on wire fraud, racketeering and conspiracy charges. He was
also charged with concealing from the government that Park was a
Korean government agent and not a legitimate rice dealer. All the
charges against Connell were subsequently dismissed.
   The civil suit contends bribes that Connell Rice paid to Park
were part of the antitrust scheme.
   Langer presented evidence in court papers that the congressmen
received honoraria and campaign contributions from Connell Rice.
   Alexander received $7,000 for attending four company seminars
between 1981 and 1985. Breaux, then a House member, was also paid
$7,000 plus expenses for making four trips to the seminars during
the same period. Coelho was paid $3,000 for two trips and Fazio
received $5,000 for three trips, according to court papers.
   Park, who said he distributed $850,000 worth of bribes, was
given immunity from prosecution for his cooperation in the
investigation, which resulted in the conviction of one congressman.
</TEXT>
