<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0815 08-03 0907</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0815,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Pledges Support for RNC Chairman</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: CORRECTS spelling of Fahrenkopf throughout, subject-verb
agreement in 12th graf, Bush toured...defense-authorization bill.
^With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush said Wednesday that he will
keep Republican National Committee Chairman Frank Fahrenkopf on as
party chairman, even though his campaign is moving toward greater
control of the party structure for the general election.
   The vice president, however, said his convention manager, Fred
V. Malek, would have an expanded role in the committee and would be
designated deputy RNC chairman.
   ``I think they'll function as a very good team,'' Bush said
after touring a Westinghouse plant that manufactures and tests
underwater electronic systems for the Defense Department.
   Bush indicated that he had spurned Fahrenkopf's offer to resign
because of the change at the top. At the same time, he said, ``I
think Malek going up there will maximize coordination between the
campaign and the important functions of the RNC.''
   Meanwhile, Lee Atwater, Bush's campaign manager, denied that a
``palace revolt'' was under way in the party. ``There's total
confidence in Frank Fahrenkopf. He offered to resign. The vice
president didn't want him to,'' Atwater told a news conference in
Washington.
   Malek, a top executive of the Marriott Corp., has been serving
as Bush's convention manager since last March. He was a former
White House aide in the Nixon administration and developed a
controversial plan known as the ``responsiveness program'' to
marshal federal resources and personnel to help re-elect Nixon.
   Malek, who appeared with Atwater at the news conference,
described his role at the RNC as being one of a partnership with
Fahrenkopf _ who has been the party chairman since 1983 _ rather
than an adversarial one.
   ``I think you have a situation where one plus one can equal
three. That's the point of this whole thing,'' Malek said.
   Atwater, meanwhile, said that Bush planned to arrive in New
Orleans for the Republican National Convention on Aug. 16 _ the
second day of the event _ and after President Reagan, who speaks on
the first night, leaves.
   He said he saw nothing unusual in the fact that Reagan and Bush
would not be together during the convention that will formally
install Reagan's 1980 and 1984 running mate as the GOP nominee.
   ``I've been to the last two conventions with Ronald Reagan, and
he never stays at conventions long,'' Atwater said.
   Bush toured an assembly room at the Westinghouse Oceanics
Division plant where sonar equipment for mine-detectors is
developed. He also ate lunch with workers in the plant cafeteria
where he used the occasion to praise President Reagan's veto
earlier in the day of a defense-authorization bill.
   ``That is good national security policy,'' Bush said. ``If we
start cutting our advanced technological edge, as that bill did, it
would not be good for our national security and not good for the
strength of the (NATO) alliance.''
   Bush sidestepped questions on the health of Democratic
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis as well as Reagan's reference
to Dukakis as ``an invalid.'' The president later said, ``I was
trying to be funny and it didn't work.''
   Bush said he was ``not going to be drawn into this
mini-controversy,'' a remark that drew applause from Westinghouse
employees in the cafeteria.
   ``If somebody has a question, I will try to answer it frankly. I
do find some of the inquiries intrusive. But I will be glad to
respond to questions as it relates to my health ...,'' he said.
   Later, at a White House meeting with a women's group, Bush said
he would release his medical records. ``I believe I responded in
1980 about my medical background and I'm prepared to do it again,''
he said.
   On another subject, Bush put some distance between himself and
Reagan on recommendations from a presidential commission on AIDS,
indicating support for the centerpiece of the commission's report _
legislation banning discrimination against victims of the disease.
   ``Basically, I support the objectives of the commission,'' Bush
said. ``We have a national health problem. People are scared. We
need education, we need testing, we need research, we need all of
these things. And I don't want to see some child, who is an
innocent victim of this outrageous horrible disease, be
discriminated against. I just don't want to see that.''
   Reagan on Wednesday told federal agencies to adopt guidelines
preventing such discrimination, but stopped short of advocating
stronger measures.
   Later, in a statement issued by the White House, Bush said he
endorses proposals to speed the availability of new drugs for AIDS
and other life-threatening diseases.
   Bush said the Food and Drug Administration, when considering
whether to license new drugs for serious diseases, should give
greater weight to the risks the illnesses pose to life.
   Bush, who heads a presidential task force on regulatory relief,
also announced that the FDA is relaxing control over an
experimental drug _ pentostatin _ used to treat leukemia that does
not respond to other drugs or surgery.
   FDA spokeswoman Faye Petersen said pentostatin is the sixth drug
to qualify for what is known as ``treatment IND'' status since the
new category _ just short of full-market approval _ was established
about a year ago.
   She said pentostatin distribution will be handled through the
National Cancer Institute and that officials estimate 60 to 100
people nationwide might benefit from the new treatment.
</TEXT>
