<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 4thLd-Writethru a0882 08-03 0947</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0882,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Calls Dukakis ``An Invalid;'' Dukakis Says He's ``Healthy
Guy''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To give comment from Mrs. Dukakis, INSERT two grafs after 6th
graf, Democratic vice...same time.; picks up 7th graf pvs, Bush,
campaigning...the alliance; edits to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan called Michael Dukakis ``an invalid''
Wednesday, then said he'd just been trying to be funny but failed.
The Democratic presidential nominee later released a summary of his
medical history and said, ``I'm a very healthy guy.''
   As the delicate subject of candidate health _ and in particular
mental health _ arose in Washington, George Bush, on a short
campaign trip, stressed his support for ``Star Wars,'' the proposed
space-based missile defense system. Dukakis termed the program a
``fantasy'' and repeated his longstanding opposition.
   Bush said he wanted no part of ``this mini-controversy''
surrounding the health of his opponent for the White House. The
vice president, who will formally win the Republican presidential
nomination at this month's party convention, said he released
``relevant records'' of his own medical past in 1980 and would do
so this year.
   Dukakis, a devotee of power-walking _ fast-paced walking while
holding weights in each hand _ said ``no apology was needed'' for
Reagan's comment, and the president didn't offer one.
   ``I was just trying to be funny and it didn't work,'' he told
reporters.
   Democratic vice presidential candidate Lloyd Bentsen said the
president's remark was ``outrageous and laughable'' at the same
time.
   
   
   
   
   
   Kitty Dukakis, the candidate's wife, said during a visit to New
Jersey that such remarks come when ``people are desperate and
afraid of dealing with the real issues.''
   ``There is no truth to any of those rumors,'' Mrs. Dukakis told
reporters. ``My husband has never seen a psychiatrist.''
   
   
   Bush, campaigning in Annapolis, Md., said Reagan's veto of the
$299.5 billion defense bill was ``good national security policy.
We've got to keep this country strong. And if we start cutting our
advanced technological edge, as that bill did, it would not be good
for our national security and not good for the strength of the
alliance.''
   Dukakis, working in Boston, urged Congress to override the veto.
``This is a bipartisan defense authorization bill ... a bill which
will strengthen our national security,'' he said.
   Bush toured a defense installation in Annapolis and paused long
enough to field questions on a variety of subjects. He said he
would dispatch Fred Malek to the Republican National Committee as
deputy chairman. The vice president said that despite the move, ``I
have a lot of confidence'' in the current Republican chairman,
Frank Fahrenkopf.
   Bush shed little light on his search for a vice presidential
running mate, telling reporters he hoped to make his decision
before going to New Orleans on Aug. 16. His aides have said they
expect no public announcement until Thursday, Aug. 18, the final
day of the convention.
   In a related political matter, Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas said he
would make the nominating speech for Bush in New Orleans.
   Publicly, Dukakis and his aides responded mildly to the
emergence of the questions about his health, and particularly his
mental health.
   ``We all occasionally misspeak and I don't think the president
needed to apologize,'' said Dukakis. He responded ``no'' when asked
whether he had ever suffered from depression or consulted a
psychiatrist.
   Rumors concerning Dukakis' mental health have swirled just below
the surface of the campaign in recent days, and they cropped up at
the White House when Reagan was asked a question by a reporter
representing a publication backed by political extremist Lyndon
LaRouche.
   Reagan was asked whether he thought Dukakis should make his
records public and he replied, ``Look, I'm not going to pick on an
invalid.''
   ``An invalid in what sense,'' he was asked.
   ``I can't take any further questions,'' the president said.
   But a short time later, he returned to the subject in another
brief encounter with reporters.
   ``I attempted a joke in response to a question and _ I think I
was kidding, but I don't think I should have said what I did,''
Reagan said. Still he said the public does have a right to know the
medical history of a president.
   Late Wednesday, Dukakis' physician, Dr. Gerald R. Plotkin,
released a statement saying the candidate is in good health and
``has had no psychological symptoms, complaints or treatment.''
   Plotkin said at a news conference that Dukakis, after his
brother's death and after his political defeat in 1978, showed a
``normal grief reaction.'' But he added, ``He generally is very
strong in these situations.''
   He said the only surgery Dukakis has undergone was in 1936, when
he had his tonsils out as a child. Since 1971, the doctor reported,
Dukakis has suffered a variety of aches and pains _ including a
pulled achilles tendon and other ailments often experienced by
runners, hoarseness while he was a lecturer at Harvard and a cyst
on his back, successfully drained.
   The only prescription medicines he has taken during that period
have been antihistamines for hay fever and naproxin, a pain killer,
for muscular sprains and aches.
   Bush spokesman Stephen Hart said the vice president replied to a
medical questionnaire by the Detroit News on July 22 by saying that
his physician describes his health as ``excellent and vigorous.''
   As for health difficulties, Bush told the paper, ``I have mild
arthritis in the hips, which is non-limiting. I have cut back my
running to two miles at a time. Mild symptons are readily
controlled. I am also allergic to bee stings, for which I have
received shots that are highly effective.''
</TEXT>
