<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Medical     08-03 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Medical,1st Ld-Writethru,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Says Dukakis In Excellent Health, Aches And Pains Top
Complaints</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 5, Plotkin released...family doctor, to add details
on Plotkin affiliation; INSERTS new grafs 6-9 with background on
Mrs. Dukakis saying husband was depressed after death of his
brother, election loss; pickup graf 6 pvs, bgng, ``Plotkin said....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis is
in excellent health, has only received treatment for routine
ailments and ``has had no psychological symptoms, complaints or
treatment,'' his longtime doctor said Wednesday.
   Dr. Gerald R. Plotkin, at a news conference called by the
Dukakis campaign to dispel rumors the Massachusetts governor has
received psychiatric treatment, said Dukakis has never had such
treatment and has been prescribed drugs only for hay fever and
muscle sprains and aches.
   ``He has had no significant illnesses during his lifetime and
has been in excellent health,'' Plotkin said. ``He has never
appeared depressed to me.''
   Supporters of political extremist Lyndon LaRouche were
distributing fliers questioning Dukakis' mental capacity during the
Democratic National Convention in Atlanta.
   Plotkin released a three-page statement summarizing any
treatment he has given Dukakis over the past 17 years at the
Harvard Community Health Plan, a health maintenance organization
whose services are available through the state employees benefits
program. Prior to that, Dukakis was treated by his father, a family
doctor.
   Dukakis' wife Kitty, has decribed her husband as being depressed
following the 1973 death of his brother, Stelian, who was killed by
a hit-and-run driver, and after he lost the 1978 gubernatorial
primary after serving four years in the office.
   But Mrs. Dukakis said Wednesday during an appearance in New
Jersey that her husband has never seen a psychiatrist, and Plotkin
said Dukakis showed no signs of clinical depression.
   ``There is a normal grieving after any loss, from minor to
major, and the response usually is in relation to the gravity of
the loss,'' Plotkin said. ``I was struck at the time of both losses
at his strength rather then his depression. ... I saw him on a
number of occasions and he never demonstrated any symptoms or signs
that he would require counseling.''
   Stelian Dukakis suffered from clinical depression and once tried
to commit suicide. But Plotkin said the condition was not
hereditary.
   Plotkin said Dukakis has been treated for:
   _ Plantar fascitis, a form of minor foot discomfort associated
with jogging. Dukakis was treated in 1983. He since has given up
jogging but keeps an almost daily regimen of speed walking.
   _ A pinched nerve in his neck, in 1979.
   _ A pulled achilles tendon, in 1976.
   The prescribed treatment for those conditions was rest, heat and
naproxen, an anti-inflammatory medicine slightly more powerful than
aspirin, Plotkin said.
   The doctor said Dukakis also has received treatment for:
   _ A minor fracture of his collarbone, sufferred in a foot race
in Ireland in 1976.
   _ A splinter under the nail of his left index finger, in 1979.
   _ Hoarseness, in 1981, which was attributed to his lecturing at
the John F. Kennedy School of Government.
   _ A cyst on his back, in 1986, which was drained.
   Plotkin said the material he had released was essentially that
contained in his file on Dukakis with the exception of personal
notes.
   He said it was possible Dukakis could have seen another
physician or a psychiatrist but he did not believe he had.
   All of his tests were within normal limits, Plotkin said.
</TEXT>
