<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-KittyDukakis     08-03 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Kitty Dukakis,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis' Wife Calls for U.S. Embassy Move to Jerusalem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kitty Dukakis, wife of Democratic presidential
nominee Michael Dukakis, was quoted as saying in an interview
published Wednesday that she favors moving the U.S. Embassy to the
disputed city of Jerusalem.
   Her husband stirred controversy last May when he said he
supported Israel's decision to move its capital from Tel Aviv to
Jerusalem. ``If Israel wants its capital in Jerusalem, then as far
as I'm concerned, its capital is in Jerusalem,'' Dukakis told The
Los Angeles Times.
   Despite Mrs. Dukakis' remark, she was quoted by the Israeli
weekly Haolam Hazeh as saying that ``the subject (of the capital's
location) should not be in the headlines now.''
   ``First, we must take care of more burning issues.''
   Mrs. Dukakis, who is Jewish, was interviewed in the United
States by a Haolam Hazeh reporter.
   Israel has declared Jerusalem its capital, but many countries do
not recognize it as such. U.S. officials say the U.S. embassy must
remain in Tel Aviv until the dispute over Jerusalem has been
resolved in peace negotiations.
   Israel annexed Arab east Jerusalem after capturing it from
Jordan in the 1967 Middle East war. The city is considered holy by
Jews, Moslems and Christians.
   Mrs. Dukakis also was quoted as saying that as first lady, she
would ``continue being a proud Jew,'' but as stressing that
religion and politics must remain separate.
   Mrs. Dukakis, who would be the first Jewish first lady if her
husband is elected next November, also said her first visit to
Israel in 1976 renewed her interest in Judaism, according to the
weekly.
   ``That visit changed everything for me,'' it quoted the
51-year-old Mrs. Dukakis as saying.
   Haolam Hazeh quoted her as saying the most important experience
of that trip was a visit to the Holocaust Memorial Yad Vashem in
Jerusalem. Six million Jews were killed by Nazi Germany in the
Holocaust.
   ``My parents left Germany before the Holocaust. They sensed what
was going to happen,'' she was quoted as saying. ``I was brought up
on this memory, but I don't think I understood the full
significance until I visited Yad Vashem.''
   Her parents, both Jewish, studied in Berlin but left before
World War II.
   Mrs. Dukakis said that if her husband is elected, she would like
him to appoint her to the President's Commission on the Holocaust,
according to the publication.
   Mrs. Dukakis was appointed to the panel by former President
Jimmy Carter, but his successor, Ronald Reagan, did not extend her
term when it expired in 1986.
   She also was quoted as saying her five visits to Israel have
strengthened her commitment to her religion.
   ``I grew up in a Jewish neighborhood (in Brookline, Mass.). I
used to go to synagogue with my grandmother, but I never studied in
a Jewish or religious school,'' Mrs. Dukakis said, according to
Haolam Hazeh.
   She was quoted as saying that after returning to the United
States from her first visit to Israel in 1976, she joined a
synagogue and began raising funds for the Jewish state.
   Asked whether her religion would affect how she would fill her
role as first lady, she said, according to the weekly: ``There is a
separation between church and state. This is very important and
must be protected.''
   It said that she added, however: ``I will continue being a proud
Jew in the White House, too.''
  
</TEXT>
