<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-PrivateEye Adv04   08-03 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Private Eye, Adv 04,0737</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday PMs, Aug. 4</NOTE>
<HEAD>Jim Rockford, Yes; Richie Brockelman, No</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At a recent news conference, NBC's Brandon
Tartikoff facetiously suggested ``Jerry Buck, Private Eye'' as a
replacement show on the network's fall schedule.
   Having a somewhat proprietary view of this new show, I have a
few suggestions to make.
   Tartikoff, who is president of NBC Entertainment, spoke of the
show during a news conference outlining how the network would cope
in the fall because of the writers strike.
   Explaining his idea for bringing back old shows as ``American
Revivals,'' Tartikoff said:
   ``You go and get eight or 10 `Richie Brockelman' scripts and
redo it (the decade-old series) with Bruce Willis and call it
`Jerry Buck, Private Eye' and I don't think viewer one would say,
`Wait a second, didn't I see that plot back in 1979?'''
   Now, I have no objection to Bruce Willis. We do sort of look
alike, except I'm taller. But ``Richie Brockelman, Private Eye''
has to go. That's as bad as ``The Hardy Boys,'' which Tartikoff
actually is reviving.
   Richie Brockelman was a wet-behind-the-ears kid. Wimp is an
expression that comes to mind. His mother and father even hung
around and worried about him and gave him advice. The show, which
ran briefly on NBC, was not something you'd want to see again. Even
with Bruce Willis and even retitled ``Jerry Buck, Private Eye.''
   The show was a spinoff of ``The Rockford Files.'' Now, there was
a detective series!
   If Tartikoff is going to bring back an old detective show and
name it after me, this is the one he should think about. James
Garner was Jim Rockford.
   Rockford's father also hung around, but it was different. His
pop, Rocky, didn't stand around and wring his hands. You could tell
he was a man's man because he drove a pickup truck.
   Rockford was down at the heels, the way a private eye's supposed
to be. Instead of a walk-up office in some seedy Hollywood building
and a wisecracking secretary, he lived on a trailer at the beach
and had an answering machine.
   It was a great show, quite possibly the best detective show ever
on television. Rockford frequently used questionable methods to
solve his cases. His disguises were always so transparent, his
bribes were too cheap to ever win over anybody, and he usually got
stiffed for his fee at the end of each episode.
   Rockford was sometimes outsmarted by other private detectives,
most notably Lance White. Lance White, who was sort of Mr. Perfect,
was played by Tom Selleck. Selleck, of course, went on to become
Thomas Magnum.
   Perhaps Tartikoff might consider the old scripts of ``Magnum,
P.I.'' for my show. I can see myself tooling around Oahu in Robin
Masters' red Ferrari. I could irritate Higgins as much as Magnum.
I'd also steer clear of Zeus and Apollo.
   ``Peter Gunn'' is another detective show Tartikoff should think
about reviving. It's not every private eye whose hangout was called
``Mother's.'' Or had a girlfriend like Edie. Besides, Henry
Mancini's jazzy theme was the first of the memorable television
themes.
   Other possible revivals: ``Mannix,'' ``McCloud,'' ``Barney
Miller,'' or even ``The Lone Ranger.'' I'd look good in a black
mask.
   ``Columbo'' was a possibility, but ABC beat NBC to the punch.
They've got Peter Falk back in the old raincoat. They're even
getting back that tiny Peugeot Cabriolet he got around in.
   So, Brandon, thanks for the offer, but I'll pass on ``Richie
Brockelman.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   CUTTING EDGE _ Peter Ustinov will be the host of Harmony Gold's
live presentation of ``The Secret Identity of Jack the Ripper'' on
Oct. 26. Ustinov, the winner of two Academy Awards and three Emmys,
also portrayed Inspector Hercule Poirot in movies based on the
Agatha Christie detective. The two-hour special, featuring
world-renowned forensic scientists and criminologists, will attempt
to uncover the identity of Jack the Ripper.
   DEBUT _ Playwright David Mamet will make his debut as a
television executive producer with ``Lip Service'' for Home Box
Office. Griffin Dunne stars in the HBO Showcase presentation in
October. Mamet won the Pulitzer Prize for drama for ``Glengary Glen
Ross.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thursday PMs, Aug. 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
