<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 1348EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Netherlands-SocialLaboratory adv07   08-03 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Netherlands-Social Laboratory, adv 07,0476</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AP SPOTLIGHT: The Netherlands _ Tolerance Makes It A Social</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Laboratory
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: One of a three-story package</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Dutch confront
controversial issues like euthanasia, drug abuse, and AIDS, their
reaction is firmly rooted in a tradition of tolerance and consensus.
   ``Dutch politics since the 17th century have been marked by
attempts to forge compromise and harmony between competing
interests and ideologies,'' said Leen Vroegindewey, a political
scientist at Leiden University, the nation's oldest.
   ``More often than not, those compromises are far more pragmatic
than partisan solutions would be in the sense that the sharp
ideological edges have eroded from the issue in the course of the
public debate,'' Vroegindewey told The Associated Press in a recent
interview.
   The euthanasia debate raged for years in Parliament, newspapers,
hospitals, and from the pulpit. The practice is widespread here,
with an estimated 5,000 cases annually, according to recent
government figures.
   The center-right coalition government of Prime Minister Ruud
Lubbers, in which the anti-euthanasia Christian Democrats dominate,
vetoed a proposal to permit euthanasia. It then introduced
legislation that does not decriminalize euthanasia, but sets
guidelines that physicians can use as a defense in courts.
   In the few euthanasia cases that have gone to court, only
suspended sentences have been routinely imposed. Vroegindewey
referred to the legislation, which has not yet come to a vote, as
``an archetypical Dutch compromise.''
   In another example, police tolerate the small-scale possession
and use of hashish and marijuana, which is readily available in
Dutch coffee shops. The city has methadone clinics for its
estimated 7,000 drug addicts.
   ``There has been a lot of clamor in the surrounding countries on
how we do it here,'' said Amsterdam police spokesman Klaas Wilting.
``But I'd like to claim that although we haven't solved the drug
problem, it's at least contained.''
   After a spectacular rise in the 1970s and early 1980s, the
number of drug-related crimes stabilized. And while cocaine
consumption in the United States skyrocketed, here it declined,
according to the Dutch Justice Ministry.
   Despite the opposition of the religious right, the Dutch
government reacted to acquired immune deficiency syndrome with a
``safe sex'' information campaign, and local authorities provided
free hypodermic needles to intravenous drug abusers, one of the
worst risk groups.
   ``Whatever the government might think of it, they know that
proselytizing against adultery, promiscuity and premarital sex will
have very little impact here,'' said Amsterdam sociologist Enna van
Lingen.
   Amsterdam health authorities claim the free needle program has
been a major factor in fighting AIDS. Only 539 cases have been
reported in the Netherlands, one of the lowest incidence rates in
the Western world.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
