<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 1328EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s p BC-BakerProfile Adv07   08-03 1297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Baker Profile, Adv 07,1336</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>James Baker Set to Chair Campaign of `Real Friend' _ George Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Among the mementos Treasury Secretary James A.
Baker III keeps on the wall in his office are a photograph of a
smiling George Bush and a framed copy of a Texas newspaper article
from the 1930s.
   The Bush picture is autographed: ``What would we do without real
friends?'' And the newspaper article quotes millionaire grandfather
``Captain'' James A. Baker's formula for success: ``Work hard,
study and keep out of politics.''
   When it came to that last piece of advice, Baker went his own
way. that ``real friend'' is part of the reason why.
   Baker is poised to become Bush's presidential campaign chairman
after resigning his Treasury job. It's a scene similar to the one
18 years ago when Baker took time out from his Houston corporate
law practice to dabble in politics for the first time.
   At the time, Baker heeded a request for campaign help from a
tennis partner at the Houston Country Club, then-congressman George
Bush, who was running for the Senate _ against a Democrat named
Lloyd Bentsen.
   Bitten by the political bug, Baker _ then a Democrat _ became a
Republican at Bush's urging, and a fast friendship and political
alliance blossomed between the two Texans. Their careers have been
intertwined ever since.
   Clearly, Baker is leaving the Treasury post with some reluctance.
   Baker has amassed more influence than any other recent secretary
of the Treasury _ a job he assumed in 1985 when, as President
Reagan's first-term chief-of-staff, he engaged in a celebrated
``job switch'' with Donald T. Regan.
   The nation is in its 69th month of a record peacetime expansion,
unemployment is it at lowest level in 14 years, and the nation's
massive trade deficit finally is beginning to shrink _ due in part
to Baker's intricate management of the dollar.
   He is credited with steering the 1986 tax-overhaul bill through
Congress, just as he had manuevered the Reagan tax cut through a
Democratic Congress in 1981 as chief of staff.
   Baker has won plaudits internationally for persuading U.S.
allies to coordinate their economic polices and for negotiating a
U.S.-Canadian free trade pact.
   ``These are some of the things I think will survive this
administration. And I think they are, hopefully, some important
achievements,'' Baker said in an interview.
   While it is believed that Baker could have any post in a Bush
administration he wanted _ his associates say he would like to be
secretary of state _ the 58-year-old Baker shrugs off such
speculation.
   ``I would like to make sure I finish my job here and do it
right.''
   Baker and Bush _ six years his senior _ seem to be cut out of
the same patrician cloth.
   Both come from wealthy families, both went to prep schools in
the East _ Bush to Phillips Academy in Andover, Mass., and Baker to
the Hill School in Pottstown, Pa. And both graduated from Ivy
League colleges: Baker, Princeton; Bush, Yale.
   Baker, who was born in Houston, and Bush, who grew up in
Connecticut but considers Texas his adopted state, both are viewed
as political moderates and pragmatists.
   Both share a love of Mexican food and sports.
   Bush boats and fishes; Baker fishes and hunts.
   And while both Baker and Bush have proven adept at winning
appointive office _ Baker also served as an undersecretary of
Commerce in the Ford administration _ the two have been less
successful in getting each other elected.
   Despite Baker's help, Bush lost that 1970 Senate race to Bentsen
as well as his 1980 race against Reagan for the Republican
presidential nominaiton. And, despite Bush's help, Baker lost his
only try at elective office _ a 1978 race for Texas attorney
general.
   Still, Baker today has a reputation as one of the Republican
Party's craftiest political strategists _ a reputation honed when
he signed on in 1976 as President Gerald Ford's chief delegate
hunter after Ford lost five straight primaries to Ronald Reagan.
   Baker came up with the delegates that helped Ford narrowly
defeat Reagan for the GOP nomination; and as general-election
campaign manager for Ford saw the former president's 30-plus lag in
the polls to Democrat Jimmy Carter close to within one percentage
point of the total vote.
   Baker is also credited with masterminding Bush's dramatic
victory in the Iowa caucuses in 1980.
   ``He's very good. He was very good for Ford, when he really did
make a big difference when he got deeply involved; and he's been a
good help to Bush,'' said John Sears, a political consultant who
represented Reagan in that 1976 head-to-head scramble with Baker
for delegates.
   ``For one thing, he brings to (the 1988 Bush campaign) one very
important ingredient: he can handle the candidate. No one else is
around who has that kind of level relationship with George,'' said
Sears.
   A good campaign manager has to have a multitude of virtues, Bush
wrote in his autobiography, ``Looking Forward.'' The most
important, he said, is being ``able to tell his candidate what the
candidate doesn't want to hear.''
   That moment of truth came in June 1980, right before the
California primary when Bush was seriously trailing Reagan and out
of money, but wanted to press on anyway.
   Bush quotes Baker as telling him: ``The campaign is finished,
George. You're the only one who doesn't seem to know it.''
   Reagan made Baker a special campaign assistant after the 1980
convention. Baker took on the role of helping Reagan prepare for
his debates against then-President Carter.
   When Reagan was elected, he quickly announced that Baker would
be his chief-of-staff.
   Baker quickly went to work in quietly guiding Reagan's
supply-side tax cut and other first-term initiatives through
Congress. His ability to get along with congressional Democrats
continued after he switched jobs.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee, calls Baker ``an honest adversary'' with ``a first
class political gut.''
   Many Baker admirers claim that some of the problems afflicting
the Reagan administration over the past few years _ including the
Iran-contra arms sales _ might not have happened had Baker remained
on as chief of staff, with his immense attention for detail.
   Still, despite Baker's celebrated penchant for caution and
keeping out of the public spotlight, he hasn't always been
successful.
   In 1985, aboard Air Force One en route to China with Reagan,
Baker was asked if he'd ever been to a communist country. ``Well,
I've been to Massachsetts,'' he said.
   That comment _ for which Baker later apologized _ brought a
testy letter from the state's governor, Michael Dukakis. Dukakis
invited Baker to ride on the Boston subway route known as ``The Red
Line.''
   And some economists claim that Baker's remarks in criticizing
West German interest rates last October helped trigger the record
508-point stock market crash.
   ``His comments clearly disturbed the markets,'' said David Wyss,
chief financial economist for Data Resources Inc. ``He was pushing
a little to hard.''
   However, Wyss overall said Baker ``has been a very good treasury
secretary. He made some mistakes but he grew into the job.''
   One of Baker's chief initiatives as treasury secretary _ a plan
to help ease the Third World debt crisis with a $29 million package
of new loans, mostly from commercial banks _ never bore fruit.
   However, Baker still lists that debt-relief plan as one of his
major initiatives _ and one that may still come to pass. ``Our
approach is the only viable approach if you're not going to try to
solve (the debt problem) on the backs of taxpayers in creditor
countries,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
