<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation is beginning to see more
inflationary pressures, with prices rising for a range of products
from metals and paper to food, the Federal Reserve Board has said
in a review of the economy.
   The outlook, released Tuesday, was based on reports from all 12
regional Federal Reserve banks. It found bottlenecks developing in
some sectors of the economy, caused partly by the highest industry
operating rates this decade.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has urged Congress
to reject calls by savings and loan executives for a taxpayer
bailout of their industry.
   George D. Gould, undersecretary of the treasury for finance,
told the Senate Banking Committee on Tuesday that such relief is
unnecessary and would hurt taxpayers. But others, including
committee chairman William Proxmire, D-Wis., said the problem has
grown so large it could threaten healthy S&Ls.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel company executives say they are
optimistic the next administration will extend steel trade
agreements covering 30 nations.
   The executives, representing the nation's top three steelmakers,
told a Congressional Steel Caucus briefing Tuesday that their
optimism was based on statements from both presidential candidates
supporting domestic steelmakers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Worldwide trade in goods grew in volume by 5
percent last year and is expected to rise by the same percentage in
1988, the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade says.
   A study released today by the international trading body paints
a more upbeat picture of the world economy than one issued in
February that estimated 4 percent growth in 1987 and 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's securities industry fired a net
15,900 employees between last October's stock market crash and the
end of the first quarter, according to a new study.
   The joint study released Tuesday was made by the Securities
Industry Association and the accounting firm Arthur Andersen & Co.
   It said about 262,200 employees were employed in the securities
industry as of Sept. 30, 1987, the last benchmark before the Oct.
19 crash. That number dropped to 260,500 employees as of Dec. 31,
1987 and to 246,300 by March 31 of this year.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks finished fractionally higher Tuesday in a volatile
session. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials edged up 0.71
point to close at 2,131.22.
   Bonds rose strongly despite government reports detailing
economic strength. The Treasury's key 30-year issue rose nearly $10
per $1,000 in face amount and its yield fell to 9.06 percent from
9.15 percent.
   The dollar rose, gold and oil prices fell, and crop futures
closed mixed despite a third day of scorching heat in the farm belt.
</TEXT>
