<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0136EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     08-03 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economic Barometer Leaps 1.4 Percent, But Inflation Fears Are Mild</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Fears of surging inflation have remained modest among many
observers despite three government reports indicating surprisingly
robust economic growth in the month of June.
   The government's main forecasting gauge rose 1.4 percent, its
biggest gain in 18 months; sales of new homes shot up 8.4 percent;
and orders to U.S. factories for manufactured goods soared 5.5
percent, the government said Tuesday in a series of reports.
   Prices rose Tuesday in the bond market, which often is hurt by
news of strong growth because of the fear that a boom in the
economy will contribute to higher inflation and erode the value of
fixed-income securities.
   Meanwhile, the stock market struggled through an uneven session
as the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 0.71 point to
2,131.22. Stocks normally react better than bonds to strong
economic growth because of the prospect for rising corporate
profits.
   The Commerce Department said the increase in its Index of
Leading Indicators was the sharpest rise in 18 months.
   Analysts credited renewed consumer confidence for the rebound in
sales of new homes after a sluggish period earlier this spring.
   The 5.5 percent rise in factory orders was the largest one-month
advance in more than 17 years and was propelled by the biggest
increase in military orders in more than five years.
   ``The leading index has been up in four of the last five months.
You have to consider that very good news for the economy,'' said
David Wyss, chief financial economist for Data Resources Inc.
``There is certainly no sign of a recession coming at least for the
rest of this year.''
   The economy, as measured by the gross national product, expanded
at a healthy 3.3 percent annual rate in the first six months of
1988, far better than many economists had expected following last
October's stock market crash.
   Given the momentum provided by exceptionally strong activity in
June, many analysts said they expected growth in the current
July-September quarter to remain strong.
   Many analysts worry that strong growth eventually will prompt
the Federal Reserve Board to boost interest rates to restrain
inflation.
   The Fed, in a review of the economy released Tuesday, noted
rising prices for a wide variety of materials from metals and paper
to food. The report, prepared for Fed policymakers, said high
factory operating rates in many industries were beginning to reach
capacity restraints.
   Many analysts say that while the economy will continue growing
at a good clip this year, the Fed's efforts to fight inflationary
pressures could result in a recession sometime in 1989.
   Analysts said the increase in the leading index partly was a
rebound from May, when the index dropped 0.8 percent after three
months of solid gains. The June advance was the biggest one-month
rise since the index climbed 2.2 percent in December 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880803-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0136EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     08-03 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Decline Ahead of OPEC Committee Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Traders' skepticism about today's OPEC pricing
committee meeting has weakened oil futures prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for September
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, fell 47 cents a barrel Tuesday to close at $15.61. The
September contract had lost 23 cents on Monday.
   Futures prices for refined oil products also retreated. The
September contract for wholesale heating oil dropped 0.83 cent a
gallon to finish at 44.29 cents, while wholesale unleaded gasoline
for September fell 0.73 cent a gallon to 47.86 cents.
   Analysts said traders were doubtful the 13-nation Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries, which was to hold a meeting of
its price-monitoring committee today in Lausanne, Switzerland, will
take effective action to bolster oil prices.
   ``I think there's a lot of doubt,'' said Peter Beutel, assistant
director of the energy group at Elders Futures Inc.
   Even if the meeting of the five-member price-monitoring
committee turns into a full-scale OPEC ministerial conference, the
market could remain skeptical, Beutel said. ``Then the question
becomes, `What are they (OPEC) going to do from there?''' he said.
   Indonesian Oil Minister Ginandjar Kartasasmita, arriving for the
meeting in Lausanne, said Tuesday he would not exclude the
possibility of an emergency OPEC conference following the
price-monitoring panel's meeting.
   In addition to Kartasasmita, the price-monitoring committee
includes the oil ministers of Saudi Arabia, Venezuela, Algeria and
Nigeria.
</TEXT>
