<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-03 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against all major currencies in
moderate late-morning trading in Europe today.
   Gold prices fell.
   In the absence of any market-moving news, foreign exchange
trading was dominated by technical factors, traders said.
   ``The dollar just broke one technical resistance level after
another,'' one trader said.
   Traders predicted that the dollar soon would soon run into
strong resistance and that the currency would remain locked in a
narrow trading range.
   Fear of possible central bank intervention was keeping a lid on
the currency, dealers said.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.7017, weaker than
$1.7093.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.8793 West German marks, up from 1.8760; 1.5655
Swiss francs, up from 1.5635; 6.3370 French francs, up from 6.3265;
2.1181 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1140; 1,385.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,380.75; 1.2069 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2068.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 0.45 yen to a closing 132.85 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 133.15 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $432.00 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $433.00. At midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $431.25.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $431.40, down from $433.00 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.70 to close at a bid $433.67.
   Silver, hit by profit-taking, was quoted in London today at a
bid price of $6.76 a troy ounce, down from Tuesday's $6.86.
</TEXT>
