<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     08-03 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up today, while share prices
traded slow and closed lower, ending seven straight daily gains.
   The dollar opened at 132.97 yen and was steady in a narrow range
of 132.83 yen and 133.00 yen before closing at 132.85 yen, up 0.45
yen from Tuesday's close.
   Spot trading totaled $2.721 billion, down from Tuesday's $4.253
billion.
   Meanwhile, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues,
which gained 40.02 points Tuesday to post a record closing high of
28,366.33, was off 17.88 points, or 0.06 percent. It closed at
28,348.45, about midway between the day's high and low.
   Volume in the first section was a thin 800 million shares,
unchanged from Tuesday's total.
   On the stock market, declining issues outnumbered advancers, 444
to 421, with 183 others unchanged.
   Traders said investors were cautious after the Nikkei index set
its record high close Tuesday and that there was little
market-affecting news to offset the general lack of buying interest.
   ``U.S. employment figures, which will be released Friday, will
be a checkpoint for the market,'' said Masahiro Umemori of Nomura
Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   The U.S. Labor Department is scheduled to announce July
unemployment figures on Friday.
</TEXT>
