<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TobaccoWarnings     08-03 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tobacco Warnings,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Environmental Groups Announce Effort To Seek Warning Signs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to CORRECT cycle designator and change style
to PMs in first two grafs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVE LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmental activists, claiming
retailers have been playing ``hide and seek with consumer health,''
said they will try to force stores to post cancer warnings for 225
tobacco products, mostly cigars and pipe tobacco.
   Three environmental groups and Tom Hayden's Campaign California
political organization announced plans Tuesday to file a $1.3
billion lawsuit against eight major retail chains and 27 tobacco
companies, claiming they have failed to adequately warn customers
about risks in the tobacco products.
   They took the action under a ``citizen's suit'' provision of
Proposition 65, a controversial 1986 ballot measure that requires
warnings for a long list of substances believed to cause cancer or
birth defects.
   Proposition 65 allows private parties to sue under its
provisions if prosecutors fail to act after receiving 60 days
notice from the potential plaintiffs.
   David Roe, an attorney for the Environmental Defense Fund, and
Carl Pope of the Sierra Club announced at a news conference that
they were giving that notice. ``If they don't act, we will,'' Roe
said.
   Proposition 65 allows fines of up to $2,500 a day for a
violation. Pope and Roe said the $1.3 billion figure used by their
groups was a ``fairly conservative estimate of the maximum
potential liability'' faced by the chains and tobacco companies.
   Pope said the groups targeted the 225 tobacco products because
they do not carry federally required package warnings like
cigarettes do and have a well-documented cancer risk.
   Leslie Howe, vice president for governmental affairs for the
California Retailers Association, declined to discuss the issue.
``This is the type of thing that attorneys talk to other attorneys
about,'' he said.
   A Tobacco Institute representative in Sacramento did not return
a reporter's phone call.
   But Norman F. Sharp, president of the Cigar Association of
America and the Pipe Tobacco Council, told The New York Times the
tobacco industry took ``great pains'' to comply with the law,
placing advertisements in 58 newspapers across the state and
sending out more than a million notices for retailers to place on
shelves.
   The eight chains targeted by the environmentalists are
Albertson's Inc., the Alpha Beta Co., Lucky Stores Inc., Raley's,
Ralphs Grocery Co., Safeway Stores Inc., Thrifty Drug and Discount
Stores and Vons Grocery Co.
   Roe said group representatives had been in some stores operated
by the chains and had not found warning signs for the tobacco
products.
   Tobacco companies cited by the groups include R.J. Reynolds,
United States Tobacco Co., Consolidated Cigar Co. and General Cigar
Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880803-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0853EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-OPEC     08-03 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-OPEC,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Price Monitoring Committee Meeting Opens</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subroto, one name, is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price monitoring committee of
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries met today to
discuss the cartel's continuing overproduction and pricing problems.
   The five-nation committee, comprising ministers from Venezuela,
Nigeria, Saudi Arabia, Indonesia and Algeria, met behind closed
doors at a luxury hotel in this lakeside city.
   Venezuelan oil minister Arturo Hernandez Grisanti said Tuesday
one item on the agenda would be a report by OPEC Secretary-General
Subroto, of Indonesia, on his visit to the United Arab Emirates in
July.
   Subroto visited the U.A.E. after it decided to abandon its OPEC
oil production quota of 948,000 barrels a day and said it would aim
for a daily output of 1.5 million barrels.
   The committee is also to discuss the OPEC auditors' report for
the cartel's production in May, as well as estimates from secondary
sources for June and July production.
   Indonesian oil minister Ginandjar Kartasasmita said Tuesday that
industry estimates for June OPEC production were between
18.54-18.56 million barrels a day, while July production estimates
were understood to be around 19 million barrels a day.
   One OPEC delegate source said ``19 million barrels a day is
definitely too much (for OPEC to be producing). We will never see
prices recover in the short-to-medium term at that level.''
   In a related development, Saudi Arabian oil minister Hisham
Nazer, responding to press reports that his country's oil output in
July was above its OPEC quota, said Wednesday, ``that is wrong.''
He said Saudi Arabia is producing within its output quota of 4.343
million barrels a day.
   The OPEC price committee is empowered to study world oil price
trends, and to call an emergency meeting of the full 13-member OPEC
ministerial conference if it finds that world oil prices have
diverged significantly from OPEC's $18-a-barrel average reference
price.
   Delegate sources said another topic of discussion by the pricing
committee would be the effect on OPEC production levels of a
possible ceasefire between Iran and Iraq.
   The sources said that two opinions have apparently arisen on the
possible effect.
   Some within OPEC believe a ceasefire could result in the two
countries' flooding world oil markets with crude as they try to
sell more oil to finance the reconstruction of their war-torn
economies.
   Others seem to think that an end to the war would mean greater
cooperation within OPEC and lead to production restraint, the
sources said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
