<DOCNO> AP880803-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 0910EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TimberStrike     08-03 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Timber Strike,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Willamette Industries Reaches Tentative Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willamette Industries Inc. has reached a
tentative settlement with two unions that have been on strike
against it and several other Northwest wood-products companies for
nearly two months.
   The settlement Tuesday was the first since the strike began June
6. It came during the second day of negotiations with a federal
mediator in Portland, said Cathy Baldwin, a company spokeswoman.
   Industry and union officials are optimistic the settlement will
lead to agreements with the other companies, said a source close to
the negotiations who asked not to be named.
   Baldwin said no details of the proposed pact would be released
until the 1,275 striking workers with the Portland-based company
vote on it Thursday.
   ``It was a fair compromise,'' she said.
   Mike Draper, executive secretary of the Western Council of
Industrial Workers, said he was pleased with the contract. ``We
didn't get everything on our wish list, but neither did Willamette
Industries,'' he said.
   The Western Council and the International Woodworkers of
America-U.S. went on strike against Willamette Industries and
several other companies after negotiations broke down. A total of
13 Willamette mills and logging operations were affected in Sweet
Home, Lebanon, Dallas and Albany.
   The strike spread to eight companies with operations in Oregon,
Washington, Idaho, Montana and Northern California, affecting an
estimated 9,000 workers, including those with Willamette Industries.
   Willamette Industries and the other companies had met just once
with the unions during the past two weeks, and each session lasted
less than two hours. The latest negotiations lasted a total of 14
hours Monday and Tuesday, federal mediator Paul Stuckenschneider
said.
   The other companies affected by the strike are Boise Cascade
Corp., Champion International Corp. Simpson Timber Co., DAW Forest
Products Inc., and WI Forest Products Inc. The Western Council also
has struck two smaller companies: Lakeview Lumber Co. and a door
plant operated by Morgan Products Ltd. in Springfield.
   The unions also have threatened to strike Weyerhaeuser Co., the
region's largest wood-products company with 6,000 union members in
Oregon and Washington. Union officials said last week, however,
that the Weyerhaeuser strike plans were on hold.
   The workers have sought restoration of wages and benefits cut in
1986, when the industry was in a recession. The unions accepted the
cuts after a series of strikes.
   Company officials have said they cannot not restore wages and
still compete with smaller, non-union mills. Some of the companies,
however, have offered bonus plans in lieu of wage hikes.
   One union official recently said the unions were willing to
consider a combination of wage increases and bonuses as long as the
wage increases comprised the bulk of the additional compensation.
   Willamette Industries, which employs 8,600 workers overall,
manufactures wood and paper products. Its paper mills have not been
affected by the strike.
   Baldwin said that in the strike's first eight weeks, $1.6
million in wages were lost just in the small town of Sweet Home,
where four mills were shut down.
   In an interview last week, Baldwin said the wood-products
industry had not rebounded as well as officials had hoped it would.
   ``There's no question that we feel our people deserve wage
increases,'' she said. ``But the question is how much?''
   ``I think everyone thought in 1986 when we had to take wage
cuts, that the economic climate would change and would be a lot
more hospitable for the forest-products industry in 1988. That
never happened, however.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
