<HEAD>London Shares Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were higher at midday Wednesday on
the London Stock Exchange, as speculative trading and positive
sentiment combined to give the market a lift.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 9.7
points, or 0.5 percent, at 1,865.2, its best level for the day, at
about 12:30 p.m. local time.
   The British pound's retreat, especially against the West German
mark, had a buoyant effect on shares of export-sensitive companies
and also helped overall market sentiment, dealers said.
   Also showing notable gains were real estate and insurance
company shares.
   The FT-SE 100-share index opened unchanged and then declined
slightly as the market fumbled for direction in early trading. Flat
performances on Wall Street Tuesday and in Tokyo earlier Wednesday
provided little lead for London stocks.
   Trading volume at around midday was 244.8 million shares, up
from 224.4 million at the same time Tuesday.
   Dealers said business was slow with many investment fund
managers away on summer vacations.
