<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BATUS-Farmers 1stLd-Writethru   08-03 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BATUS-Farmers, 1st Ld-Writethru,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Washington State's Insurance Chief Rejects Batus Bid for Farmers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: makes editing changes, CORRECTS name of B.A.T. in lead,
CORRECTS style of Batus throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID AMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington's insurance commissioner has
rejected an unfriendly takeover bid for Farmers Insurance Group by
the British conglomerate B.A.T. Industries PLC.
   ``The policyholders could quite possibly lose from the
acquisition, and they do not stand to gain anything from it,''
Commissioner Dick Marquardt said in an order turning down the bid
on Tuesday.
   Marquardt's spokesman Ed Ives said the company was expected to
appeal the decision.
   Washington joins Oregon, Idaho and California in rejecting the
$4.5 billion, or $63 per share, takeover bid. Arizona has approved
the offer, made through B.A.T.'s American subsidiary Batus Inc.
Decisions are pending in Illinois, Ohio, Kansas and Texas.
   The commissioner's ruling followed almost a week of hearings in
Seattle last month.
   Farmers Insurance Co. of Washington, based in Vancouver, and
Farmers New World Life, headquartered on Mercer Island, are
affiliates of Farmers Insurance Group of Los Angeles, which has
rejected the Batus offer.
   The interests of Farmers' policyholders, shareholders and the
general public are best served by Farmers remaining independent,
said Leo E. Denlea Jr., chairman and chief executive officer of
Farmers.
   Farmers is the No. 1 auto insurance company in the state,
writing 17.4 percent of the policies in the market, Marquardt said.
   Marquardt said he did not believe Batus claims that it would not
change Farmers' operations if it was successful in acquiring the
insurance company.
   ``Simply by virtue of the change in control, different
individuals would be in ultimate control of the two Washington
domestic companies,'' the order said. ``Those individuals are bound
to have different ideas about where the companies should be going
and how they should get there.''
   Marquardt said his decision was based partly on the greater
likelihood that Batus would drop non-smoker discounts on auto and
homeowner policies and medical malpractice coverage now offered by
Farmers.
   Batus Vice President Wilson Wyatt said, however, the company
does not plan to change Farmers' operations.
   ``Our sworn testimony was that we have no intention of
discontinuing either smoker or non-smoker discounts or hospital
professional liability policies,'' he said.
   Wyatt said Batus would be able to satisfy Marquardt's concerns.
   Marquardt noted that Batus has substantial holdings in the
tobacco industry _ it owns Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corp. _ and
that a takeover would cause ``some degree of tension'' between
sister subsidiaries that could result in canceling the special
rates.
   Should that happen, ``there would cease to be any competition in
those lines of coverage based on the smoker-nonsmoker distinction,
as no other companies offer such a discount in those lines,'' the
order said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880803-0266 </DOCNO>
