<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Auto Recalls,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>About 41,000 Volkswagens to be Recalled in Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yanase and Co., a Japanese dealer of West
German-made Volkswagen automobiles, said it will recall 41,122 of
the vehicles because of defective bulkheads.
   Also on Wednesday, Daihatsu Motor Co. said it will recall 8,928
of its passenger cars because of defective bolts for the fan belt.
   Yanase official Yutaka Nakazato said no accidents had occurred
because of the defect but that the company, after consulting with
the manufacturer Volkswagen AG, decided to recall the Golf model
cars exported to Japan between 1975 and 1981.
   Nakazato said the bulkhead was not strong enough to firmly hold
clutch wires attached to it and could cause trouble in working the
clutch.
   Meanwhile, a Daihatsu official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the company would recall its Rugger, Rugger Turbo,
Delta 1750 and Delta 1750 Low-Deck models produced between Sept. 1,
1987 and June 1 of this year.
   He said 7,917 of the vehicles to be recalled were exported,
including 2,013 to Britain, 1,257 to West Germany, 991 to Belgium,
926 to Australia and the rest to 76 other countries.
   The Daihatsu official said defective bolts might allow the fan
belt to work loose and cause the engine to overheat.
   He said the company will recall the cars according to the
regulations of each country.
</TEXT>
