<1ST_LINE>u f PM-DeereTalks 1stLd-Writethru   08-03 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deere Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deere Begins Contract Negotiations with UAW</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 new grafs to UPDATE with talks beginning, quote.
Picks up 4th graf pvs, ``The talks ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST MOLINE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deere & Co. and the United Auto Workers
sat down at the bargaining table today to begin negotiating a new
labor contract, 18 months after the end of a bitter 163-day strike.
   UAW President Owen Bieber and union secretary-treasurer Bill
Casstevens shook hands with Hans W. Becherer, Deere president, and
Michael S. Plunkett, a senior vice president, to raise the curtain
on negotiations over a contract to replace the current 20-month
agreement that expires at midnight, Sept. 30.
   The two sides made their initial presentation at the traditional
meeting site of a union hall and will move to a neutral site for
negotiations.
   ``I'm always excited and I'm always optimistic at the start of
talks,'' Bieber said. ``I've been reading analysts' reports that
say Deere has been making money and their stock is going up. It all
looks very encouraging, and they need to recognize the need to
share that with their employees.''
   The talks cover about 13,400 active employees, and 4,000
laid-off workers, at 11 cities in Illinois, Iowa, Minnesota,
Colorado and Georgia. Deere employs about 38,000 employees
worldwide.
   Over the next two months, the bargaining teams will discuss such
issues as restoration of wage cuts, pension increases, job
security, farming-out of work to outside contractors, and worker
retraining.
   The average Deere factory worker makes $15.47 per hour, or
$32,177 annually, and the company calculates its labor costs at
$26.90 per hour, including vacation, bonuses, holidays and other
fringe benefits.
   Before the start of negotiations, spokesmen for both sides
declined specific comment on the issues, saying they would do their
talking behind closed doors at the bargaining table.
   ``Deere & Co. is looking forward to the upcoming meetings with
the UAW. We expect to reach an agreement that satisfies the
requirements of Deere and its UAW-represented employees,'' said G.
Bart Bontems, director of industrial relations for the company.
   ``High priority goals in the bargaining with Deere & Co. will be
to strengthen the security of jobs and incomes of UAW members,''
Bieber said last week.
   Moline-based Deere leads the nation in farm tractor and
agricultural implement manufacturing and is a major competitor in
the industrial equipment market.
   But the company is recovering from a prolonged farm belt
recession and years of labor turmoil including a five-month strike
in 1986-87, the longest in the company's 151-year history.
   The 163-day work stoppage at 13 Deere plants in Illinois, Iowa,
Minneapolis, Georgia, Tennessee and Colorado ended Feb. 1, 1987,
when union workers accepted a wage freeze, a one-time payment of
$735 each and creation of a job protection plan.
   Deere's earnings collapsed and the company racked up $328
million in losses in two years. For the six-year period of 1982-87,
Deere's operating losses totaled $637 million.
   A program of cost cutting, layoffs and a turn-around in the
agricultural sector helped Deere return to the black and analysts
projected earnings of more than $200 million in the 1988 fiscal
year, which ends Oct. 30.
   But Deere's recovery may be stunted by the recent drought which
has slightly stalled sales of farm tractors. The company has
acknowledged isolated cancellations of farm equipment contracts but
stands by its sales projections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
