<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crop futures opened mixed today in cautious
trading on the Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for an
increasing chance of showers in the northern Corn Belt.
   Wheat and soybean futures prices gained modestly in early
trading while corn and oats were slightly lower.
   Analysts said that with the increasing likelihood of rain, grain
and soybean traders were unwilling to bet heavily on declining crop
yields and rising prices.
   Nevertheless, analysts said corn and soybean crop conditions
were worsening with each passing day of a scorching heat wave in
the Midwest.
   Temperatures above 90 degrees were expected to continue into the
weekend, and those forecasts ``really do indicate the crop is
deteriorating further, especially the soybean crop,'' said Walter
Spilka, a grain market analyst in New York with Smith Barney,
Harris Upham & Co.
   The wheat market got a boost from reports that China had
purchased 500,000 metric tons of subsidized U.S. wheat, he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 2{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.78 a bushel; corn was }
cent to 2 cents lower with September at $2.99{ a bushel; oats were
3{ cents to 5{ cents lower with September at $2.84 a bushel; and
soybeans were { cent to 7 cents higher with August at $8.36 a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .02 cent lower to .65 cent higher with August
at 65.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .78 cent
higher with August at 78.05 cents a pound; hogs were .50 cent lower
to .20 cent higher with August at 44.95 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .40 cent lower to .55 cent higher with August at 32.70
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
