<1ST_LINE>s f BC-FallApparel Adv07   08-03 0989</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fall Apparel, Adv 07,1026</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Aug. 7 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Apparel Retailers Dress Up for Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shoppers walking into the Limited store at
Crossgates Mall are being greeted by three mannequins, crisply
attired in tailored suits.
   Is Limited, more often associated with casual wear, going career?
   Not quite. This retailer _ like many other apparel stores _ is
taking on a different look this fall in hopes of reversing a
year-long sales slump.
   Apparel sales began to skid last August as retailers were beset
by two problems: Women rebelled against shorter skirts, and they
were turned off by styles that looked too casual, too bulky and too
much like those of past seasons.
   Fall displays suggest that part of the industry's peace offering
for the fall is to back off on the skirt issue.
   Several of the mannequins at Limited sport below-the-knee
skirts, while down in Manhattan, the windows of high-fashion stores
such as Bloomingdale's, Bergdorf Goodman and Saks Fifth Avenue
showcase a variety of lengths.
   Retailers surveyed customers and test-marketed new designs for
months before coming up with the more tailored and more feminine
clothes showing up in stores for fall.
   The new lines at Crossgates' apparel retailers show the results
of their efforts. The styles on Limited's suited manneent ``sale'' signs.
   Now, said Greenstein, stores must try to wean customers away
from markdowns, which take a heavy toll on profits. ``It will be
very difficult to change that,'' he said.
   Some markdowns are being taken at the start of the season just
to get traffic started, Loeb said.
   Limited is already using the strategy. A sign in the window of
its Crossgates Mall store offers $10 off on any $50 purchase of the
store's fall Outback Red Heritage line, while the $249 suits
featured at the entrance all are marked down $50.
   Wintzer doubted stores would mark down much of their merchandise.
   ``Women have still been paying up for what few items have been
hot,'' he said.
   Markdowns also may be less likely because the retailers, burned
by the large inventories they were stuck with last fall and spring,
have bought very conservatively for the new season. This means
women who don't shop early may find they can't get what they want,
Loeb said.
   ``Retailers are willing to forego reordering hot-selling items
and go to the next line,'' he said, and advised consumers, ``Unless
you rush in now and buy ... you'll find it will be gone.''
   Analysts watch fashions because their success has a direct
effect on retailers' profits _ and most stores saw their earnings
slump during the past year.
   Now, the analysts warn that because last year's results were so
bad, a mediocre performance may look better than it really is.
Wintzer said a retailer would have to chalk up five or six months
of double-digit sales growth for their second half to be considered
good.
   Storeowners likely will tout any sales increase, but ``if it's
just a modest improvement, it's artificial,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday Aug. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
