<1ST_LINE>r f BC-AluminumTalks     08-03 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Aluminum Talks,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Early Aluminum Contract Talks Set</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two major unions will be looking for a share
of the aluminum industry's profits next week when they open early
negotiations to replace contracts that expire 10 months from now.
   The current two-year pacts with the United Steelworkers of
America and the Aluminum, Brick and Glass Workers International
Union lowered benefits by 95 cents per hour for their members at
Aluminum Company of America and Reynolds Metals Co.
   ``When we negotiated the current contracts in 1986, our members
made sacrifices to help the companies over hard time,'' said George
Becker, internatinal vice president of the USW. ``Now that these
companies are profitable again, our members deserve to share in
those gains and recover the sacrifices they made.''
   Becker, who chairs the union's aluminum industry conference, was
quoted in the USW publication ``Steelabor.''
   Pittsburgh-based Alcoa, the nation's largest aluminum producer,
reported profits of $200.1 million, or $2.25 per share, on sales of
$7.77 billion for all of 1987 and profits of $416.3 million, or
$4.71 per share, on sales of $4.59 billion in the first six months
of this year.
   Reynolds of Richmond, Va., reported 1987 net earnings of $219.5
million, or $4.33 per share, on sales of $4.32 billion and net
earnings of $204.9 million, or $3.84 per share, on revenue of $2.65
billion in the 1988 first half.
   The contract talks are scheduled to begin Aug. 8 in Cincinnati.
The two unions will conduct concurrent but separate negotiations.
Their contracts expire May 31, 1989.
   The USW said it represents more than 6,000 Alcoa workers at nine
locations in the United States and approximately 4,000 Reynolds
workers at 21 locations in the United States and Canada.
   The ABGWU represents between 6,000 and 7,000 Alcoa workers and
an estimated 4,700 Reynolds workers.
</TEXT>
