<1ST_LINE>r f BC-GE-JapanPlastics     08-03 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-GE-Japan Plastics,0151</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GE To Form Plastics Venture With Japanese</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A unit of General Electric Co. will form a
Japanese-based joint venture in plastics with two Japanese
partners, Mitsui Petrochemical Industries Ltd. and Nagase and Co.
Ltd., the companies said Wednesday.
   The effort is described as a restructuring move to improve
existing ties between the three partners.
   The new entity will be called GE Plastics Japan Ltd. and will
focus on the manufacture of polycarbonate resin through the
construction of a Japanese plant with a productive capacity of
40,000 tons per year.
   GE Plastics (U.S.A.) will hold a 51 percent stake in the
venture, with Mitsui and Nagase accounting for 24.5 percent each.
Full operations are expected to start in early 1991.
   Polycarbonate resin is used to make car vehicle components,
compact disks, safety equipment and a host of other products.
