<HEAD>Stocks Uo</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with closing figures, comment.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed broadly higher Wednesday on
the London Stock Exchange, as dealers reported the reemergence of
some long-awaited institutional buying interest in the leading
British stocks.
   Trading volume, which has been concentrated in a few speculative
stocks in recent sessions, was more broadly based, dealers said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index rose 9.6
points, or 0.5 percent, to close at 1,865.1 after rising as much as
10.9 points in the early afternoon.
   Volume was 416.1 million shares, up from 376.5 million shares a
day earlier.
   Dealers said the market was lifted by some good institutional
buying interest in the major 100-share index stocks.
   ``It's the first time for days that we've seen a bit of trading
volume,'' one dealer said. ``Institutions are bidding for the big
international stocks.''
   But the other major markets again failed to provide direction to
London stocks. On the New York Stock Exchange, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 5.69 points at 2,136.91 soon after the
London market closed. In Tokyo, the Nikkei index fell 17.88 to
28,348.45 earlier Wednesday.
   In London, the Financial Times 30-share index rose 10.6 points
to 1,502.0. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 5.78 points to
1,064.28.
</TEXT>
