<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WritersStrike 2ndLd-Writethru   08-03 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike, 2nd Ld-Writethru,f0059,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with guild's chief bargainer
expected to recommend approval of contract; PICKS UP 7th graf pvs,
`The 21-member ... Also moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top negotiator for the striking film and
TV scriptwriters was expected to recommend approval of the
producers' latest offer, proposed today after all-night talks, a
union bargainer said.
   Writers Guild of America chief negotiator Brian Walton was to
present the contract to the union's full negotiating committee. A
favorable vote could effectively end the strike that has paralyzed
the entertainment industry for 22 weeks.
   ``It's my expectation that he is going to recommend that we go
with this,'' said Arthur Sellers, a member of the WGA negotiating
committee.
   There was no immediate word on the contents of the proposed
contract.
   Formal approval would require a vote by the full membership of
the union. Membership meetings, which require a 48-hour advance
notification, could be held as early as Friday with the vote tally
announced the following day.
   A highly placed guild source, speaking on condition of
anonymity, confirmed that Walton was expected to recommend approval.
   The committee planned to meet with Alliance of Motion Picture
and Television Producers representatives an hour later, and a WGA
board meeting was scheduled for later today at guild headquarters
in West Hollywood.
   The 9,000 film and TV scriptwriters went on strike March 7 over
payments for reruns and syndication of TV shows.
   The strike cut short last year's TV season and suspended
production of countless series and movies. It has forced the
networks to scramble to fill their fall lineups with specials,
movies and remakes of old series.
   Asked if a settlement was possible as he left the all-night
bargaining session about 6:30 a.m., Walton said: ``It's possible.
It's always been possible.''
   ``I'm not unhappy with what happened tonight. We'll just see
what happens when we come back,'' Walton added.
   Alliance spokesman Herb Steinberg and WGA President George Kirgo
did not immediately return calls seeking comment.
   The two sides adjourned this morning after holding informal
talks for more than 12 hours at alliance headquarters in Sherman
Oaks.
   The 21-member dissident Writers Coalition, which has threatened
to break from the guild to return to work, announced it will honor
the walkout but will again consider resigning if the strike
continues past this week, spokesman Lionel Chetwynd said.
   Barry Diller, head of 20th Century Fox, said his studio will pay
any union fines incurred by striking scriptwriters who cross picket
lines.
   Guild fines against strike-breaking writers are set at 110
percent of all compensation received for unauthorized strike work,
and violators are subject to lifetime expulsion from the guild, Ms.
Rhoden said.
</TEXT>
