<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Eastern-LaborPlan     08-03 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern-Labor Plan,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Flight Attendants Offer Plan to Save Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flight attendants at Eastern Airlines fighting to
save more than 1,000 jobs on Wednesday proposed a two-tiered,
work-reduction scheme they say would save Eastern $15 million
annually and let them stay on the carrier's payroll.
   Mary Jane Barry, president of the Transport Workers Union's
Miami branch, said a survey of 1,000 Eastern flight attendants
showed that senior attendants were willing to share weekly work
schedules, cutting their working time _ and pay _ in half.
   Hundreds of others, Ms. Barry said, would accept long-term
leaves from active service while remaining employees of the
financially troubled airline, which is a subsidiary of giant Texas
Air Corp.
   ``The (union) was excited about the plan we had developed,'' she
said, adding: ``Our plan could enable (Eastern) to avoid laying off
one single flight attendant.''
   Ms. Barry said similar programs have operated successfully at
other airlines _ including Pan Am, American, Republic and Ozark _
since the early 1980s.
   The Transport Workers' proposal came 10 days after Eastern
President Phil Bakes announced that the airline would eliminate
4,000 jobs and cut service to 14 cities in a move to bring the
carrier back into the black.
   The labor plan also came a week after Eastern management
rejected a similar proposal from the flight attendants for massive
long-leave agreements.
   ``Mr. Bakes would rather lay off the 1,000 flight attendants
than save millions at Eastern,'' Ms. Barry told a news conference.
   Eastern had a net operating loss of $182 million last year, and
the job cuts, if carried out, would bring the airline's total staff
to 29,521, down sharply from the 43,308 people employed by the
carrier in September 1986.
   Ms. Barry said the union filed a suit Tuesday seeking a
temporary restraining order to block Eastern's layoff proposal.
   On July 28, the Machinists union, which represents about 12,000
Eastern employees, filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in
Washington seeking a preliminary injunction or a temporary
restraining order against the planned layoffs.
   Charles Bryan, president of the Machinists' local in Miami, said
management's proposed cutbacks ``will significantly increase
(Eastern's) recurring losses and lead to the ultimate destruction
of the carrier.''
   Bryan charged that Eastern was in violation of the Railway Labor
Act with the layoff plan, asserting that the program amounted to
``an act of self-help'' for Texas Air.
   The Eastern cutbacks, he argued, would benefit Continental
Airlines, another Texas Air subsidiary.
   According to Bakes, the cutbacks were unavoidable because of
Eastern's losses.
   ``In essence, '' he said, ``Eastern is returning to its basic
roots in an attempt to regain strength in the marketplace.''
   Under the management proposal, Eastern would concentrate on its
service to Boston, New York, Washington, Atlanta and Miami,
dropping Kansas City, Mo., as its western hub.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880803-0283 </DOCNO>
