<1ST_LINE>u f AM-IBMWorkstation 1stLd-Writethru   08-03 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IBM Workstation, 1st Ld-Writethru,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM Seeks No. 1 Position In Workstations By 1991</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf, Ms. Dezan's ..., to include
description of workstations.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. committed
itself Wednesday to achieving market leadership in workstations,
the speedier siblings of personal computers that make up one of the
fastest-growing parts of the computer business.
   ``Our strategy hasn't been competitive. Today it is. Our
objective is to be the leader in the industry for workstations by
1991,'' IBM spokeswoman Linda Dezan said.
   Ms. Dezan's comments, based on the official IBM position, were
an expansion of remarks by IBM executive Arthur G. Goldberg that
were quoted in Wednesday's editions of the Wall Street Journal.
   Workstations are expensive desktop computers that are typically
used for work that requires intensive manipulation of numbers or
sophisticated graphics, such as science, engineering, design and
financial modeling.
   IBM's RT workstation was widely faulted for being underpowered
and lacking in software when it was introduced in early 1986, and
sales lagged badly. But Ms. Dezan said IBM has steadily added
software while doubling the performance of the RT every 12 to 18
months.
   IBM had 3.9 percent of the worldwide market for workstations
used for science and engineering last year, trailing Sun
Microsystems Inc.'s 29 percent share, Apollo Computer Inc.'s 21
percent, Digital Equipment Corp.'s 20 percent and Hewlett-Packard
Co.'s 12 percent, according to International Data Corp.
   Those numbers understate the RT's popularity because they focus
only on machines used for science and engineering. About half the
RTs sold are used for general corporate business.
   Goldberg said a version of the RT that will be available
relatively soon will be at least twice as fast as current models
for general-purpose computing and many times as fast for
engineering and design work.
   IBM has devoted a huge effort to improving the RT because
workstations are a booming segment of the computer industry, with
industrywide sales growing 30 percent a year.
   June was the best month yet for RT sales because of improvements
already made in the product, IBM says. The RT will get another
boost from the $3.6 billion contract IBM recently won from the
Federal Aviation Administration for an air-traffic-control system.
That system will be largely based on the RT and will include 12,000
to 15,000 RTs.
   ``We have been experiencing much more success with the RT than
we've generally been given credit for,'' Ms. Dezan said.
   IBM says it is spending as much money on development of RT
hardware as on hardware for its huge personal computer business. In
addition, it is increasing the number of marketing people for the
RT ten-fold, to at least 300.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880803-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 1700EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BizWeekProbe 1stLd-Writethru   08-03 0737</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biz Week Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru,0757</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two More Fired, Two Quit; FBI Investigating Scandal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2 grafs for 8th graf pvs, Donnelley officials ...
against them., to include identity of Donnelley worker fired
earlier.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four more people lost their jobs Wednesday
because of suspected insider trading on swiped tips from
unpublished copies of Business Week, and a U.S. attorney announced
the first criminal probe into the scandal. R.R. Donnelley & Sons
Co., one of the companies that prints the business weekly, said it
fired two workers and another quit. The investment firm Advest Inc.
said a broker suspended because of Business Week-linked trading
resigned.
   The developments raised to seven the list of brokers and
printers forced out of their jobs because of the scandal, in which
an undetermined number of people traded stocks based on stolen tips
from the business magazine's ``Inside Wall Street'' stock-touting
column prior to publication.
   Buying and selling stocks based on information unavailable to
everyone is commonly referred to as insider trading and is
considered fraud under federal securities laws.
   Donnelley said it fired a previously suspended employee at its
plant in Torrance, Calif., and another worker there resigned. The
company also said it fired a second worker at a printing plant in
Old Saybrook, Conn., where a production employee was dismissed
earlier this week.
   ``This is not the way we do business,'' John R. Walter,
Donnelley president, said in a statement from the company's
headquarters in Chicago.
   ``We have a long, proud tradition of protecting our customers'
materials,'' he said. ``Although a few employees have violated our
rules, we continue to have confidence in our more than 23,000
Donnelley employees. We are continuing our investigate and we will
deal severely with any individuals involved.''
   Donnelley officials declined to name the employees affected in
the latest action, but confirmed the identity of the Old Saybrook
worker fired earlier as William Rady, who was said to live in the
New London area. Directory assistance said there was no residential
telephone listing under that name.
   The printing company has said it is considering unspecified
legal action against the disciplined workers.
   Evidence uncovered so far in the scandal suggests some printers
distributed or peddled unpublished copies of Business Week to
brokers, who bought stocks recommended by ``Inside Wall Street''
and sold them later at a profit, after publication had attracted
more buyers and raised the price of the stocks.
   Stanley Twardy Jr., the U.S. attorney in Hartford, Conn., said
he had asked the FBI to investigate ``any possible wrongdoing in
Connecticut in connection with this matter.'' He declined to
elaborate on the nature or scope of the probe, the first criminal
inquiry since the scandal surfaced late last month.
   Last week Merrill Lynch & Co. fired a broker from its New
London, Conn., office, near Donnelley's Old Saybrook plant, and
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. fired a broker from its Anaheim,
Calif., branch, near the Torrance plant. Merrill Lynch also is
investigating a second broker.
   Advest spokeswoman Martha Payne said Wednesday that broker
Thomas Griffin, who had worked at the firm's New London office and
was suspended last week, had resigned.
   She would not disclose whether Griffin admitted involvement in
the scandal but said he previously had been employed at the
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. office in Old Saybrook.
   Griffin was not in the New London office Wednesday and he did
not return messages left on his home telephone answering machine.
Griffin's attorney, S.W. Bromson, was said to be out of the office
and did not return messages.
   Ms. Payne said no other Advest brokers were under scrutiny but
she said the firm was continuing to investigate the suspicious
trading.
   At least nine investment firms have undertaken internal
inquiries into trading possibly connected to the purloined tips and
are known to be cooperating with a Securities and Exchange
Commission probe of the scandal.
   In addition, there have been unconfirmed reports that up to two
dozen investment firms are involved.
   The scandal surfaced when Business Week, the nation's leading
business weekly with a circulation of nearly 1 million, disclosed
July 21 that it had long suspected prepublication misuse of
``Inside Wall Street'' tips.
   The magazine has been criticized for failing to tell the SEC or
the major stock exchanges about the suspicions earlier. Business
Week officials have said they were seeking definitive evidence
before alerting regulatory authorities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880803-0290 </DOCNO>
