<2ND_LINE>BC-Auto Sales,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford, Chrysler Report Car Sales Increases in Late July</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Late July car sales rose at Ford Motor Co. and
Chrysler Corp. but slipped at General Motors Corp., the automakers
reported Wednesday.
   Ford sold 70,857 cars in nine selling days from July 21-31,
compared with 72,443 in 10 selling days in the comparable 1987
period, for a daily sales increase of 8.7 percent.
   Chrysler sold 32,498 cars in the same period, up from 30,865 a
year earlier, amounting to a 17 percent jump in daily sales.
   GM car sales of 114,789 compared with 130,696 sold in the
year-earlier period, a 2.4 percent slide in daily sales.
   But GM's light truck sales leaped 14.3 percent on a daily basis,
to 57,993 from 56,353 a year earlier, and GM said its daily sales
overall were up 1.9 percent.
   Ford sold 44,994 light trucks, up 1.4 percent on a daily basis,
and Chrysler sold 32,377 for a 10.5 percent increase in daily sales.
   Several foreign carmakers reported U.S. sales for the month of
July.
   Among Japanese car makers, Toyota Motor Corp. reported selling
6,434 of its U.S.-made cars in July, up from 3,289 in July 1987,
and 59,602 of its imported cars, up from 53,345 a year earlier.
   Honda Motor Co. sold 29,125 U.S.-made cars in July, up from
26,287 a year earlier, but its sales of imports slid to 35,042 from
37,009.
   Mazda Motor Corp. sold 19,078 imported cars, down from 20,036
last July, but added 3,023 U.S. made cars. Mazda had no U.S.-made
cars last July; its Flat Rock, Mich., plant opened in September.
   Among European companies, Volkswagen sales fell to 11,831 for
the month from 20,961 in July 1987.
   Mercedes-Benz sold 6,699 of its luxury German imports, down from
7,008 the previous July.
</TEXT>
