<1ST_LINE>u f AM-EconomyRdp     08-03 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy Rdp,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Confidence Dips; Markets Quiet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought has spread pessimism through parts of the country and
dragged down a national index of consumers' confidence, a
business-supported research group said Wednesday.
   In other drought-related news, grain and soybean futures prices
finished mixed on the Chicago Board of Trade as predictions of rain
offset the impact of the crop-wilting heat hovering over the Farm
Belt.
   The Worldwatch Institute, a private research organization, said
drought in the United States, Canada and China will produce the
steepest one-year drop in world grain stocks ever recorded.
   On Wall Street Wednesday, stock prices edged upward and the Dow
Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 2.85 to 2,134.07.
   Bonds fell in light trading, which brokers called a reaction to
the market's sharp rise earlier this week and investor apprehension
about an impending government report on unemployment.
   The dollar drifted fractionally lower against most major
currencies after giving a mixed performance overseas. Gold prices
rose.
   In other economic news, car sales rose in late July at Ford
Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. but fell at General Motors Corp. in
comparison with a year earlier.
   The Conference Board's Consumer Confidence Index fell in July to
113 from a revised 115.7 in June and a peak of 120.2 in May.
Despite the decline, the index remained well above its recent low
of 100.8 in November, the month after the stock market crash.
   ``Virtually all of the loss in consumer confidence during the
last two months can be attributed to the drought,'' Fabian Linden,
executive director of the board's Consumer Research Center, said in
a prepared statement.
   The survey revealed stark regional differences in consumers'
attitudes.
   In New England, where the economy is strong and the weather has
been less dry, the confidence index rose in July to 154.2 from
149.8.
   By contrast, in the drought-plagued West North Central states of
Minnesota, Iowa, Missouri, North Dakota, South Dakota, Nebraska and
Kansas, the confidence index plunged to 69.7 from 91.4.
</TEXT>
