<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AutoWarranties Bjt   08-03 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Warranties, Bjt,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Extends Warranty Coverage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. will make a new
attack in the warranty wars among automakers with three-year,
50,000-mile coverage on most of its 1989 cars and light trucks, GM
President Robert C. Stempel said Wednesday.
   The change extends GM's current 12-month, 12,000-mile ``bumper
to bumper'' warranty covering virtually all repairs, but drops its
added six-year, 60,000-mile coverage on engines and transmissions,
Stempel said.
   Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. officials did not immediately
say whether they would follow suit.
   Stempel told a University of Michigan Management Briefing
Seminars session the new warranties will cover virtually all
repairs except accident damage, including repairs of air
conditioning, steering and suspension systems and electronics and
power options.
   ``Every part is covered, from front to back, from road to
roof,'' he said.
   In the last round of warranty upgrades, GM had announced in
January it was extending coverage on engines and transmissions to
six years or 60,000 miles.
   Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. have 12-month or 12,000-mile
basic warranties similar to GM's. Both quickly matched GM's longer
engine and transmission warranties.
   But Stempel said two thirds of those polled in GM customer
surveys favored the three-year, 50,000-mile coverage on the entire
vehicle over the current plan.
   GM has offered complete vehicle coverage for three years or
80,000 kilometers (49,600 miles) on vehicles sold in Canada since
February and Canadian customers said they preferred that coverage,
Stempel said.
   Ford will study the GM move, spokesman Charles L. Snearly said.
``It is always our intention to keep Ford and Lincoln-Mercury
dealers competitive.''
   For now, Snearly said, ``We believe our present warranty is a
good one and serves the customer well. Our six-year, 60,000-mile
power train warranty is comparable to others in the industry.''
   Chrysler officials had no immediate comment on the GM move or
whether Chrysler would follow suit, spokesman Thomas F. Houston
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
