<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   08-03 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0465</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought has spread pessimism through parts of the country and
dragged down a national index of consumer confidence, a
business-supported research group has reported.
   In other drought-related news Wednesday, grain and soybean
futures prices finished mixed on the Chicago Board of Trade as
predictions of rain offset the impact of the crop-wilting heat
hovering over the Farm Belt.
   Also, the Worldwatch Institute, a private research organization,
said drought in the United States, Canada and China will produce
the steepest one-year drop in world grain stocks ever recorded in
1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC's price-monitoring committee
has expressed concern over a ``serious deterioration in prices''
due partly to overproducing members but failed to schedule
emergency talks to address the problem.
   Prices fell sharply in oil futures trading in response to the
news Wednesday.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for September
delivery of West Texas Intermediate crude oil, fell 35 cents a
barrel to close at $15.26.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Late July car sales rose at Ford Motor Co. and
Chrysler Corp. but slipped at General Motors Corp., the automakers
have reported.
   Ford said Wednesday its daily sales improved 8.7 percent.
Chrysler reported a 17 percent jump in daily sales, while GM said
sales declined 2.4 percent.
   GM also said it would make a new attack in the warranty wars
among automakers with three-year, 50,000-mile coverage on most of
its 1989 cars and light trucks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's 13 largest airlines in June had
their best record of on-time flights since the government began
issuing reports on their performance last fall, the Department of
Transportation said.
   In its monthly report Wednesday, the department said 84.3
percent of the airlines' flights that were tallied operated on
schedule.
   The improvement came even as the airlines began their annual
summertime crunch period.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department has announced it will
borrow $29 billion to replenish government coffers next week, but
for the first time in six years will not issue 30-year bonds at its
quarterly auctions.
   No 30-year bonds will be issued because the government has used
up practically all of its congressional authority to do so, the
Treasury said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices edged upward Wednesday, and the Dow Jones average
of 30 industrial stocks rose 2.85 to 2,134.07.
   Bonds fell in light trading, which brokers called a reaction to
the market's sharp rise earlier this week and investor apprehension
about an impending government report on unemployment.
   The dollar drifted fractionally lower, gold prices rose and crop
futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
