<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets     08-03 0136</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower; Stocks Up In Early Tokyo Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened slightly lower Thursday in
Tokyo, while stock prices gained moderately on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The dollar opened at 132.75 yen, down from Wednesday's close of
132.85 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 92.33
points to 28,440.78 in the first 15 minutes of trading.
   Securities dealers attributed the stock market's gain to the
stability of the dollar, but also said rumors of tightened margin
trading requirements were sidelining investors.
   ``If the exchange tightens control on margin trade, prices of
large-capital shares, which have been leading the market in recent
days, are bound to decline,'' said a dealer at a major securities
firm in Tokyo. ``But other than the rumors, the market situation
looks fine.''
</TEXT>
