<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WritersStrike 2ndLd-Writethru f0323 08-03 0967</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike, 2nd Ld - Writethru, f0323,0992</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scriptwriters, Producers Announce Tentative Agreement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 5th graf pvs, `Members of...', with
reaction from ABC president, actress Betty White, one scriptwriter.
Picks up 6th graf pvs, `The settlement...'. Guild committee still
planning telephone-conference call vote this evening, but timing of
further announcements uncertain.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking screenwriters reached tentative
agreement with motion picture and television producers Wednesday,
effectively ending a 150-day walkout that paralyzed Hollywood and
left the fall TV schedule in shambles.
   ``It was time to bring it to a conclusion and the deal was
there,'' Brian Walton, chief guild negotiator, said at a joint news
conference.
   ``We are very pleased to have reached a tentative agreement,''
said Nicholas Counter III, chief negotiator for the Alliance of
Motion Picture and Television Producers. Asked who won, Counter
said: ``No one wins a strike.''
   Walton said the agreement reflected ``some serious bargaining.''
   Members of the Writers Guild of America were expected to ratify
the contract at a membership meeting later this week, and
scriptwriters may return to work as early as Monday.
   ``Thank God! Isn't that wonderful news? We're all champing at
the bit to go back to work,'' said actress Betty White, the
Emmy-winning star of NBC-TV's ``The Golden Girls,'' after she heard
about the agreement.
   Writer I.C. Rapoport, who wrote the CBS television movie ``Cook
and Peary: Race To The Pole,'' said he was ``relieved that the
strike is over _ and so is my family. I can start earning some
money again.''
   ABC Entertainment President Brandon Stoddard said in a statement
that settlement of the strike this week would leave his network
``able to premiere most of our fall schedule either before, after
or combined with (the miniseries) `War and Remembrance' in
November.'' Premiere dates would be announced soon, he said.
   The settlement announcement ends what had become one of the
longest and more painful strikes in modern Hollywood history,
surpassed only by the WGA's 1960 walkout, which lasted 23 weeks.
The current walkout began March 7, 21{ weeks ago.
   Federal mediator Floyd Wood said no details of the contract
would be released until the WGA's board of directors on the West
Coast and East Coast are informed of the agreement during an
evening telephone conference call.
   The joint boards will then vote via telephone and results will
be revealed later during a news conference at guild headquarters in
West Hollywood.
   ``It was a fair deal _ negotiated, not dictated _ and it was
OK,'' said a member of the negotiating committee who asked not to
be identified.
   News of the settlement came after two days of intense efforts by
a variety of intermediaries to bring an end to the 22-week-long
walkout.
   Final contract details were ironed out at an 12-hour meeting
between Walton and Counter that ended early Wednesday.
   The pair, who had repeatedly sniped at each other throughout the
walkout, shook hands after the announcement.
   As recently as last weekend, it looked as though the two sides
were at an impasse, with a producers spokesman saying talks were
``hopelessly deadlocked.''
   Despite the strike settlement, the fall television season cannot
proceed as planned. Its start will be delayed, perhaps until
November. The financial costs to the networks could range into tens
of millions of dollars.
   The WGA has 9,000 members, most living and working in Southern
California. The alliance has 217 member companies, responsible for
85 percent of network primetime television and 90 percent of
feature film production and distribution.
   The contract proposal reflects improvements in the foreign
residual structure and gains in the area of creative rights, the
main issues dogging negotiations, said the union negotiator.
   Alliance spokesman Herb Steinberg credited the break in the
stalemated talks to the two federal mediators, Wood and Leonard
Farrell. The two ``had a considerable role in keeping the dialogue
open,'' he said.
   The settlement brings to an end a period of acrimony that has
few recent equals. Lawsuits were filed by both parties and
